er delivers lots of holiday goodies from Jupiter's north pole |work=Geekwire |first=Alan |last=Boyle |date=December 26, 2018 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 12, 2019, 17:36:13\n|Perijove 18\n|-\n|April 6, 2019, 13:30:13\n|Perijove 19\n|-\n|May 29, 2019\n|Perijove 20\n|-\n|July 21, 2019\n|Perijove 21<ref name=JunoUpdate>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2016/11030800-juno-update.html |title=Juno update: 53.5-day orbits for the foreseeable future, more Marble Movie |publisher=[[Planetary Society]] |last=Lakdawalla |first=Emily |author-link=Emily Lakdawalla |date=November 3, 2016 |accessdate=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|September 12, 2019\n|Perijove 22\n|-\n|November 3, 2019\n|Perijove 23\n|-\n|December 26, 2019\n|Perijove 24\n|-\n|February 17, 2020\n|Perijove 25\n|-\n|April 10, 2020\n|Perijove 26\n|-\n|June 2, 2020\n|Perijove 27\n|-\n|July 25, 2020\n|Perijove 28\n|-\n|September 16, 2020\n|Perijove 29\n|-\n|November 8, 2020\n|Perijove 30\n|-\n|December 30, 2020\n|Perijove 31\n|-\n|February 21, 2021\n|Perijove 32\n|-\n|April 15, 2021\n|Perijove 33\n|-\n|June 7, 2021\n|Perijove 34<ref name=\"pds.juno\" />\n|-\n|July 30, 2021\n|Perijove 35: End of mission<ref name=\"pds.juno\" /><ref name=\"End of mission\">{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/40830-nasa-extends-juno-jupiter-mission-2021.html/ |title=NASA Extends Juno Jupiter Mission Until July 2021 |work=Space.com |first=Mike |last=Wall |date=June 8, 2018 |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Gallery of Jupiter images ==\n<center><gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"140\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:PIA21032 Jupiter Down Under.jpg|Image from about {{convert|94500|km|mi|abbr=on}} of Jupiter's southern polar region (August 27, 2016)\nFile:PIA21034 Arrival and Departure at Jupiter.jpg|Jupiter growing and shrinking in apparent size before and after the spacecraft made its closest approach (August 27, 2016)\nFile:PIA21033 Juno's View of Jupiter's Southern Lights.jpg|Infrared view of the southern aurora of Jupiter (August 27, 2016)\nFile:PIA21641-Jupiter-SouthernStorms-JunoCam-20170525.jpg|Southern storms of Jupiter\nFile:When Jovian Light and Dark Collide.png|Area of Jupiter where multiple atmospheric conditions appear to collide (March 27, 2017)\nFile:Jupiter\u2019s Clouds of Many Colors.png|Retreating from Jupiter, about {{convert|46900|km|mi|abbr=on}} above the cloud tops (May 19, 2017)\nFile:Great red spot juno 20170712.jpg|Closeup of the [[Great Red Spot]] taken from about {{convert|5000|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} above it (July 11, 2017)\nFile:Jupiter A New Point of View.png|Image taken from {{convert|16535|km|mi|abbr=on}} above the atmosphere at a latitude of -36.9 degrees (July 10, 2017)\nFile:Io by JunoCam, processed by Roman Tkachenko.png|Low resolution view of [[Io (moon)|Io]] captured by JunoCam (September 2017)\nFile:189401-JupiterMoon-Io-PlumeNearTerminator-Juno-20181221.jpg|Plume near Io's [[Terminator (solar)|terminator]] (December 21, 2018)<ref name=\"EA-20181231\">{{cite news |url=https://www.swri.org/press-release/light-from-volcanoes-io-juno-jupiter-moon |title=Juno mission captures images of volcanic plumes on Jupiter's moon Io |publisher=[[Southwest Research Institute]] |date=December 31, 2018 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\nFile:PIA22946-Jupiter-RedSpot-JunoSpacecraft-20190212.jpg|<div align=\"center\">Jupiter viewed by Juno<br />(February 12, 2019)</div>\n</gallery></center>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{div col|colwidth=50em}}\n* [[Atmosphere of Jupiter]]\n* [[Comet Shoemaker\u2013Levy 9]]\n* ''[[Europa Clipper]]''\n* [[Exploration of Jupiter]]\n* [[Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer]]\n* [[List of missions to the outer planets]]\n* [[Moons of Jupiter]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Juno (spacecraft)|''Juno''}}\n{{wikinews|NASA's Juno spacecraft enters Jupiter orbit}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.nasa.gov/juno/}}\n* [ht