ndoran/albums/72157704984828914 17], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157706805004725 18], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157708854751916 20] [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157709899101647 21], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157711668623647 23], [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157712578176341 24] and [https://www.flickr.com/photos/seandoran/albums/72157713247493493 25] for more)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/kevinmgill/albums/72157672426118932 Juno image album] by Kevin M. Gill\n\n{{Juno spacecraft}}\n{{Planetary Missions Program Office|New Frontiers=y}}\n{{Jupiter spacecraft}}\n{{Jupiter}}\n{{Satellite and spacecraft instruments}}\n{{NASA space program}}\n{{Jet Propulsion Laboratory}}\n{{Solar System probes}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2011}}\n{{2016 in space}}\n{{Portal bar|Solar System|Spaceflight}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Juno (Spacecraft)}}\n[[Category:Juno (spacecraft)| ]]\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:New Frontiers program]]\n[[Category:Lockheed Martin satellites and probes]]\n[[Category:Missions to Jupiter]]\n[[Category:Orbiters (space probe)]]\n[[Category:Space probes launched in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Atlas rockets]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Marsbound2024", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScientific instruments:minor fix of the updated reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juno_(spacecraft)"}
{"title_page": "Eric Weinstein", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{distinguish|Eric W. Weisstein}}\n{{short description|American venture capital director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = Eric Ross Weinstein\n| name               = \n| image              = Eric Weinstein in January 2019.png\n| caption            = Weinstein in 2019\n| birth_date         =\n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Managing director of Thiel Capital\n| spouse             = Pia Malaney<ref>{{cite web |last1=McClurg |first1=Lesley |title=Let's Talk About Death Over Dinner |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2015/05/07/405003161/lets-talk-about-death-over-dinner |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = American\n| workplaces         = \n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] (PhD)\n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| doctoral_students  = \n| notable_students   = \n| known_for          = \n| influences         = \n| influenced         = \n| relatives          = [[Bret Weinstein]] (brother)\n| awards             = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Eric Ross Weinstein''' is the managing director of Thiel Capital, [[Peter Thiel]]'s personal investment firm, since 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Illing |first=Sean |date=August 20, 2017 |title=Why capitalism can't survive without socialism |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/7/25/15998002/capitalism-socialism-peter-thiel-wall-street-eric-weinstein |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=July 2, 2018}}</ref> He and his brother [[Bret Weinstein]] coined the term [[Intellectual Dark Web]] to refer to an informal group of pundits.<ref>{{cite web |last1=French |first1=David A. |author-link1=David A. French |title=Critics Miss the Point of the 'Intellectual Dark Web' |url= https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/05/intellectual-dark-web-meaning-audience/ |work=[[National Review]] |access-date=June 25, 2019 |date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sommer |first1=Will |title=Intellectual Dark Web Frays After Jordan Peterson Tweets Critically About Brett Kavanaugh |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/intellectual-dark-web-frays-after-jordan-peterson-tweets-critically-about-brett-kavanaugh |publisher=Daily Beast |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWeinstein received his PhD in mathematical physics from the Mathematics Department at [[Harvard University]] in 1992.<ref name=\"mathgenealogy\">{{MathGenealogy|86697}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bVFTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47 |page=47 |journal=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] |title=Raoul Bott: Collected Papers, Volume 5 |series=Contemporary Mathematicians |editor-last=Tu |editor-first=Loring W. |publisher=[[Birkh\u00e4user]] |year=2018 |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math.harvard.edu/graduate/dissertations/|title=PhD Dissertations Archival Listing|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard Mathematics Department|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In his dissertation, titled \"''Extension of Self-Dual Yang-Mills Equations across the Eighth Dimension''\" Weinstein showed that the [[self-dual Yang\u2013Mills equations]] were not really peculiar to dimension four and admitted generalizations to higher dimensions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beaulieu|first1=Laurent|last2=Kanno|first2=Hiroaki|last3=Singer|first3=I. M.|year=1998|title=Special Quantum Field Theories in Eight And Other Dimensions|journal=Communications in Mathematical Physics|volume=194|issue=1|pages=149\u2013175|arxiv=hep-th/9704167|bibcode=1998CMaPh.194..149B|doi=10.1007/s002200050353|issn=0010-3616}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://inspirehep.net/record/345600?ln=en|title=Extension of Self-Dual Yang-Mills Equations Across the 8th Dimension|website=The High Energy Physics Information System|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Physics===\nIn May 2013, Weinstein gave a colloquium talk, ''Geometric Unity,'' promoted by [[Marcus du Sautoy]] as a potential unified theory of physics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/may/23/eric-weinstein-answer-physics-problems|title=Eric Weinstein may have found the answer to physics' biggest problems|last=du Sautoy|first=Marcus|date=May 23, 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 31, 2013|author-link=Marcus du Sautoy}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z7rd04KzLcg&t=35m10s ''Geometric Unity''], Eric Weinstein lecture at Oxford University (May 23, 2013) with \"Supplementary Explainer\" (Apr 1, 2020), posted to YouTube on Apr 2, 2020</ref> His unpublished theory includes an \"observerse,\" a 14-dimensional space, and predictions for undiscovered particles which he stated could account for [[dark matter]]. Joseph Conlon of the [[University of Oxford]] stated that some of these particles, if they existed, would already have been detected in existing accelerators such as the [[Large Hadron Collider]].<ref name=\"Pontzen2013\" />\n\nFew physicists attended and no preprint, paper, or equations were published.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pontzen|first=Andrew|date=March 2013|title=End of darkness: the stuff that really rules the cosmos|journal=New Scientist|volume=217|issue=2909|pages=32\u201335|doi=10.1016/s0262-4079(13)60757-5|issn=0262-4079}}</ref> Weinstein's ideas were not widely debated. The few that did engage expressed skepticism.<ref name=\"Pontzen2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23595-weinsteins-theory-of-everything-is-probably-nothing|title=Weinstein's theory of everything is probably nothing|last=Pontzen|first=Andrew|date=May 24, 2013|newspaper=[[New Scientist]]|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aron|first=Jacob|date=June 2013|title=How to test Weinstein's provocative theory of everything|journal=New Scientist|volume=218|issue=2920|pages=10|doi=10.1016/s0262-4079(13)61403-7|issn=0262-4079}}</ref> They were unable to debate more intensely due to the fact that there was no published paper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/dear-guardian-youve-been-played/|title=Dear Guardian: You've Been Played|last=Ouellette|first=Jennifer|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==Intellectual dark web==\nWeinstein said he coined the term \"[[intellectual dark web]]\" after his brother, [[Bret Weinstein]], resigned from [[Evergreen State College|The Evergreen State College]] in response to a campus controversy. The term is used to group a number of academics and podcast hosts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Phillips |first=Melanie |author-link=Melanie Phillips |date=May 23, 2018 |title='Intellectual Dark Web' leads fightback against academic orthodoxy |url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-australian/20180523/281977493282862 |newspaper=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Weiss>{{cite news |last=Weiss |first=Bari |author-link=Bari Weiss |date=May 8, 2018 |title=Meet the Renegades of the Intellectual Dark Web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/opinion/intellectual-dark-web.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=wapo>{{cite news |first1=Susan |last1=Svrluga |first2=Joe |last2=Heim |date=June 1, 2017 |title=Threat shuts down college embroiled in racial dispute |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/06/01/threats-shut-down-college-embroiled-in-racial-dispute/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]  |access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==''The Portal''==\nIn June 2019, Weinstein launched a podcast called ''The Portal''.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Derek |last1=Beres |date=July 12, 2019 |website=[[Big Think]]|title=Mathematician Eric Weinstein launches a new podcast, 'The Portal' |url=https://bigthink.com/personal-growth/eric-weinstein-the-portal |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Since its launch, it has featured academics, entrepreneurs, authors, filmmakers, artists, and [[Internet personalities]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://ericweinstein.org/}}\n* {{MathGenealogy|86697}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Eric}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{distinguish|Eric W. Weisstein}}\n{{short description|American venture capital director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = Eric Ross Weinstein\n| name               = \n| image              = Eric Weinstein in January 2019.png\n| caption            = Weinstein in 2019\n| birth_date         =\n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Managing director of Thiel Capital\n| spouse             = Pia Malaney<ref>{{cite web |last1=McClurg |first1=Lesley |title=Let's Talk About Death Over Dinner |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2015/05/07/405003161/lets-talk-about-death-over-dinner |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = American\n| workplaces         = \n| alma_mater         = [[Harvard University]] (PhD)\n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| doctoral_students  = \n| notable_students   = \n| known_for          = \n| influences         = \n| influenced         = \n| relatives          = [[Bret Weinstein]] (brother)\n| awards             = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Eric Ross Weinstein''' is the managing director of Thiel Capital, [[Peter Thiel]]'s personal investment firm, since 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Illing |first=Sean |date=August 20, 2017 |title=Why capitalism can't survive without socialism |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/7/25/15998002/capitalism-socialism-peter-thiel-wall-street-eric-weinstein |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=July 2, 2018}}</ref> He and his brother [[Bret Weinstein]] coined the term [[Intellectual Dark Web]] to refer to an informal group of pundits.<ref>{{cite web |last1=French |first1=David A. |author-link1=David A. French |title=Critics Miss the Point of the 'Intellectual Dark Web' |url= https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/05/intellectual-dark-web-meaning-audience/ |work=[[National Review]] |access-date=June 25, 2019 |date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sommer |first1=Will |title=Intellectual Dark Web Frays After Jordan Peterson Tweets Critically About Brett Kavanaugh |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/intellectual-dark-web-frays-after-jordan-peterson-tweets-critically-about-brett-kavanaugh |publisher=Daily Beast |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWeinstein received his PhD in mathematical physics from the Mathematics Department at [[Harvard University]] in 1992 under the supervision of [[Raoul Bott]].<ref name=\"mathgenealogy\">{{MathGenealogy|86697}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bVFTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47 |page=47 |journal=[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]] |title=Raoul Bott: Collected Papers, Volume 5 |series=Contemporary Mathematicians |editor-last=Tu |editor-first=Loring W. |publisher=[[Birkh\u00e4user]] |year=2018 |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math.harvard.edu/graduate/dissertations/|title=PhD Dissertations Archival Listing|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard Mathematics Department|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In his dissertation, titled \"''Extension of Self-Dual Yang-Mills Equations across the Eighth Dimension''\" Weinstein showed that the [[self-dual Yang\u2013Mills equations]] were not really peculiar to dimension four and admitted generalizations to higher dimensions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beaulieu|first1=Laurent|last2=Kanno|first2=Hiroaki|last3=Singer|first3=I. M.|year=1998|title=Special Quantum Field Theories in Eight And Other Dimensions|journal=Communications in Mathematical Physics|volume=194|issue=1|pages=149\u2013175|arxiv=hep-th/9704167|bibcode=1998CMaPh.194..149B|doi=10.1007/s002200050353|issn=0010-3616}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://inspirehep.net/record/345600?ln=en|title=Extension of Self-Dual Yang-Mills Equations Across the 8th Dimension|website=The High Energy Physics Information System|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Physics===\nIn May 2013, Weinstein gave a colloquium talk, ''Geometric Unity,'' promoted by [[Marcus du Sautoy]] as a potential unified theory of physics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/may/23/eric-weinstein-answer-physics-problems|title=Eric Weinstein may have found the answer to physics' biggest problems|last=du Sautoy|first=Marcus|date=May 23, 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 31, 2013|author-link=Marcus du Sautoy}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z7rd04KzLcg&t=35m10s ''Geometric Unity''], Eric Weinstein lecture at Oxford University (May 23, 2013) with \"Supplementary Explainer\" (Apr 1, 2020), posted to YouTube on Apr 2, 2020</ref> His unpublished theory includes an \"observerse,\" a 14-dimensional space, and predictions for undiscovered particles which he stated could account for [[dark matter]]. Joseph Conlon of the [[University of Oxford]] stated that some of these particles, if they existed, would already have been detected in existing accelerators such as the [[Large Hadron Collider]].<ref name=\"Pontzen2013\" />\n\nFew physicists attended and no preprint, paper, or equations were published.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pontzen|first=Andrew|date=March 2013|title=End of darkness: the stuff that really rules the cosmos|journal=New Scientist|volume=217|issue=2909|pages=32\u201335|doi=10.1016/s0262-4079(13)60757-5|issn=0262-4079}}</ref> Weinstein's ideas were not widely debated. The few that did engage expressed skepticism.<ref name=\"Pontzen2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23595-weinsteins-theory-of-everything-is-probably-nothing|title=Weinstein's theory of everything is probably nothing|last=Pontzen|first=Andrew|date=May 24, 2013|newspaper=[[New Scientist]]|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aron|first=Jacob|date=June 2013|title=How to test Weinstein's provocative theory of everything|journal=New Scientist|volume=218|issue=2920|pages=10|doi=10.1016/s0262-4079(13)61403-7|issn=0262-4079}}</ref> They were unable to debate more intensely due to the fact that there was no published paper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/dear-guardian-youve-been-played/|title=Dear Guardian: You've Been Played|last=Ouellette|first=Jennifer|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\n==Intellectual dark web==\nWeinstein said he coined the term \"[[intellectual dark web]]\" after his brother, [[Bret Weinstein]], resigned from [[Evergreen State College|The Evergreen State College]] in response to a campus controversy. The term is used to group a number of academics and podcast hosts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Phillips |first=Melanie |author-link=Melanie Phillips |date=May 23, 2018 |title='Intellectual Dark Web' leads fightback against academic orthodoxy |url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-australian/20180523/281977493282862 |newspaper=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Weiss>{{cite news |last=Weiss |first=Bari |author-link=Bari Weiss |date=May 8, 2018 |title=Meet the Renegades of the Intellectual Dark Web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/opinion/intellectual-dark-web.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=wapo>{{cite news |first1=Susan |last1=Svrluga |first2=Joe |last2=Heim |date=June 1, 2017 |title=Threat shuts down college embroiled in racial dispute |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/06/01/threats-shut-down-college-embroiled-in-racial-dispute/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]  |access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==''The Portal''==\nIn June 2019, Weinstein launched a podcast called ''The Portal''.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Derek |last1=Beres |date=July 12, 2019 |website=[[Big Think]]|title=Mathematician Eric Weinstein launches a new podcast, 'The Portal' |url=https://bigthink.com/personal-growth/eric-weinstein-the-portal |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Since its launch, it has featured academics, entrepreneurs, authors, filmmakers, artists, and [[Internet personalities]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://ericweinstein.org/}}\n* {{MathGenealogy|86697}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Eric}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "86.21.216.254", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEducation:Removed false information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Weinstein"}
{"title_page": "Ti\u00ebsto", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Dutch DJ}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:Wiki Project_Musicians -->\n| name             = Ti\u00ebsto\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Orange-Nassau|OON]]\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image            = Ti\u00ebsto @ Airbeat One 2017.jpg\n| image_size       = 240px\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Ti\u00ebsto at the 2017 Airbeat One festival, Germany\n| birth_name       = Tijs Michiel Verwest\n| spouse           = [[Annika Backes]]\n| alias            = Allure\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|17}}\n| birth_place      = [[Breda]], [[North Brabant]], [[Netherlands]]\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Progressive house]]\n* [[future house]]\n* [[electro house]]\n* [[big room house]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pilotonline.com/entertainment/music/ti-sto-gets-em-dancing-with-trance-electro-house/article_49edc2cb-8d63-5e9d-aa7f-f1a728a474cc.html |title=Ti\u00ebsto gets 'em dancing with trance, electro-house |last=Ollison |first=Rashod |date=20 September 2011 |website=[[The Virginian-Pilot]] |access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Trance music|trance]]\n* [[deep house]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.beatport.com/en/tiesto-exits-big-room-mellowed-new-label-aftrhrs|title=Ti\u00ebsto exits the big room with his mellowed-out new label, AFTR:HRS|work=beatport.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511154139/https://news.beatport.com/en/tiesto-exits-big-room-mellowed-new-label-aftrhrs/|archivedate=11 May 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* DJ\n* record producer\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* Digital audio workstation\n* keyboard\n* synthesiser\n}}\n| years_active     = 1994\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* AFTR:HRS\n* Musical Freedom\n* [[Black Hole Recordings|Black Hole]]\n* [[Spinnin' Records|Spinnin']]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Gouryella]]\n* [[Kamaya Painters]]\n* [[Armin van Buuren]]\n* [[Hardwell]]\n* [[Steve Aoki]]\n* [[Martin Garrix]]\n* [[BT (musician)|BT]]\n* [[MOTi]]\n* [[KSHMR]]\n* [[DallasK]]\n* [[John Christian (musician)|John Christian]]\n* [[Oliver Heldens]]\n* [[Avicii]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|tiesto.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Tijs Michiel Verwest''' {{small|[[Order of Orange-Nassau|OON]]}} ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8t\u025bis mi\u02c8xil v\u0259r\u02c8\u028b\u025bst|lang}}; born 17 January 1969),<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=DJ Ti\u00ebsto profile|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ti%C3%ABsto-mn0000591459/biography|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=5 August 2008}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Ti\u00ebsto''' ({{IPAc-en|t|i|\u02c8|\u025b|s|t|o\u028a}} {{respell|tee|ES|toh}}<span style=\"margin-left:1.5px\">;</span> {{IPA-nl|\u02c8ti'\u025bsto\u02d0|lang}}), is a Dutch DJ and record producer from [[Breda]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiesto Biodata |url=http://djz.com/featured_djs/tiesto/ |publisher=DJZ.com |accessdate=11 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329021252/http://djz.com/featured_djs/tiesto/ |archivedate=29 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.imorecords.co.uk/house-2/house-artists/tisto-biography-2 Ti\u00ebsto profile]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Imorecords.co.uk; accessed 23 June 2015.</ref> He was named \"the Greatest DJ of All Time\" by ''[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]]'' magazine in a poll voted by the fans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1656432/david-guetta-tiesto/|title=Tiesto's 'Greatest DJ of All Time' Title Earns David Guetta's 'Respect'|last=Bhansali|first=Akshay|date=21 January 2011|publisher=MTV|newspaper=MTV News|access-date=9 October 2016|via=}}</ref> In 2013, he was voted by ''[[DJ Mag]]'' readers as the \"best DJ of the last 20 years\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://djmag.com/content/tiesto-legend |title=TIESTO: LEGEND. Dutch DJ on his Top 100 DJs Legend Award |last=Whitehurst |first=Andrew |publisher=[[DJ Magazine]] |publication-date=6 November 2013 |access-date=27 December 2016}}</ref> He is also regarded as the \"Godfather of [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]\" by many sources.<ref>Sources referring to Ti\u00ebsto as the \"Godfather of EDM\":\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/features/lifestyles-of-the-superstar-djs-how-calvin-harris-david-guetta-and-more-live-756966|title=Lifestyles of the Superstar DJs \u2013 How Calvin Harris, David Guetta And More Live \u2013 NME|date=16 October 2015|work=NME|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://edm.com/articles/2016/12/26/tiesto-aftr-hrs-compilation|title=Tiesto Shares the Diverse Taste of AFTR:HRS With New Compilation|last=Woods|first=Rachel|date=26 December 2016|work=EDM.com|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502181500/http://edm.com/articles/2016/12/26/tiesto-aftr-hrs-compilation|archive-date=2 May 2017|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/2014/06/tiesto-interview-a-town-called-paradise/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Explains the Universe (of EDM)|date=20 June 2014|work=Spin|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/why-ti-sto-is-tired-of-all-the-subgenre-labeling-in-dance-music-6654762|title=Why Ti\u00ebsto Is Tired of All the Subgenre Labeling in Dance Music|last=Lambert|first=Eleanor|date=14 January 2015|work=Village Voice|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.magneticmag.com/2016/03/what-happened-to-the-gods-of-trance/|title=What Ever Happened to The \"Gods of Trance\"?|last=Tyler|date=3 March 2016|work=Magnetic Magazine|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-us}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1851591/superstar-djs-diplo-disclosure/|title=Diplo, Disclosure and a Few More 'Superstar DJs' Are Getting Their Own TV Show|last=White|first=Caitlin|date=20 June 2014|work=MTV News|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/06/superstar-djs-with-annie-mac-trailer|title=Superstar DJs With Annie Mac Debuts on 25 June|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2016/12/26/tiesto-releases-new-aftrhrs-compilation-album/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Releases New AFTR:HRS Compilation Album|last=Andrew Claps|date=26 December 2016|website=Your EDM|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://relentlessbeats.com/2017/01/tiesto-releases-brand-new-aftrhrs-compilation-album/|title=Tiesto Releases Brand New AFTR:HRS Compilation Album|last=Andres|first=Jose|work=Relentless Beats|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, he founded the label [[Black Hole Recordings]] with Arny Bink, where he released the ''[[Magik (series)|Magik]]'' and ''[[In Search of Sunrise (series)|In Search of Sunrise]]'' CD series. Ti\u00ebsto met producer Dennis Waakop Reijers in 1998; the two have worked together extensively since then.<ref name=\"DJ Times - Dennis Waakop Reijers\">{{cite news|last=Tan |first=Emily |title=Ti\u00ebsto Returns With \"Elements of Life\", Another Crowd-Pleasing Dish of Melodic Trance. But Is The World's Biggest DJ Still Following His Muse? |url=http://www.djtimes.com/issues/2007/06/_features_06_2007.htm |accessdate=29 April 2011 |newspaper=DJ Times Magazine |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928143604/http://www.djtimes.com/issues/2007/06/_features_06_2007.htm |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1998 to 2000, Ti\u00ebsto collaborated with [[Ferry Corsten]] under the name [[Gouryella]]. His 2000 remix of [[Delerium]]'s \"[[Silence (Delerium song)|Silence]]\" featuring [[Sarah McLachlan]] exposed him to more mainstream audiences. In 2001, he released his first solo album, ''[[In My Memory]]'', which gave him several major hits that launched his career. He was voted World No. 1 DJ by ''DJ Magazine'' in its annual Top 100 DJs readership poll consecutively for three years from 2002 to 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edmtunes.com/2015/07/dj-mag-top-100-history/|title=A Look Back at 23 Years of the DJ Mag Top 100 Poll \u2013 EDMTunes|last=Ben|date=18 July 2015|website=EDMTunes|language=en-US|access-date=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nJust after releasing his second studio album ''[[Just Be]]'' he performed live at the [[2004 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Athens]], the first DJ to play live on stage at an Olympics. In April 2007 Ti\u00ebsto launched his radio show ''[[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life]]'' on [[Radio 538]] in the Netherlands and released his third studio album ''[[Elements of Life]]''. The album reached number one on the Belgian album chart as well on ''Billboard'' Top Electronic Albums in the U.S. and received a nomination for a [[Grammy Award]] in 2008.<ref name=\"grammy nomination\">{{cite news|title=50th Annual Grammy Awards Nominations|url=http://www.variety.com/awardcentral_article/VR1117977172.html?nav=news&categoryid=1983&cs=1|publisher=Variety|accessdate=5 December 2007|date=6 December 2007}}</ref> Ti\u00ebsto released his fourth studio album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' in October 2009, followed by ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]'' in June 2014. He won the [[Grammy Award for Best Remixed Recording, Non-Classical]] for his remixed version of [[John Legend|John Legend's]] hit \"[[All of Me (John Legend song)|All of Me]]\" at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"grammy\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2015/02/tiesto-wins-grammy-best-remixed-recording-non-classical/ |title=Ti\u00ebsto wins Grammy for Best Remixed Recording, Non Classical |authors=Dancing Astronaut Staff |date=8 February 2015 |website=Dancing Astronaut |access-date=18 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Ti\u00ebsto married model Annika Backes in a Utah desert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/dj-tijs-tiesto-verwest-model-annika-backes-wedding-amangiri-utah|title=Ti\u00ebsto,gets married in the Middle of the Utah Desert|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTijs Michiel Verwest was born in [[Breda]], Netherlands, on 17 January 1969.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/biography/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Biography|publisher=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|accessdate=23 October 2016|author=Ti\u00ebsto Blog}}</ref> He began to cultivate his passion for music from age twelve. At age fourteen, he intensified his commitment to the art, and began DJing professionally at school parties. Between 1985 and 1994, Ti\u00ebsto began a residency at several clubs in the Netherlands at the behest of his manager. At the Spock, a small club in Breda, he fine-tuned his own live style by performing from 10 p.m. until 4 a.m. on weekends. In the beginning of his career as a DJ he mostly played [[new beat]] and [[acid house]].<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1994\u20132000: Early projects and success ===\nIn 1994, he began releasing material on Noculan Records' sub-labels Chemo and Coolman. During these years, he produced [[Hardcore techno|hardcore]] and [[gabber]] tracks under such aliases as Da Joker and DJ Limited.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/> Ti\u00ebsto was later discovered by the [[general manager]] of [[Rotterdam]]-based Basic Beat Recordings.<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.starpulse.com/Music/DJ_Tiesto/Biography |title=DJ Tiesto Biography |publisher=Star Pulse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080710153232/http://www.starpulse.com/Music/DJ_Tiesto/Biography |archive-date=10 July 2008 |access-date=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tiesto.jpg|thumb|144px|Ti\u00ebsto in [[Sant Antoni de Portmany|Sant Antoni]], [[Ibiza]], prior to performing at [[Amnesia (nightclub)|Amnesia]], July 2000]]\nIn late 1994, Ti\u00ebsto signed to Basic Beat where he met Arny Bink, Ti\u00ebsto released records on the sub-label Trashcan, founded by Arny, and later created the Guardian Angel sub-label with Arny in which they introduced the popular ''Forbidden Paradise'' series. From 1995\u201396 he released four extended plays on Bonzai Jumps and XTC, sub-labels of [[Lightning Records]]. In 1997, he joined his friend Yves Vandichel on his sub-label, DJ Yves, a division of the now defunct Human Resource label XSV Music. In the fall of 1997, Bink and Ti\u00ebsto decided to leave Basic Beat and create their own parent label, [[Black Hole Recordings]], Trashcan was discontinued and Guardian Angel continued releasing music until 2002. Through Black Hole, Ti\u00ebsto released the [[Magik (series)|''Magik'' series]] and also created two major sub-labels; [[SongBird]] and [[In Trance We Trust]]. From 1998 to 1999, he released music on Planetary Consciousness where he met [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Hardy Heller and invited him to release some records on Black Hole.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Ti\u00ebsto joined forces with fellow Dutch deejay [[Ferry Corsten]] to create the trance based duo of [[Gouryella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/ferry-corsten/sets/ferry-corsten-presents-gouryella|title=Ferry Corsten presents Gouryella|website=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=22 March 2017|first=Corsten|last=Ferry}}</ref> The first Gouryella track, also called Gouryella, was released in May 1999 and became a huge hit scoring various chart positions around the world, including a top fifteen position in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/gouryella-gouryella/|title=Gouryella \"Gouryella\"|publisher=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=23 January 2011|accessdate=24 July 2016|author=Ti\u00ebsto Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/ferrycorsten/biography|title=Resident Advisor: Ferry Corsten|publisher=[[Resident Advisor]]|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> Ti\u00ebsto showcased this track in ''[[Magik Three: Far from Earth]]'' as well as in his set at the first [[ID&T]] Innercity party (''[[Live at Innercity: Amsterdam RAI]]''), his first major breakthrough.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/dj-tiesto-live-at-innercity-1999/|title=DJ Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Live At Innercity 1999|website=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=8 January 2011|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> The next single, entitled \"Walhalla\", also made it on the charts worldwide, peaking at No. 27 in the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clubplanet.com/Articles/877/Ferry-Corsten |title=Ferry Corsten |website=Clubplanet |publication-date=3 June 2002 |access-date=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/7571/gouryella/|title=GOURYELLA {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=16 June 2016}}</ref> Released via Ferry's Tsunami, both singles went on to be certified Gold on record sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ferrycorsten.com/news/ferry-corsten-announces-gouryella-live|title=From the studio to the stage: Ferry Corsten announces Gouryella live!|publisher=[[Flashover Recordings]]|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=9 August 2016|author=Flashover Recordings|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912040028/http://ferrycorsten.com/news/ferry-corsten-announces-gouryella-live|archive-date=12 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> During these years, Ti\u00ebsto also collaborated with [[Benno de Goeij]] of [[Rank 1]] under the name [[Kamaya Painters]]. In November 1999, he released the first installment of the [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'']] series. Since then, he performed monthly as a resident at [[Gatecrasher]] in [[Sheffield]], and played a 12-hour set, his longest, in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Longest concert in Amsterdam|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/interview/11b_dj_tiesto_interview.html|publisher=AskMen.com|accessdate=2 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020043825/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/interview/11b_dj_tiesto_interview.html|archive-date=20 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 31 December 1999, he performed at [[Trance Energy]] 2000, a special party held by ID&T for the turn of the millennium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aQYn3YGLod0|title=DJ Tiesto \u2013 Live @ Energy 2000 Complete version|website=[[YouTube]]|date=8 December 2011|accessdate=23 October 2016|first=Vincent|last=Bouwmeester}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/tiesto-live-trance-energy-2000/|title=Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Live @ Trance Energy 2000|website=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Armin van Buuren]], Ti\u00ebsto created two projects in 2000; Alibi \u2013 \"Eternity\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weraveyou.com/2016/06/22/armin-van-buuren-tiestos-joint-collaboration-eternity-alibi-alias-16-years-old/|title=Armin van Buuren and Ti\u00ebsto\u2019s joint collaboration \"Eternity\" under the Alibi alias is 16 years old|publisher=We Rave You|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=9 September 2016|first=Raymond|last=Murphy}}</ref> which was released on Armind, and Major League \u2013 \"Wonder Where You Are?\", which came out on Black Hole. After the release of \"Tenshi\" in September 2000, Ti\u00ebsto decided to concentrate on his solo work and left Ferry Corsten to take on the Gouryella project solely as his own.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/> Through his first compilations and the \"In Trance We Trust\" series, he ended up introducing Armin van Buuren and [[Johan Gielen]] to the mainstream. ''[[Summerbreeze]]'' marked Ti\u00ebsto's U.S. debut,<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\" /> a mix album that showcased his remix of [[Delerium]]'s \"[[Silence (Delerium song)|Silence]]\", which spent four weeks in the UK's Top Ten chart and reached number three in the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' dance chart.<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\" /> ''[[In Search of Sunrise 2]]'' was released in November 2000.\n\n=== 2001\u20132003: ''In My Memory'' ===\n{{external media | float = right | width = 220px | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ersa1s2SkKQ Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Urban Train ft. Kirsty Hawkshaw (Official Music Video)] }}\nIn 2001, Ti\u00ebsto created a new sub-label, [[Magik Muzik]], and released his first solo album, ''[[In My Memory]]'', which contained 5 major hits; \"[[Lethal Industry]]\", which was actually produced in 1999 and had only 3 copies released at that time, the track was officially released in 2001 which was remixed by [[Richard Durand]] in 2006 along with \"[[Flight 643]]\" which was another leading single that was later adapted with vocals by [[Suzanne Palmer]] and released as \"[[643 (Love's on Fire)]]\". Other tracks were \"[[Obsession (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Obsession]]\" in which Ti\u00ebsto worked alongside [[Junkie XL]], the instrumental tracks \"Dallas 4PM\" and \"[[Suburban Train/Urban Train|Suburban Train]]\" with \"[[Suburban Train/Urban Train|Urban Train]]\" as its vocal version. The last singles to be released were \"[[In My Memory (song)|In My Memory]]\" which is the title track for the album as it only received high ratings in the United States and the opening track \"Magik Journey\" which opened [[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]] (2003). On 2 February 2002, Ti\u00ebsto played nine consecutive hours during the second edition of the Dutch Dimension festival.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n[[File:Ti\u00ebsto 2003.jpg|thumb|280px|Ti\u00ebsto at [[w:de:Columbiahalle|Columbiahalle]] in [[Berlin]], 2003]]\nOn 27 February, Ti\u00ebsto was awarded a Zilveren ('Silver') Harp music award. The same year he also received a Lucky Strike Dance Award in the category Best DJ Trance/Progressive. In August he became part of Moby's [[Area Festival|Area2 Tour]]. For eighteen days he travelled through the United States with artists such as [[Moby]] himself, but also [[David Bowie]] and [[Busta Rhymes]]. In January 2003, Ti\u00ebsto received the annual Dutch Popprijs ('Pop Award') during the Noorderslag festival. After touring with Moby, Ti\u00ebsto remixed two songs from him, \"[[We Are All Made of Stars]]\" and \"[[Extreme Ways]]\" in the same year, having \"We Are All Made of Stars\" reach No. 13 in the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]. In 2002 he released his first ''In Search of Sunrise'' mix to feature a place on its name, ''[[In Search of Sunrise 3: Panama]]''. On 28 March 2003; Ti\u00ebsto, [[Dieselboy]], [[Bad Boy Bill]], and Noel Sanger joined the [[PlayStation 2]] Dual Play tour. Ti\u00ebsto and Noel's appearance began on 13 April and ended on 6 June.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top DJs Sign on For Dual Play Tour|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/71910/top-djs-sign-on-for-dual-play-tour|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nHis fame continued to increase for then known he has in the early 2000s, following his six-hour \"Ti\u00ebsto Solo\" sets which he performed without other DJs or opening acts. This idea, of one DJ playing alone to a large crowd was new. Ti\u00ebsto was the first DJ to hold a solo concert in a stadium; on 10 May 2003, he performed for 25,000 people in [[Arnhem]]'s [[GelreDome]], later called ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]''. He repeated the same type of concert the following year during two consecutive nights in late October.<ref name=\"Ti\u00ebsto in Concert\">{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto in Concert|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=79&step=5&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=7 October 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007011448/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=79&step=5&pid=NaN}}</ref> In addition to holding these two concerts for 35,000 of his fans, he held another concert for a crowd of 20,000 in [[Hasselt|Hasselt, Belgium]] the following week.<ref name=\"Ti\u00ebsto in Concert\"/> [[DVD]]s of both his 10 May 2003 and 30 October 2004 concerts have been released, having the other DVD titled ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert 2]]''. The DVDs show the journey from the first idea to the main event, featuring live performances by [[Andain]], [[Dinand Woesthoff]], and [[Jan Johnston]]. The event includes live music and dancers performing at different times throughout the set.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto in Concert Review|url=http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/reviews/fr/DJTiestoDVD.htm|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211213948/http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/reviews/fr/DJTiestoDVD.htm|archivedate=11 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== 2004\u20132006: ''Just Be'' and appointment to the Order of Orange-Nassau ===\n[[File:Tiesto 2004.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Ti\u00ebsto performing in [[Arnhem]]'s [[GelreDome]], 2004]]\n\nIn 2004, he released his second artist album ''[[Just Be]]'', which featured his first single \"[[Traffic (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Traffic]]\" which is the first non-vocal track to reach number one spot in the Dutch national charts for 23 years.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nThe track \"Sweet Misery\" was originally written for [[Evanescence]] but it did not meet the deadline for the release of their album. In support to his ''Just Be'' album, he played at [[Breda]], [[Eindhoven]], [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]], and [[Amsterdam]]; these stops were later named [[Just Be#Just Be: Train Tour|Just Be: Train Tour]]. On 20 May 2004 he was appointed Officer of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]] by Her Majesty [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] of the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestolive.fr/2015/08/video-tiesto-officer-of-the-order-of-orange-nassau-may-20-2004.html|title=Vid\u00e9o: Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Officer of the Order of Orange-Nassau \u2013 May 20, 2004|publisher=Ti\u00ebstolive.fr|date=14 August 2015|accessdate=2 August 2016|author=Ti\u00ebstolive.fr}}</ref> The [[Athens Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games]] (ATHOC) asked Ti\u00ebsto to perform at the Olympic Games, making him the first DJ to play live on stage at an [[Olympic Games]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Athens]], where he played for 90 minutes.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n{{external media\n| float = right\n| width = 180px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2EaE0_gQLw0 Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Adagio For Strings (Official Music Video)]\n}}\nTi\u00ebsto flew to Athens in January 2004 to have a meeting with the ATHOC. His ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]'' DVD caught their attention, after which he was asked to write more tracks based on his opening tune \"[[Adagio for Strings (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Adagio for Strings]]\" which would fit in with the Olympic spirit and combine the classical with the modern age. The first rehearsal was on 7 August, for an empty stadium; the second rehearsal was on 8 August, with 35,000 volunteers. The last rehearsal included almost 60,000 people in the stadium which was on 10 August.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nDuring the course of his performance at the Olympics, the Dutch athletes started dancing in front of the DJ booth and had to be moved on by officials. The performance included new tracks produced especially for the Opening Ceremony and songs that were created to complement the spirit and theme of the ceremony. A condensed studio-recorded album of the songs played on the Olympic set was later released, including new songs specially composed for the occasion, entitled ''[[Parade of the Athletes]]'' in October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto Performs at Olympic Games Opening Ceremony|url=http://remixmag.com/news/remix_tiesto_performs_olympic|publisher=Remix Magazine|accessdate=30 January 2010|archivedate=18 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518175558/http://remixmag.com/news/remix_tiesto_performs_olympic}}</ref> In the liner notes, he noted the IOC requested that the music not contain any lyrics as they could be inadvertently misinterpreted. In late 2004, he began his touring across [[Latin America]], with his release of ''[[In Search of Sunrise 3: Panama]]'' in which he gained influence from the sun and sand in summer 2002. The tour continued in 2005, and Ti\u00ebsto performed live in Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Panama, Peru, Costa Rica, Uruguay, Paraguay, Ecuador, Venezuela and Colombia. Following the tours, ''[[In Search of Sunrise 4: Latin America]]'' was released in 2005, featuring a second CD for the first time in the [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'' series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2004\u20132005 Tours|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?PID=3929142&style=music&cart=724839394&All=yes#rev|publisher=CD Universe|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, his ''[[Perfect Remixes Vol. 3]]'' compilation was released through Warlock Records, containing ten tracks which were created during the beginning of his career, between those is [[Junkie XL]], [[Mauro Picotto]] and [[Roc Project|The Roc Project]]. On 20 August 2005, Verwest took ''Ti\u00ebsto in Concert'' to the US when he played to 16,000 at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena]] with [[Cirque du Soleil]] dancers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto Live at the Los Angeles Sports Arena |url=http://www.grooveradio.com/article.asp?ArticleID=1885 |publisher=Groove Radio |accessdate=2 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422200548/http://www.grooveradio.com/article.asp?ArticleID=1885 |archivedate=22 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFor the second year in a row he performed live at a New Year's Eve/New Year's concert in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] at the [[Orleans Arena]] to a sell-out crowd. His four-city U.S. tour was postponed due to the hurricane damage in [[New Orleans]] and [[Miami]]. [[BPM (magazine)|BPM magazine]] has an annual poll in the US which is unveiled in the [[Winter Music Conference|WMC]], in 2005 Ti\u00ebsto took the No. 1 spot.<ref name=\"Night Shift\">{{cite web|title=Remix Magazine March 2004 by Kylee Swenson|url=http://web.ebscohost.com/src/detail?vid=4&hid=14&sid=0a728d15-8c81-4ce3-bf2a-0c522ea9b15b%40sessionmgr2|accessdate=2 August 2008|publisher=Remix Magazine|df=}}</ref> The influences of [[Los Angeles]] remained with him and would later influence his ''In Search of Sunrise'' compilation.\n\nA wax sculpture of Ti\u00ebsto was placed behind a turntable at [[Madame Tussauds]] in Amsterdam where visitors can mix Ti\u00ebsto's music together.<ref>{{cite web|title=In the mix with Ti\u00ebsto at Madame Tussauds Amsterdam|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=68&step=10&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=27 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227151230/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=68&step=10&pid=NaN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto at Madame Tussauds Amsterdam |url=http://www.madametussauds.com/Amsterdam/en/OnzeBeelden/PopulaireMuzikanten/Tiesto/Default.aspx |publisher=Madame Tussauds |accessdate=29 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923003349/http://www.madametussauds.com/Amsterdam/en/OnzeBeelden/PopulaireMuzikanten/Tiesto/Default.aspx |archivedate=23 September 2009 }}</ref> Stops were made in Ukraine, Slovakia, Serbia, Macedonia, Romania, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Turkey, Croatia, Poland and South Africa. The United States tour that was part of ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]'' was dwarfed by his appearance at [[Sensation (event)|Sensation White]] in 2006 where he performed to over 45,000 people in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sensation White 2006|url=http://www.sensation-white.com/portal/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&Itemid=74&limit=14&limitstart=56&lang=en|publisher=[[Sensation (event)|Sensation White]]|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706115516/http://www.sensation-white.com/portal/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&Itemid=74&limit=14&limitstart=56&lang=en|archivedate=6 July 2008}}</ref> The compilation was launched in the [[Winter Music Conference]] in [[Miami Beach]] to support his release, Ti\u00ebsto went on his [[In Search of Sunrise 5 Asia Tour]] for more than three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto to Launch in Search of Sunrise 5: Los Angeles|url=http://www.internetdj.com/article.php?storyid=740|publisher=Internet DJ|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref> In September 2006, Ti\u00ebsto was admitted to hospital after experiencing pain in his chest. He was diagnosed with [[pericarditis]] and subsequently had to cancel a number of shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto in Heart Scare |url=http://www.megamindmagazine.com/globalnews/tiesto-in-heart-scare |publisher=Megamind |accessdate=17 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217193645/http://www.megamindmagazine.com/globalnews/tiesto-in-heart-scare |archivedate=17 February 2011 }}</ref> With the diagnosis, he was invited to support [[Dance4Life]] to help teens who are not aware of the risks of [[HIV/AIDS]].\n\n=== 2007\u20132008: ''Elements of Life'' ===\n[[File:Ti\u00ebsto5, Tallinn, 2007.jpg|thumb|200px|Ti\u00ebsto in [[Tallinn]], 2007]]\nOn 6 April 2007, Ti\u00ebsto began presenting a new weekly two-hour radio show called ''[[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life]]'' on Dutch radio station [[Radio 538]]. Ten days later, Ti\u00ebsto released his third studio album ''[[Elements of Life]]''. The album moved 73,000 units in its April release, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref name=\"Night Shift\"/>\n\nDuring the production of the album Ti\u00ebsto in several cases sent a demo with the music to certain artists, and they replied back with the lyrics and vocals and other duration times. In the case of [[Christian Burns]] from [[BBMak]], Ti\u00ebsto met him through [[MySpace]] and contacted him and the production of the single \"[[In the Dark (Ti\u00ebsto song)|In the Dark]]\".<ref name=\"About interview\">{{Cite web |url=http://dancemusic.about.com/od/remixersproducers/a/TiestoEOLInterv.htm |title=Elements of Life interview |publisher=[[About.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615025152/http://dancemusic.about.com/od/remixersproducers/a/TiestoEOLInterv.htm |archive-date=15 June 2011 |access-date=2 August 2008}}</ref> The album consists of [[rock music|rock]], [[trance music|trance]] and [[experimental music]], which shows the style Ti\u00ebsto has grown throughout the years since his previous albums which contained lyrics, ''[[In My Memory]]'' and ''[[Just Be]]''. Producer [[BT (musician)|Brian Transeau]] collaborated with Ti\u00ebsto in three tracks, he composed \"Bright Morningstar\" and \"[[Elements of Life|Sweet Things]]\", and performed the vocals in the single \"[[Break My Fall]]\". Together, they produced more tracks which were not released in the album, Ti\u00ebsto has mentioned they would work again during the coming summer.<ref name=\"About interview\" />\n\n{{external media\n| float = left\n| width = 170px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EE7CXZ1Lyu4 Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Elements of Life (Official Music Video)]\n}}\nIn December 2007 it was announced that the album was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]], in the category \"Best Electronic/Dance Album.\"<ref name=\"grammy nomination\"/> The album also received gold certifications in Belgium, Hungary, Netherlands, and Romania. In support of the album, he embarked on the worldwide [[Elements of Life World Tour]], and released the ''[[Copenhagen: Elements of Life World Tour]]'' DVD in 2008.\n\nTi\u00ebsto announced his residence at [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]]. He played sets in [[Ibiza]] every Monday, from 7 July to 22 September in the style of his [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'' series]]. In 2007, he had released ''[[In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza]]'' which was inspired by the island.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residence at Privilege, Ibiza|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=829&step=1&pid=44|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730172927/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=829&step=1&pid=44|archivedate=30 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April, he released ''[[Elements of Life: Remixed]]'', a recompilation of the ''Elements of Life'' album with all remixed versions. In mid-2008, Ti\u00ebsto announced his [[In Search of Sunrise: Summer Tour 2008]], which was presented by [[Armani Exchange]] in May in support of his [[In Search of Sunrise 7: Asia]] compilation<ref name=\"Armani Summer Tour\"/> and the previously released ''In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza''.\n\n=== 2009\u20132012: ''Kaleidoscope'' and ''Kiss from the Past'' ===\nOn 6 October 2009, he released his fourth studio album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'', which featured artists such as [[Priscilla Ahn]], [[Calvin Harris]], [[Tegan & Sara]] and [[Nelly Furtado]]. Unlike his earlier albums, which were all mostly trance, Kaleidoscope explores other electronic genres, and is considered Tiesto's most experimental album. The first single \"[[I Will Be Here]]\" featuring [[Sneaky Sound System]] being released in July 2009. It reached number three on the much acclaimed Driscoll 5, and lasted there for 24 weeks in the beginning of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.styletraxx.com/2009/03/tisto_is_king_of_the_world.php |title=Tiesto is the King of the World |publisher=Styletraxx |accessdate=22 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327142514/http://www.styletraxx.com/2009/03/tisto_is_king_of_the_world.php |archivedate=27 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/the-business-of-life/entertainment/king-of-spin-does-the-biz-2009-03-13-1.94566|title=King of Spin Does the Biz|publisher=Rachel McArthur Emirates Business 24-7|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/08/entertainment/et-fave8|title=L.A. scene inspires his sound|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=8 May 2009|first=Mark|last=Sachs}}</ref> In its first week, the album reached the Top 10 chart on [[iTunes]].<ref name=\"clichemag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clichemag.com/issue08|title=Clich\u00e9Magazine \u2013 Issue 08|publisher=Clichemag.com|accessdate=23 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227093815/http://www.clichemag.com/issue08/|archivedate=27 February 2010}}</ref> To release the album he set up a new record label called Musical Freedom after parting ways with [[Black Hole Recordings]]. Ti\u00ebsto felt that his music was evolving in a new direction and his focus as an artist was moving away from what Black Hole was set up to support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hangout.altsounds.com/news/109776-ti-sto-signs-pias-deal-australia-zealand.html |title=Ti\u00ebsto signs deal&nbsp;\u2014 Australia & New Zealand |publisher=Altsounds.com |accessdate=19 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606142350/http://hangout.altsounds.com/news/109776-ti-sto-signs-pias-deal-australia-zealand.html |archivedate=6 June 2012 }}</ref> His new tour, sharing the name of his new album, called [[Kaleidoscope World Tour]] commenced in late September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2009/07/23/680879.aspx|title=Ti\u00ebsto Conquers The World|publisher=Pollstar.com|accessdate=23 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725085903/http://pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2009/07/23/680879.aspx|archivedate=25 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2010, he released a greatest hits album, ''[[Magikal Journey|Magikal Journey: The Hits Collection 1998\u20132008]]'', a two disc album focusing on his most famous songs and remixes of his songs. On 7 April, he announced that he would start a new compilation series called ''A New Dawn'' with his own label Musical Freedom. In his interview Ti\u00ebsto furthermore confirmed that he would no longer have any more involvement with Black Hole Recordings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixmag.net/content/tiesto-announces-new-mix-album-series-new-dawn|title=Tiesto Announces New Mix Album Series \u2013 'A New Dawn'|work=Mixmag|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=9 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909210122/http://www.mixmag.net/content/tiesto-announces-new-mix-album-series-new-dawn}}</ref> On 31 August, ''[[Kaleidoscope: Remixed]]'' was released, a remix album of his album ''Kaleidoscope''.\n\nAlso in 2009 and 2010, Ti\u00ebsto contributed songs to both the ''[[DJ Hero]]'' and ''[[DJ Hero 2]]'' video games and is a playable character in the second game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6217443.html |title=Daft Punk mixing up DJ Hero |publisher=GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124021332/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6217443.html |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6274493.html?tag=result%3Btitle%3B0 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731161901/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6274493.html?tag=result;title;0 |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |title=DJ Hero 2 spinning 105 songs |publisher=Gamespot.com |accessdate=13 August 2010 }}</ref> He also produced a trance-flavored song for Memphis rap duo [[Three 6 Mafia]]'s album called \"[[Feel It (Three 6 Mafia song)|Feel It]]\", which features [[Sean Kingston]] and [[Flo Rida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267845/three-6-mafia-lays-down-laws-of-power|title=Three 6 Mafia Lays Down 'Laws of Power'|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tiesto 2012.jpg|thumb|260px|Ti\u00ebsto performing at the 2012 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]]]\nOn 4 April 2011, his mix compilation ''[[Club Life: Volume One Las Vegas]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471904576229122190118978?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Ti\u00ebsto: Electronic Music's Superstar|accessdate=5 April 2011|work=The Wall Street Journal|first=Jim|last=Fusilli|date=30 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/intl/49559/Tiestos_new_style_at_work_on_Club_Life_mixCD|title=Tiesto's \"new style\" at work on 'Club Life' mix-CD|accessdate=5 April 2011}}</ref> On 13 June, his studio album, ''[[Kiss from the Past]]'', was released under his alias Allure, and featured [[Christian Burns]], [[Jes Brieden|JES]], and [[Emma Hewitt]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiss From The Past|url=http://www.beatport.com/release/kiss-from-the-past/381943|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, satellite radio broadcaster [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio|Sirius XM]] launched [[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life Radio]], one of five dance/electronic stations on the platform. Programming was \"curated by Ti\u00ebsto himself<ref>{{cite web |title=Tiesto's Club Life Radio Channel to Launch from Miami Music Week on SiriusXM |url=http://investor.siriusxm.com/investor-overview/press-releases/press-release-details/2012/Tiestos-Club-Life-Radio-Channel-to-Launch-from-Miami-Music-Week-on-SiriusXM/default.aspx |website=investor.siriusxm.com |accessdate=18 November 2018 |language=en-CA}}</ref>\". The station ran until 2017.\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: ''Club Life'' and ''A Town Called Paradise''===\n{{external media\n| float = left\n| width = 170px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CFF0mV24WCY Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Red Lights (Official Music Video)]\n}}\n''[[Club Life: Volume Three Stockholm]]'' was released worldwide physically on 25 June 2013 and it hit No. 16 on the Billboard Top 200 Chart. He followed up his third \"Club Life\" installment with the 2014 effort, ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]''. The album featured an assortment of guest stars and was preceded by two singles, \"[[Red Lights (song)|Red Lights]]\" and \"[[Wasted (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Wasted]]\" \u2013 yielding his first two gold singles in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electronic.vegas/news/tiesto-celebrates-gold-certified-singles-hakkasan-gold-party/|title=Tiesto celebrates two gold-certified singles at Hakkasan Gold Party|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> A medley from the album also soundtracks a presentation at the [[Bellagio (resort)]] fountain in Las Vegas, a first for a dance music artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.bellagio.com/bellagio/latest-news/fountains-of-bellagio-learn-new-dance-to-hits-by-famed-djproducer-tisto.htm|title=Fountains of Bellagio Learn New Dance to Hits by Famed DJ/Producer Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Bellagio Resort & Casino|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 interview with ''[[DJ Magazine]]'', Ti\u00ebsto revealed why he left trance music. When asked whether his decision to leave the genre was influential to his popularity in the United States, the Dutch producer said: \"Maybe, it's hard to say. I think I'd still be the 'Tiesto trance guy' but the difference is you're not really being relevant. Some of the old trance guys still have their following but it doesn't feel like anybody really cares \u2013 and that's the biggest difference. It's nice to be in touch with the new kids who are coming up \u2013 the 16 and 18-year olds who are producing house music see me as kind of a godfather, and it's really cool to be in touch with them. I think if I'd still been a trance DJ, they'd have been so disconnected with that sound that I wouldn't be much inspiration for them, and vice versa.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3khHSmbrBqs | title=Tiesto: \"Why I left trance\" | publisher=[[DJ Magazine]] | date=10 April 2014 | accessdate=23 October 2016 | author=DJ Magazine | website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], he won the [[Grammy Award for Best Remixed Recording, Non-Classical]] for his remixed version of [[John Legend]]'s hit \"[[All of Me (John Legend song)|All of Me]]\".<ref name=\"grammy\"/> The same year his fourth installment of the Club Life compilation series, titled ''[[Club Life: Volume Four New York City]]'', was released through Musical Freedom. In April 2016, he launched a [[deep house]] label, AFTR:HRS, to promote deep house music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7341834/tiesto-aftrhrs-label-deep-house-blr-nungwi|title=Ti\u00ebsto Launches AFTR:HRS Deep House Sub-Label, Premieres BLR's 'Nungwi': Exclusive|first=Elias|last=Leight|date=25 April 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2016/04/26/tiesto-unveils-sub-label-aftrhrs-inaugural-track/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Unveils Sub-Label AFTR:HRS with Inaugural Track|first=Cameron|last=Gregg|date=26 April 2016|website=Your EDM|access-date=15 July 2016}}</ref> He appeared in the 2016 [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated documentary film about American DJ and producer [[Steve Aoki]], titled ''[[I'll Sleep When I'm Dead (2016 film)|I'll Sleep When I'm Dead]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/steve-aoki-ill-sleep-when-im-dead-documentary-hits-netflix/|title=Steve Aoki 'I'll Sleep When I'm Dead' Documentary Hits Netflix {{!}} The Nocturnal Times|website=www.thenocturnaltimes.com|access-date=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2017, Ti\u00ebsto was awarded the key to the city of [[Las Vegas]]. The day is now known as \"Ti\u00ebsto Day\" in [[Clark County, Nevada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7655127/tiesto-on-my-way|title=Tiesto Seizes the New Year and Celebrates His Birthday With 'On My Way'|publisher=[[Billboard magazine]]|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref> He was featured in the 2017 documentary starring [[Carl Cox]] and [[Martin Garrix]], titled ''[[What We Started]]''''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-what-we-started-filmmakers-talk-world-premiere-and-the-evolu-119767|title=Interview: 'What We Started' filmmakers talk world premiere and the evolution of EDM|work=AXS|access-date=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 October 2017, the fifth installment of the Club Life series entitled '[[ClubLife, Vol. 5 - China]]' was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edmtunes.com/2017/10/tiesto-releases-clublife-vol-5-china/|title=Tiesto Releases Super Amped Up 'Clublife' Vol.5 China |first=Michael|last=Tam|date=6 October 2017|publisher=EDM Tunes|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref> The compilation album features tracks by John Christian, SWACQ, Ti\u00ebsto and Z.Tao, and collaborations between Ti\u00ebsto and Aloe Blacc, John Christian, [[Dzeko (DJ)|Dzeko]], Diplo, KSHMR, Talay Riley, Sevenn, Stargate, SWACQ and Vassy.\n\nIn March 2018, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' named Tiesto as number eight on their 2018 ranking of dance musicians titled Billboard Dance 100.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8257429/billboard-dance-100-2018 |title=Billboard Dance 100 Artists of 2018: The Complete List |website=Billboard |access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wjbdradio.com/music-news/2018/03/22/the-chainsmokers-named-top-djs-in-the-world-by-billboard |title=The Chainsmokers named top DJs in the world by Billboard |website=WJBD Radio |access-date=23 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322221157/http://www.wjbdradio.com/music-news/2018/03/22/the-chainsmokers-named-top-djs-in-the-world-by-billboard |archive-date=22 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2018, Ti\u00ebsto released his debut EP titled ''[[I Like It Loud (EP)|I Like It Loud]]'', featuring four songs that are collaborations with artists such as [[John Christian (musician)|John Christian]], [[Mesto]], [[Matisse & Sadko]] and [[MOTi]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8260989/tiesto-john-christian-i-like-it-loud-listen |title=Tiesto & John Christian Turn It Up on 'I Like It Loud': Listen |website=Billboard |access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2018, Ti\u00ebsto collaborated with [[Dzeko (DJ)|Dzeko]], [[Post Malone]] and [[Preme]] on a track titled \"[[Jackie Chan (song)|Jackie Chan]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463601/tiesto-jackie-chan-video-dzeko-post-malone-preme|title=Tiesto, Dzeko, Post Malone & Preme Find Adventure in 'Jackie Chan': Watch|work=Billboard|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2019, Ti\u00ebsto released his remix of [[Avicii|Avicii's]] posthumous \"Tough Love\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cultr.com/news/avicii-tough-love-tiesto-remix|title=Ti\u00ebsto Has Officially Released His Remix of Avicii's Posthumous 'Tough Love' |website=Cultr |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Income==\nIn 2016, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated that Ti\u00ebsto's annual income was $39 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/tiesto/?list=celebrities |title=Ti\u00ebsto |work=[[Forbes]] |year=2015 |accessdate=28 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nOn 6 January 2005, Ti\u00ebsto performed in an outdoor fundraiser in De Dam, Amsterdam. The free event involved Dutch artists like [[Dinand Woesthoff]], [[BL\u00d8F]], [[Acda en De Munnik|Acda & De Munnik]], [[Di-rect]], and [[Trijntje Oosterhuis]] were involved in it to provide financial aid to the people who suffered from the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]] in [[South Asia|southern]] and [[Southeast Asia|southeastern Asia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto closes fundraiser in the Netherlands for Asian tsunami victims|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=71&step=10&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=27 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227151243/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=71&step=10&pid=NaN}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, Ti\u00ebsto was named the official worldwide ambassador for the [[Dance4Life]] foundation promoting awareness of [[HIV/AIDS]], as the foundation's ambassador he has helped the organisation with fundraising along with recording the track \"[[Dance4life (song)|Dance4life]]\" that he recorded with [[Maxi Jazz]] from [[Faithless]]. The foundation consists on a better way of living with safe sex in exchange of entertainment to the young crowd.<ref name=\"dance4life\">{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto new ambassador of Dance4Life|url=http://www.dance4life.com/en_4life_news_article/2160|publisher=dance4life.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=8 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708224352/http://www.dance4life.com/en_4life_news_article/2160}}</ref> The song was a huge success, peaking for five weeks in number 3 and eleven consecutive weeks in the Top 10 of the [[Dutch Top 40|Dutch Singles Chart]], it reached number 5 in Belgium, number 6 in Finland and also charting in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] and Germany.\n\nWith the successful release of ''[[Elements of Life]]'', Ti\u00ebsto and fashion designer [[Giorgio Armani]] collaborated on a limited edition Ti\u00ebsto T-shirt available at Armani Exchange stores. His single \"[[Elements of Life|Sweet Things]]\" comes with the shirt including an exclusive \"A|X Remix\" by Tom Cloud which shows the great influence Ti\u00ebsto has in fashion culture.<ref name=\"mercy\">{{cite web |title=Armani Exchange and Ti\u00ebsto team up to \"Remix the future\" and support mercy corps |url=http://www.styletraxx.com/2007/12/armani_exchange_and_tiesto_tea.php |publisher=Styletraxx |accessdate=23 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318155525/http://www.styletraxx.com/2007/12/armani_exchange_and_tiesto_tea.php |archivedate=18 March 2008 }}</ref> The charity raised over U.S. $300,000.<ref name=\"Armani Summer Tour\">{{cite web|title=Armani Onboard With Tiesto For Summer Tour|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/news/e3i1155cb8195120add4b2d93ba82aeb65c|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Ti\u00ebsto released a compilation album ''Dance (RED) Save Lives'' in collaboration with [[Product Red]], with the aim of donating any proceeds from the album to the fight against AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinred.com/press_releases/tiesto-joins-with-red-to-engage-the-dance-music-community-in-the-fight-against-aids |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618175659/http://www.joinred.com/press_releases/tiesto-joins-with-red-to-engage-the-dance-music-community-in-the-fight-against-aids/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 June 2013 |title=Press |publisher=Joinred.com |accessdate=23 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Ti\u00ebsto headlined the first-ever Thank You Festival, presented by Global Citizen in partnership with [[World Childhood Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/6041168/tiesto-above-beyond-to-perform-at-global-citizens-thank-you-festival|title=Ti\u00ebsto, Above & Beyond To Perform at Global Citizen's Thank You Festival|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> As a part of the festival campaign, Ti\u00ebsto took part in supporting ThankYou.org. For every song shared, the Carlson Family Foundation donated $5 to the World Childhood Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/tiesto-thankyou-childhood-campaign/|title=Ti\u00ebsto for the ThankYou by Childhood Campaign \u2013 Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=27 June 2014|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Ti\u00ebsto headlined the free [[Global Citizen Festival]] in New York's Central Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jay-z-no-doubt-tiesto-set-to-headline-free-global-citizen-festival-20140709|title=Jay Z, No Doubt, Ti\u00ebsto Set to Headline Free Global Citizen Festival|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Ti\u00ebsto discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[In My Memory]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Just Be]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Elements of Life]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]'' (2014)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Ti\u00ebsto}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|q=Ti\u00ebsto|s=no|commons=Category:Ti\u00ebsto|n=no|v=no|species=no}}\n* {{official website|http://www.tiesto.com/}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Digweed]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[DJ Magazine]] Number 1 DJ|years=2002\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Van Dyk]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Ti\u00ebsto}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Ti\u00ebsto \n| list =\n{{DJ Mag Top 100 DJs Poll \u2212 No 1 DJ|state=collapsed}} \n{{DJ Award for Best Electro DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best International DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best Progressive and Progressive House DJ|state=collapsed}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiesto}}\n[[Category:Ti\u00ebsto| ]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Club DJs]]\n[[Category:Dutch dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Dutch DJs]]\n[[Category:Dutch record producers]]\n[[Category:Dutch house musicians]]\n[[Category:Dutch trance musicians]]\n[[Category:Eurodance musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Breda]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Ultra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Orange-Nassau]]\n[[Category:Progressive house musicians]]\n[[Category:Future house musicians]]\n[[Category:Revealed Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Dutch DJ}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:Wiki Project_Musicians -->\n| name             = Ti\u00ebsto\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Orange-Nassau|OON]]\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image            = Ti\u00ebsto @ Airbeat One 2017.jpg\n| image_size       = 240px\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Ti\u00ebsto at the 2017 Airbeat One festival, Germany\n| birth_name       = Tijs Michiel Verwest\n| spouse           = [[Annika Backes]]\n| alias            = Allure\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|17}}\n| birth_place      = [[Breda]], [[North Brabant]], [[Netherlands]]\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Progressive house]]\n* [[future house]]\n* [[electro house]]\n* [[big room house]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pilotonline.com/entertainment/music/ti-sto-gets-em-dancing-with-trance-electro-house/article_49edc2cb-8d63-5e9d-aa7f-f1a728a474cc.html |title=Ti\u00ebsto gets 'em dancing with trance, electro-house |last=Ollison |first=Rashod |date=20 September 2011 |website=[[The Virginian-Pilot]] |access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Trance music|trance]]\n* [[deep house]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.beatport.com/en/tiesto-exits-big-room-mellowed-new-label-aftrhrs|title=Ti\u00ebsto exits the big room with his mellowed-out new label, AFTR:HRS|work=beatport.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511154139/https://news.beatport.com/en/tiesto-exits-big-room-mellowed-new-label-aftrhrs/|archivedate=11 May 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* DJ\n* record producer\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* Digital audio workstation\n* keyboard\n* synthesiser\n}}\n| years_active     = 1994\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* AFTR:HRS\n* Musical Freedom\n* [[Black Hole Recordings|Black Hole]]\n* [[Spinnin' Records|Spinnin']]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Gouryella]]\n* [[Kamaya Painters]]\n* [[Armin van Buuren]]\n* [[Hardwell]]\n* [[Steve Aoki]]\n* [[Martin Garrix]]\n* [[BT (musician)|BT]]\n* [[MOTi]]\n* [[KSHMR]]\n* [[DallasK]]\n* [[John Christian (musician)|John Christian]]\n* [[Oliver Heldens]]\n* [[Avicii]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|tiesto.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Tijs Michiel Verwest''' {{small|[[Order of Orange-Nassau|OON]]}} ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8t\u025bis mi\u02c8xil v\u0259r\u02c8\u028b\u025bst|lang}}; born 17 January 1969),<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|title=DJ Ti\u00ebsto profile|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ti%C3%ABsto-mn0000591459/biography|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=5 August 2008}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Ti\u00ebsto''' ({{IPAc-en|t|i|\u02c8|\u025b|s|t|o\u028a}} {{respell|tee|ES|toh}}<span style=\"margin-left:1.5px\">;</span> {{IPA-nl|\u02c8c\u025bsto\u02d0|lang}}), is a Dutch DJ and record producer from [[Breda]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiesto Biodata |url=http://djz.com/featured_djs/tiesto/ |publisher=DJZ.com |accessdate=11 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329021252/http://djz.com/featured_djs/tiesto/ |archivedate=29 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.imorecords.co.uk/house-2/house-artists/tisto-biography-2 Ti\u00ebsto profile]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Imorecords.co.uk; accessed 23 June 2015.</ref> He was named \"the Greatest DJ of All Time\" by ''[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]]'' magazine in a poll voted by the fans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1656432/david-guetta-tiesto/|title=Tiesto's 'Greatest DJ of All Time' Title Earns David Guetta's 'Respect'|last=Bhansali|first=Akshay|date=21 January 2011|publisher=MTV|newspaper=MTV News|access-date=9 October 2016|via=}}</ref> In 2013, he was voted by ''[[DJ Mag]]'' readers as the \"best DJ of the last 20 years\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://djmag.com/content/tiesto-legend |title=TIESTO: LEGEND. Dutch DJ on his Top 100 DJs Legend Award |last=Whitehurst |first=Andrew |publisher=[[DJ Magazine]] |publication-date=6 November 2013 |access-date=27 December 2016}}</ref> He is also regarded as the \"Godfather of [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]\" by many sources.<ref>Sources referring to Ti\u00ebsto as the \"Godfather of EDM\":\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/features/lifestyles-of-the-superstar-djs-how-calvin-harris-david-guetta-and-more-live-756966|title=Lifestyles of the Superstar DJs \u2013 How Calvin Harris, David Guetta And More Live \u2013 NME|date=16 October 2015|work=NME|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://edm.com/articles/2016/12/26/tiesto-aftr-hrs-compilation|title=Tiesto Shares the Diverse Taste of AFTR:HRS With New Compilation|last=Woods|first=Rachel|date=26 December 2016|work=EDM.com|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502181500/http://edm.com/articles/2016/12/26/tiesto-aftr-hrs-compilation|archive-date=2 May 2017|url-status=dead}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/2014/06/tiesto-interview-a-town-called-paradise/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Explains the Universe (of EDM)|date=20 June 2014|work=Spin|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/why-ti-sto-is-tired-of-all-the-subgenre-labeling-in-dance-music-6654762|title=Why Ti\u00ebsto Is Tired of All the Subgenre Labeling in Dance Music|last=Lambert|first=Eleanor|date=14 January 2015|work=Village Voice|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.magneticmag.com/2016/03/what-happened-to-the-gods-of-trance/|title=What Ever Happened to The \"Gods of Trance\"?|last=Tyler|date=3 March 2016|work=Magnetic Magazine|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-us}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1851591/superstar-djs-diplo-disclosure/|title=Diplo, Disclosure and a Few More 'Superstar DJs' Are Getting Their Own TV Show|last=White|first=Caitlin|date=20 June 2014|work=MTV News|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/06/superstar-djs-with-annie-mac-trailer|title=Superstar DJs With Annie Mac Debuts on 25 June|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2016/12/26/tiesto-releases-new-aftrhrs-compilation-album/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Releases New AFTR:HRS Compilation Album|last=Andrew Claps|date=26 December 2016|website=Your EDM|access-date=28 April 2017}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://relentlessbeats.com/2017/01/tiesto-releases-brand-new-aftrhrs-compilation-album/|title=Tiesto Releases Brand New AFTR:HRS Compilation Album|last=Andres|first=Jose|work=Relentless Beats|access-date=28 April 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, he founded the label [[Black Hole Recordings]] with Arny Bink, where he released the ''[[Magik (series)|Magik]]'' and ''[[In Search of Sunrise (series)|In Search of Sunrise]]'' CD series. Ti\u00ebsto met producer Dennis Waakop Reijers in 1998; the two have worked together extensively since then.<ref name=\"DJ Times - Dennis Waakop Reijers\">{{cite news|last=Tan |first=Emily |title=Ti\u00ebsto Returns With \"Elements of Life\", Another Crowd-Pleasing Dish of Melodic Trance. But Is The World's Biggest DJ Still Following His Muse? |url=http://www.djtimes.com/issues/2007/06/_features_06_2007.htm |accessdate=29 April 2011 |newspaper=DJ Times Magazine |date=June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928143604/http://www.djtimes.com/issues/2007/06/_features_06_2007.htm |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1998 to 2000, Ti\u00ebsto collaborated with [[Ferry Corsten]] under the name [[Gouryella]]. His 2000 remix of [[Delerium]]'s \"[[Silence (Delerium song)|Silence]]\" featuring [[Sarah McLachlan]] exposed him to more mainstream audiences. In 2001, he released his first solo album, ''[[In My Memory]]'', which gave him several major hits that launched his career. He was voted World No. 1 DJ by ''DJ Magazine'' in its annual Top 100 DJs readership poll consecutively for three years from 2002 to 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edmtunes.com/2015/07/dj-mag-top-100-history/|title=A Look Back at 23 Years of the DJ Mag Top 100 Poll \u2013 EDMTunes|last=Ben|date=18 July 2015|website=EDMTunes|language=en-US|access-date=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nJust after releasing his second studio album ''[[Just Be]]'' he performed live at the [[2004 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Athens]], the first DJ to play live on stage at an Olympics. In April 2007 Ti\u00ebsto launched his radio show ''[[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life]]'' on [[Radio 538]] in the Netherlands and released his third studio album ''[[Elements of Life]]''. The album reached number one on the Belgian album chart as well on ''Billboard'' Top Electronic Albums in the U.S. and received a nomination for a [[Grammy Award]] in 2008.<ref name=\"grammy nomination\">{{cite news|title=50th Annual Grammy Awards Nominations|url=http://www.variety.com/awardcentral_article/VR1117977172.html?nav=news&categoryid=1983&cs=1|publisher=Variety|accessdate=5 December 2007|date=6 December 2007}}</ref> Ti\u00ebsto released his fourth studio album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' in October 2009, followed by ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]'' in June 2014. He won the [[Grammy Award for Best Remixed Recording, Non-Classical]] for his remixed version of [[John Legend|John Legend's]] hit \"[[All of Me (John Legend song)|All of Me]]\" at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"grammy\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2015/02/tiesto-wins-grammy-best-remixed-recording-non-classical/ |title=Ti\u00ebsto wins Grammy for Best Remixed Recording, Non Classical |authors=Dancing Astronaut Staff |date=8 February 2015 |website=Dancing Astronaut |access-date=18 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Ti\u00ebsto married model Annika Backes in a Utah desert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/dj-tijs-tiesto-verwest-model-annika-backes-wedding-amangiri-utah|title=Ti\u00ebsto,gets married in the Middle of the Utah Desert|accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTijs Michiel Verwest was born in [[Breda]], Netherlands, on 17 January 1969.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/biography/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Biography|publisher=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|accessdate=23 October 2016|author=Ti\u00ebsto Blog}}</ref> He began to cultivate his passion for music from age twelve. At age fourteen, he intensified his commitment to the art, and began DJing professionally at school parties. Between 1985 and 1994, Ti\u00ebsto began a residency at several clubs in the Netherlands at the behest of his manager. At the Spock, a small club in Breda, he fine-tuned his own live style by performing from 10 p.m. until 4 a.m. on weekends. In the beginning of his career as a DJ he mostly played [[new beat]] and [[acid house]].<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1994\u20132000: Early projects and success ===\nIn 1994, he began releasing material on Noculan Records' sub-labels Chemo and Coolman. During these years, he produced [[Hardcore techno|hardcore]] and [[gabber]] tracks under such aliases as Da Joker and DJ Limited.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/> Ti\u00ebsto was later discovered by the [[general manager]] of [[Rotterdam]]-based Basic Beat Recordings.<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.starpulse.com/Music/DJ_Tiesto/Biography |title=DJ Tiesto Biography |publisher=Star Pulse |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080710153232/http://www.starpulse.com/Music/DJ_Tiesto/Biography |archive-date=10 July 2008 |access-date=20 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tiesto.jpg|thumb|144px|Ti\u00ebsto in [[Sant Antoni de Portmany|Sant Antoni]], [[Ibiza]], prior to performing at [[Amnesia (nightclub)|Amnesia]], July 2000]]\nIn late 1994, Ti\u00ebsto signed to Basic Beat where he met Arny Bink, Ti\u00ebsto released records on the sub-label Trashcan, founded by Arny, and later created the Guardian Angel sub-label with Arny in which they introduced the popular ''Forbidden Paradise'' series. From 1995\u201396 he released four extended plays on Bonzai Jumps and XTC, sub-labels of [[Lightning Records]]. In 1997, he joined his friend Yves Vandichel on his sub-label, DJ Yves, a division of the now defunct Human Resource label XSV Music. In the fall of 1997, Bink and Ti\u00ebsto decided to leave Basic Beat and create their own parent label, [[Black Hole Recordings]], Trashcan was discontinued and Guardian Angel continued releasing music until 2002. Through Black Hole, Ti\u00ebsto released the [[Magik (series)|''Magik'' series]] and also created two major sub-labels; [[SongBird]] and [[In Trance We Trust]]. From 1998 to 1999, he released music on Planetary Consciousness where he met [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Hardy Heller and invited him to release some records on Black Hole.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nIn 1998, Ti\u00ebsto joined forces with fellow Dutch deejay [[Ferry Corsten]] to create the trance based duo of [[Gouryella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/ferry-corsten/sets/ferry-corsten-presents-gouryella|title=Ferry Corsten presents Gouryella|website=[[SoundCloud]]|accessdate=22 March 2017|first=Corsten|last=Ferry}}</ref> The first Gouryella track, also called Gouryella, was released in May 1999 and became a huge hit scoring various chart positions around the world, including a top fifteen position in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/gouryella-gouryella/|title=Gouryella \"Gouryella\"|publisher=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=23 January 2011|accessdate=24 July 2016|author=Ti\u00ebsto Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/ferrycorsten/biography|title=Resident Advisor: Ferry Corsten|publisher=[[Resident Advisor]]|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> Ti\u00ebsto showcased this track in ''[[Magik Three: Far from Earth]]'' as well as in his set at the first [[ID&T]] Innercity party (''[[Live at Innercity: Amsterdam RAI]]''), his first major breakthrough.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/dj-tiesto-live-at-innercity-1999/|title=DJ Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Live At Innercity 1999|website=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=8 January 2011|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> The next single, entitled \"Walhalla\", also made it on the charts worldwide, peaking at No. 27 in the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clubplanet.com/Articles/877/Ferry-Corsten |title=Ferry Corsten |website=Clubplanet |publication-date=3 June 2002 |access-date=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/7571/gouryella/|title=GOURYELLA {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=16 June 2016}}</ref> Released via Ferry's Tsunami, both singles went on to be certified Gold on record sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ferrycorsten.com/news/ferry-corsten-announces-gouryella-live|title=From the studio to the stage: Ferry Corsten announces Gouryella live!|publisher=[[Flashover Recordings]]|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=9 August 2016|author=Flashover Recordings|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912040028/http://ferrycorsten.com/news/ferry-corsten-announces-gouryella-live|archive-date=12 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> During these years, Ti\u00ebsto also collaborated with [[Benno de Goeij]] of [[Rank 1]] under the name [[Kamaya Painters]]. In November 1999, he released the first installment of the [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'']] series. Since then, he performed monthly as a resident at [[Gatecrasher]] in [[Sheffield]], and played a 12-hour set, his longest, in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Longest concert in Amsterdam|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/interview/11b_dj_tiesto_interview.html|publisher=AskMen.com|accessdate=2 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020043825/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/interview/11b_dj_tiesto_interview.html|archive-date=20 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 31 December 1999, he performed at [[Trance Energy]] 2000, a special party held by ID&T for the turn of the millennium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aQYn3YGLod0|title=DJ Tiesto \u2013 Live @ Energy 2000 Complete version|website=[[YouTube]]|date=8 December 2011|accessdate=23 October 2016|first=Vincent|last=Bouwmeester}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/tiesto-live-trance-energy-2000/|title=Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Live @ Trance Energy 2000|website=Ti\u00ebsto Blog|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Armin van Buuren]], Ti\u00ebsto created two projects in 2000; Alibi \u2013 \"Eternity\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weraveyou.com/2016/06/22/armin-van-buuren-tiestos-joint-collaboration-eternity-alibi-alias-16-years-old/|title=Armin van Buuren and Ti\u00ebsto\u2019s joint collaboration \"Eternity\" under the Alibi alias is 16 years old|publisher=We Rave You|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=9 September 2016|first=Raymond|last=Murphy}}</ref> which was released on Armind, and Major League \u2013 \"Wonder Where You Are?\", which came out on Black Hole. After the release of \"Tenshi\" in September 2000, Ti\u00ebsto decided to concentrate on his solo work and left Ferry Corsten to take on the Gouryella project solely as his own.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/> Through his first compilations and the \"In Trance We Trust\" series, he ended up introducing Armin van Buuren and [[Johan Gielen]] to the mainstream. ''[[Summerbreeze]]'' marked Ti\u00ebsto's U.S. debut,<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\" /> a mix album that showcased his remix of [[Delerium]]'s \"[[Silence (Delerium song)|Silence]]\", which spent four weeks in the UK's Top Ten chart and reached number three in the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' dance chart.<ref name=\"starpulse_biography\" /> ''[[In Search of Sunrise 2]]'' was released in November 2000.\n\n=== 2001\u20132003: ''In My Memory'' ===\n{{external media | float = right | width = 220px | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ersa1s2SkKQ Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Urban Train ft. Kirsty Hawkshaw (Official Music Video)] }}\nIn 2001, Ti\u00ebsto created a new sub-label, [[Magik Muzik]], and released his first solo album, ''[[In My Memory]]'', which contained 5 major hits; \"[[Lethal Industry]]\", which was actually produced in 1999 and had only 3 copies released at that time, the track was officially released in 2001 which was remixed by [[Richard Durand]] in 2006 along with \"[[Flight 643]]\" which was another leading single that was later adapted with vocals by [[Suzanne Palmer]] and released as \"[[643 (Love's on Fire)]]\". Other tracks were \"[[Obsession (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Obsession]]\" in which Ti\u00ebsto worked alongside [[Junkie XL]], the instrumental tracks \"Dallas 4PM\" and \"[[Suburban Train/Urban Train|Suburban Train]]\" with \"[[Suburban Train/Urban Train|Urban Train]]\" as its vocal version. The last singles to be released were \"[[In My Memory (song)|In My Memory]]\" which is the title track for the album as it only received high ratings in the United States and the opening track \"Magik Journey\" which opened [[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]] (2003). On 2 February 2002, Ti\u00ebsto played nine consecutive hours during the second edition of the Dutch Dimension festival.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n[[File:Ti\u00ebsto 2003.jpg|thumb|280px|Ti\u00ebsto at [[w:de:Columbiahalle|Columbiahalle]] in [[Berlin]], 2003]]\nOn 27 February, Ti\u00ebsto was awarded a Zilveren ('Silver') Harp music award. The same year he also received a Lucky Strike Dance Award in the category Best DJ Trance/Progressive. In August he became part of Moby's [[Area Festival|Area2 Tour]]. For eighteen days he travelled through the United States with artists such as [[Moby]] himself, but also [[David Bowie]] and [[Busta Rhymes]]. In January 2003, Ti\u00ebsto received the annual Dutch Popprijs ('Pop Award') during the Noorderslag festival. After touring with Moby, Ti\u00ebsto remixed two songs from him, \"[[We Are All Made of Stars]]\" and \"[[Extreme Ways]]\" in the same year, having \"We Are All Made of Stars\" reach No. 13 in the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]. In 2002 he released his first ''In Search of Sunrise'' mix to feature a place on its name, ''[[In Search of Sunrise 3: Panama]]''. On 28 March 2003; Ti\u00ebsto, [[Dieselboy]], [[Bad Boy Bill]], and Noel Sanger joined the [[PlayStation 2]] Dual Play tour. Ti\u00ebsto and Noel's appearance began on 13 April and ended on 6 June.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top DJs Sign on For Dual Play Tour|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/71910/top-djs-sign-on-for-dual-play-tour|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nHis fame continued to increase for then known he has in the early 2000s, following his six-hour \"Ti\u00ebsto Solo\" sets which he performed without other DJs or opening acts. This idea, of one DJ playing alone to a large crowd was new. Ti\u00ebsto was the first DJ to hold a solo concert in a stadium; on 10 May 2003, he performed for 25,000 people in [[Arnhem]]'s [[GelreDome]], later called ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]''. He repeated the same type of concert the following year during two consecutive nights in late October.<ref name=\"Ti\u00ebsto in Concert\">{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto in Concert|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=79&step=5&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=7 October 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007011448/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=79&step=5&pid=NaN}}</ref> In addition to holding these two concerts for 35,000 of his fans, he held another concert for a crowd of 20,000 in [[Hasselt|Hasselt, Belgium]] the following week.<ref name=\"Ti\u00ebsto in Concert\"/> [[DVD]]s of both his 10 May 2003 and 30 October 2004 concerts have been released, having the other DVD titled ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert 2]]''. The DVDs show the journey from the first idea to the main event, featuring live performances by [[Andain]], [[Dinand Woesthoff]], and [[Jan Johnston]]. The event includes live music and dancers performing at different times throughout the set.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto in Concert Review|url=http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/reviews/fr/DJTiestoDVD.htm|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211213948/http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/reviews/fr/DJTiestoDVD.htm|archivedate=11 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== 2004\u20132006: ''Just Be'' and appointment to the Order of Orange-Nassau ===\n[[File:Tiesto 2004.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Ti\u00ebsto performing in [[Arnhem]]'s [[GelreDome]], 2004]]\n\nIn 2004, he released his second artist album ''[[Just Be]]'', which featured his first single \"[[Traffic (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Traffic]]\" which is the first non-vocal track to reach number one spot in the Dutch national charts for 23 years.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nThe track \"Sweet Misery\" was originally written for [[Evanescence]] but it did not meet the deadline for the release of their album. In support to his ''Just Be'' album, he played at [[Breda]], [[Eindhoven]], [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]], and [[Amsterdam]]; these stops were later named [[Just Be#Just Be: Train Tour|Just Be: Train Tour]]. On 20 May 2004 he was appointed Officer of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]] by Her Majesty [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] of the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestolive.fr/2015/08/video-tiesto-officer-of-the-order-of-orange-nassau-may-20-2004.html|title=Vid\u00e9o: Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Officer of the Order of Orange-Nassau \u2013 May 20, 2004|publisher=Ti\u00ebstolive.fr|date=14 August 2015|accessdate=2 August 2016|author=Ti\u00ebstolive.fr}}</ref> The [[Athens Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games]] (ATHOC) asked Ti\u00ebsto to perform at the Olympic Games, making him the first DJ to play live on stage at an [[Olympic Games]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Athens]], where he played for 90 minutes.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\n{{external media\n| float = right\n| width = 180px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2EaE0_gQLw0 Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Adagio For Strings (Official Music Video)]\n}}\nTi\u00ebsto flew to Athens in January 2004 to have a meeting with the ATHOC. His ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]'' DVD caught their attention, after which he was asked to write more tracks based on his opening tune \"[[Adagio for Strings (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Adagio for Strings]]\" which would fit in with the Olympic spirit and combine the classical with the modern age. The first rehearsal was on 7 August, for an empty stadium; the second rehearsal was on 8 August, with 35,000 volunteers. The last rehearsal included almost 60,000 people in the stadium which was on 10 August.<ref name=\"tiestoblog\"/>\n\nDuring the course of his performance at the Olympics, the Dutch athletes started dancing in front of the DJ booth and had to be moved on by officials. The performance included new tracks produced especially for the Opening Ceremony and songs that were created to complement the spirit and theme of the ceremony. A condensed studio-recorded album of the songs played on the Olympic set was later released, including new songs specially composed for the occasion, entitled ''[[Parade of the Athletes]]'' in October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto Performs at Olympic Games Opening Ceremony|url=http://remixmag.com/news/remix_tiesto_performs_olympic|publisher=Remix Magazine|accessdate=30 January 2010|archivedate=18 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518175558/http://remixmag.com/news/remix_tiesto_performs_olympic}}</ref> In the liner notes, he noted the IOC requested that the music not contain any lyrics as they could be inadvertently misinterpreted. In late 2004, he began his touring across [[Latin America]], with his release of ''[[In Search of Sunrise 3: Panama]]'' in which he gained influence from the sun and sand in summer 2002. The tour continued in 2005, and Ti\u00ebsto performed live in Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Panama, Peru, Costa Rica, Uruguay, Paraguay, Ecuador, Venezuela and Colombia. Following the tours, ''[[In Search of Sunrise 4: Latin America]]'' was released in 2005, featuring a second CD for the first time in the [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'' series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2004\u20132005 Tours|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?PID=3929142&style=music&cart=724839394&All=yes#rev|publisher=CD Universe|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, his ''[[Perfect Remixes Vol. 3]]'' compilation was released through Warlock Records, containing ten tracks which were created during the beginning of his career, between those is [[Junkie XL]], [[Mauro Picotto]] and [[Roc Project|The Roc Project]]. On 20 August 2005, Verwest took ''Ti\u00ebsto in Concert'' to the US when he played to 16,000 at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena]] with [[Cirque du Soleil]] dancers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto Live at the Los Angeles Sports Arena |url=http://www.grooveradio.com/article.asp?ArticleID=1885 |publisher=Groove Radio |accessdate=2 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422200548/http://www.grooveradio.com/article.asp?ArticleID=1885 |archivedate=22 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFor the second year in a row he performed live at a New Year's Eve/New Year's concert in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] at the [[Orleans Arena]] to a sell-out crowd. His four-city U.S. tour was postponed due to the hurricane damage in [[New Orleans]] and [[Miami]]. [[BPM (magazine)|BPM magazine]] has an annual poll in the US which is unveiled in the [[Winter Music Conference|WMC]], in 2005 Ti\u00ebsto took the No. 1 spot.<ref name=\"Night Shift\">{{cite web|title=Remix Magazine March 2004 by Kylee Swenson|url=http://web.ebscohost.com/src/detail?vid=4&hid=14&sid=0a728d15-8c81-4ce3-bf2a-0c522ea9b15b%40sessionmgr2|accessdate=2 August 2008|publisher=Remix Magazine|df=}}</ref> The influences of [[Los Angeles]] remained with him and would later influence his ''In Search of Sunrise'' compilation.\n\nA wax sculpture of Ti\u00ebsto was placed behind a turntable at [[Madame Tussauds]] in Amsterdam where visitors can mix Ti\u00ebsto's music together.<ref>{{cite web|title=In the mix with Ti\u00ebsto at Madame Tussauds Amsterdam|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=68&step=10&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=27 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227151230/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=68&step=10&pid=NaN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto at Madame Tussauds Amsterdam |url=http://www.madametussauds.com/Amsterdam/en/OnzeBeelden/PopulaireMuzikanten/Tiesto/Default.aspx |publisher=Madame Tussauds |accessdate=29 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923003349/http://www.madametussauds.com/Amsterdam/en/OnzeBeelden/PopulaireMuzikanten/Tiesto/Default.aspx |archivedate=23 September 2009 }}</ref> Stops were made in Ukraine, Slovakia, Serbia, Macedonia, Romania, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Turkey, Croatia, Poland and South Africa. The United States tour that was part of ''[[Ti\u00ebsto in Concert]]'' was dwarfed by his appearance at [[Sensation (event)|Sensation White]] in 2006 where he performed to over 45,000 people in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sensation White 2006|url=http://www.sensation-white.com/portal/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&Itemid=74&limit=14&limitstart=56&lang=en|publisher=[[Sensation (event)|Sensation White]]|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706115516/http://www.sensation-white.com/portal/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&Itemid=74&limit=14&limitstart=56&lang=en|archivedate=6 July 2008}}</ref> The compilation was launched in the [[Winter Music Conference]] in [[Miami Beach]] to support his release, Ti\u00ebsto went on his [[In Search of Sunrise 5 Asia Tour]] for more than three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto to Launch in Search of Sunrise 5: Los Angeles|url=http://www.internetdj.com/article.php?storyid=740|publisher=Internet DJ|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref> In September 2006, Ti\u00ebsto was admitted to hospital after experiencing pain in his chest. He was diagnosed with [[pericarditis]] and subsequently had to cancel a number of shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ti\u00ebsto in Heart Scare |url=http://www.megamindmagazine.com/globalnews/tiesto-in-heart-scare |publisher=Megamind |accessdate=17 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217193645/http://www.megamindmagazine.com/globalnews/tiesto-in-heart-scare |archivedate=17 February 2011 }}</ref> With the diagnosis, he was invited to support [[Dance4Life]] to help teens who are not aware of the risks of [[HIV/AIDS]].\n\n=== 2007\u20132008: ''Elements of Life'' ===\n[[File:Ti\u00ebsto5, Tallinn, 2007.jpg|thumb|200px|Ti\u00ebsto in [[Tallinn]], 2007]]\nOn 6 April 2007, Ti\u00ebsto began presenting a new weekly two-hour radio show called ''[[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life]]'' on Dutch radio station [[Radio 538]]. Ten days later, Ti\u00ebsto released his third studio album ''[[Elements of Life]]''. The album moved 73,000 units in its April release, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref name=\"Night Shift\"/>\n\nDuring the production of the album Ti\u00ebsto in several cases sent a demo with the music to certain artists, and they replied back with the lyrics and vocals and other duration times. In the case of [[Christian Burns]] from [[BBMak]], Ti\u00ebsto met him through [[MySpace]] and contacted him and the production of the single \"[[In the Dark (Ti\u00ebsto song)|In the Dark]]\".<ref name=\"About interview\">{{Cite web |url=http://dancemusic.about.com/od/remixersproducers/a/TiestoEOLInterv.htm |title=Elements of Life interview |publisher=[[About.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615025152/http://dancemusic.about.com/od/remixersproducers/a/TiestoEOLInterv.htm |archive-date=15 June 2011 |access-date=2 August 2008}}</ref> The album consists of [[rock music|rock]], [[trance music|trance]] and [[experimental music]], which shows the style Ti\u00ebsto has grown throughout the years since his previous albums which contained lyrics, ''[[In My Memory]]'' and ''[[Just Be]]''. Producer [[BT (musician)|Brian Transeau]] collaborated with Ti\u00ebsto in three tracks, he composed \"Bright Morningstar\" and \"[[Elements of Life|Sweet Things]]\", and performed the vocals in the single \"[[Break My Fall]]\". Together, they produced more tracks which were not released in the album, Ti\u00ebsto has mentioned they would work again during the coming summer.<ref name=\"About interview\" />\n\n{{external media\n| float = left\n| width = 170px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EE7CXZ1Lyu4 Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Elements of Life (Official Music Video)]\n}}\nIn December 2007 it was announced that the album was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]], in the category \"Best Electronic/Dance Album.\"<ref name=\"grammy nomination\"/> The album also received gold certifications in Belgium, Hungary, Netherlands, and Romania. In support of the album, he embarked on the worldwide [[Elements of Life World Tour]], and released the ''[[Copenhagen: Elements of Life World Tour]]'' DVD in 2008.\n\nTi\u00ebsto announced his residence at [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]]. He played sets in [[Ibiza]] every Monday, from 7 July to 22 September in the style of his [[In Search of Sunrise (series)|''In Search of Sunrise'' series]]. In 2007, he had released ''[[In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza]]'' which was inspired by the island.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residence at Privilege, Ibiza|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=829&step=1&pid=44|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=2 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730172927/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=829&step=1&pid=44|archivedate=30 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April, he released ''[[Elements of Life: Remixed]]'', a recompilation of the ''Elements of Life'' album with all remixed versions. In mid-2008, Ti\u00ebsto announced his [[In Search of Sunrise: Summer Tour 2008]], which was presented by [[Armani Exchange]] in May in support of his [[In Search of Sunrise 7: Asia]] compilation<ref name=\"Armani Summer Tour\"/> and the previously released ''In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza''.\n\n=== 2009\u20132012: ''Kaleidoscope'' and ''Kiss from the Past'' ===\nOn 6 October 2009, he released his fourth studio album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'', which featured artists such as [[Priscilla Ahn]], [[Calvin Harris]], [[Tegan & Sara]] and [[Nelly Furtado]]. Unlike his earlier albums, which were all mostly trance, Kaleidoscope explores other electronic genres, and is considered Tiesto's most experimental album. The first single \"[[I Will Be Here]]\" featuring [[Sneaky Sound System]] being released in July 2009. It reached number three on the much acclaimed Driscoll 5, and lasted there for 24 weeks in the beginning of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.styletraxx.com/2009/03/tisto_is_king_of_the_world.php |title=Tiesto is the King of the World |publisher=Styletraxx |accessdate=22 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327142514/http://www.styletraxx.com/2009/03/tisto_is_king_of_the_world.php |archivedate=27 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/the-business-of-life/entertainment/king-of-spin-does-the-biz-2009-03-13-1.94566|title=King of Spin Does the Biz|publisher=Rachel McArthur Emirates Business 24-7|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/08/entertainment/et-fave8|title=L.A. scene inspires his sound|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=8 May 2009|first=Mark|last=Sachs}}</ref> In its first week, the album reached the Top 10 chart on [[iTunes]].<ref name=\"clichemag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clichemag.com/issue08|title=Clich\u00e9Magazine \u2013 Issue 08|publisher=Clichemag.com|accessdate=23 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227093815/http://www.clichemag.com/issue08/|archivedate=27 February 2010}}</ref> To release the album he set up a new record label called Musical Freedom after parting ways with [[Black Hole Recordings]]. Ti\u00ebsto felt that his music was evolving in a new direction and his focus as an artist was moving away from what Black Hole was set up to support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hangout.altsounds.com/news/109776-ti-sto-signs-pias-deal-australia-zealand.html |title=Ti\u00ebsto signs deal&nbsp;\u2014 Australia & New Zealand |publisher=Altsounds.com |accessdate=19 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606142350/http://hangout.altsounds.com/news/109776-ti-sto-signs-pias-deal-australia-zealand.html |archivedate=6 June 2012 }}</ref> His new tour, sharing the name of his new album, called [[Kaleidoscope World Tour]] commenced in late September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2009/07/23/680879.aspx|title=Ti\u00ebsto Conquers The World|publisher=Pollstar.com|accessdate=23 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725085903/http://pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2009/07/23/680879.aspx|archivedate=25 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2010, he released a greatest hits album, ''[[Magikal Journey|Magikal Journey: The Hits Collection 1998\u20132008]]'', a two disc album focusing on his most famous songs and remixes of his songs. On 7 April, he announced that he would start a new compilation series called ''A New Dawn'' with his own label Musical Freedom. In his interview Ti\u00ebsto furthermore confirmed that he would no longer have any more involvement with Black Hole Recordings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixmag.net/content/tiesto-announces-new-mix-album-series-new-dawn|title=Tiesto Announces New Mix Album Series \u2013 'A New Dawn'|work=Mixmag|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=9 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909210122/http://www.mixmag.net/content/tiesto-announces-new-mix-album-series-new-dawn}}</ref> On 31 August, ''[[Kaleidoscope: Remixed]]'' was released, a remix album of his album ''Kaleidoscope''.\n\nAlso in 2009 and 2010, Ti\u00ebsto contributed songs to both the ''[[DJ Hero]]'' and ''[[DJ Hero 2]]'' video games and is a playable character in the second game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6217443.html |title=Daft Punk mixing up DJ Hero |publisher=GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124021332/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6217443.html |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/6274493.html?tag=result%3Btitle%3B0 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731161901/http://www.gamespot.com/news/6274493.html?tag=result;title;0 |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |title=DJ Hero 2 spinning 105 songs |publisher=Gamespot.com |accessdate=13 August 2010 }}</ref> He also produced a trance-flavored song for Memphis rap duo [[Three 6 Mafia]]'s album called \"[[Feel It (Three 6 Mafia song)|Feel It]]\", which features [[Sean Kingston]] and [[Flo Rida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267845/three-6-mafia-lays-down-laws-of-power|title=Three 6 Mafia Lays Down 'Laws of Power'|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tiesto 2012.jpg|thumb|260px|Ti\u00ebsto performing at the 2012 [[Consumer Electronics Show]]]]\nOn 4 April 2011, his mix compilation ''[[Club Life: Volume One Las Vegas]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471904576229122190118978?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Ti\u00ebsto: Electronic Music's Superstar|accessdate=5 April 2011|work=The Wall Street Journal|first=Jim|last=Fusilli|date=30 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/intl/49559/Tiestos_new_style_at_work_on_Club_Life_mixCD|title=Tiesto's \"new style\" at work on 'Club Life' mix-CD|accessdate=5 April 2011}}</ref> On 13 June, his studio album, ''[[Kiss from the Past]]'', was released under his alias Allure, and featured [[Christian Burns]], [[Jes Brieden|JES]], and [[Emma Hewitt]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiss From The Past|url=http://www.beatport.com/release/kiss-from-the-past/381943|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, satellite radio broadcaster [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio|Sirius XM]] launched [[Ti\u00ebsto's Club Life Radio]], one of five dance/electronic stations on the platform. Programming was \"curated by Ti\u00ebsto himself<ref>{{cite web |title=Tiesto's Club Life Radio Channel to Launch from Miami Music Week on SiriusXM |url=http://investor.siriusxm.com/investor-overview/press-releases/press-release-details/2012/Tiestos-Club-Life-Radio-Channel-to-Launch-from-Miami-Music-Week-on-SiriusXM/default.aspx |website=investor.siriusxm.com |accessdate=18 November 2018 |language=en-CA}}</ref>\". The station ran until 2017.\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: ''Club Life'' and ''A Town Called Paradise''===\n{{external media\n| float = left\n| width = 170px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CFF0mV24WCY Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Red Lights (Official Music Video)]\n}}\n''[[Club Life: Volume Three Stockholm]]'' was released worldwide physically on 25 June 2013 and it hit No. 16 on the Billboard Top 200 Chart. He followed up his third \"Club Life\" installment with the 2014 effort, ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]''. The album featured an assortment of guest stars and was preceded by two singles, \"[[Red Lights (song)|Red Lights]]\" and \"[[Wasted (Ti\u00ebsto song)|Wasted]]\" \u2013 yielding his first two gold singles in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electronic.vegas/news/tiesto-celebrates-gold-certified-singles-hakkasan-gold-party/|title=Tiesto celebrates two gold-certified singles at Hakkasan Gold Party|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> A medley from the album also soundtracks a presentation at the [[Bellagio (resort)]] fountain in Las Vegas, a first for a dance music artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.bellagio.com/bellagio/latest-news/fountains-of-bellagio-learn-new-dance-to-hits-by-famed-djproducer-tisto.htm|title=Fountains of Bellagio Learn New Dance to Hits by Famed DJ/Producer Ti\u00ebsto \u2013 Bellagio Resort & Casino|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 interview with ''[[DJ Magazine]]'', Ti\u00ebsto revealed why he left trance music. When asked whether his decision to leave the genre was influential to his popularity in the United States, the Dutch producer said: \"Maybe, it's hard to say. I think I'd still be the 'Tiesto trance guy' but the difference is you're not really being relevant. Some of the old trance guys still have their following but it doesn't feel like anybody really cares \u2013 and that's the biggest difference. It's nice to be in touch with the new kids who are coming up \u2013 the 16 and 18-year olds who are producing house music see me as kind of a godfather, and it's really cool to be in touch with them. I think if I'd still been a trance DJ, they'd have been so disconnected with that sound that I wouldn't be much inspiration for them, and vice versa.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3khHSmbrBqs | title=Tiesto: \"Why I left trance\" | publisher=[[DJ Magazine]] | date=10 April 2014 | accessdate=23 October 2016 | author=DJ Magazine | website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], he won the [[Grammy Award for Best Remixed Recording, Non-Classical]] for his remixed version of [[John Legend]]'s hit \"[[All of Me (John Legend song)|All of Me]]\".<ref name=\"grammy\"/> The same year his fourth installment of the Club Life compilation series, titled ''[[Club Life: Volume Four New York City]]'', was released through Musical Freedom. In April 2016, he launched a [[deep house]] label, AFTR:HRS, to promote deep house music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7341834/tiesto-aftrhrs-label-deep-house-blr-nungwi|title=Ti\u00ebsto Launches AFTR:HRS Deep House Sub-Label, Premieres BLR's 'Nungwi': Exclusive|first=Elias|last=Leight|date=25 April 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2016/04/26/tiesto-unveils-sub-label-aftrhrs-inaugural-track/|title=Ti\u00ebsto Unveils Sub-Label AFTR:HRS with Inaugural Track|first=Cameron|last=Gregg|date=26 April 2016|website=Your EDM|access-date=15 July 2016}}</ref> He appeared in the 2016 [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated documentary film about American DJ and producer [[Steve Aoki]], titled ''[[I'll Sleep When I'm Dead (2016 film)|I'll Sleep When I'm Dead]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/steve-aoki-ill-sleep-when-im-dead-documentary-hits-netflix/|title=Steve Aoki 'I'll Sleep When I'm Dead' Documentary Hits Netflix {{!}} The Nocturnal Times|website=www.thenocturnaltimes.com|access-date=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2017, Ti\u00ebsto was awarded the key to the city of [[Las Vegas]]. The day is now known as \"Ti\u00ebsto Day\" in [[Clark County, Nevada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7655127/tiesto-on-my-way|title=Tiesto Seizes the New Year and Celebrates His Birthday With 'On My Way'|publisher=[[Billboard magazine]]|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref> He was featured in the 2017 documentary starring [[Carl Cox]] and [[Martin Garrix]], titled ''[[What We Started]]''''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-what-we-started-filmmakers-talk-world-premiere-and-the-evolu-119767|title=Interview: 'What We Started' filmmakers talk world premiere and the evolution of EDM|work=AXS|access-date=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 October 2017, the fifth installment of the Club Life series entitled '[[ClubLife, Vol. 5 - China]]' was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edmtunes.com/2017/10/tiesto-releases-clublife-vol-5-china/|title=Tiesto Releases Super Amped Up 'Clublife' Vol.5 China |first=Michael|last=Tam|date=6 October 2017|publisher=EDM Tunes|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref> The compilation album features tracks by John Christian, SWACQ, Ti\u00ebsto and Z.Tao, and collaborations between Ti\u00ebsto and Aloe Blacc, John Christian, [[Dzeko (DJ)|Dzeko]], Diplo, KSHMR, Talay Riley, Sevenn, Stargate, SWACQ and Vassy.\n\nIn March 2018, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' named Tiesto as number eight on their 2018 ranking of dance musicians titled Billboard Dance 100.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8257429/billboard-dance-100-2018 |title=Billboard Dance 100 Artists of 2018: The Complete List |website=Billboard |access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wjbdradio.com/music-news/2018/03/22/the-chainsmokers-named-top-djs-in-the-world-by-billboard |title=The Chainsmokers named top DJs in the world by Billboard |website=WJBD Radio |access-date=23 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322221157/http://www.wjbdradio.com/music-news/2018/03/22/the-chainsmokers-named-top-djs-in-the-world-by-billboard |archive-date=22 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2018, Ti\u00ebsto released his debut EP titled ''[[I Like It Loud (EP)|I Like It Loud]]'', featuring four songs that are collaborations with artists such as [[John Christian (musician)|John Christian]], [[Mesto]], [[Matisse & Sadko]] and [[MOTi]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8260989/tiesto-john-christian-i-like-it-loud-listen |title=Tiesto & John Christian Turn It Up on 'I Like It Loud': Listen |website=Billboard |access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2018, Ti\u00ebsto collaborated with [[Dzeko (DJ)|Dzeko]], [[Post Malone]] and [[Preme]] on a track titled \"[[Jackie Chan (song)|Jackie Chan]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463601/tiesto-jackie-chan-video-dzeko-post-malone-preme|title=Tiesto, Dzeko, Post Malone & Preme Find Adventure in 'Jackie Chan': Watch|work=Billboard|access-date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2019, Ti\u00ebsto released his remix of [[Avicii|Avicii's]] posthumous \"Tough Love\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cultr.com/news/avicii-tough-love-tiesto-remix|title=Ti\u00ebsto Has Officially Released His Remix of Avicii's Posthumous 'Tough Love' |website=Cultr |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Income==\nIn 2016, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated that Ti\u00ebsto's annual income was $39 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/tiesto/?list=celebrities |title=Ti\u00ebsto |work=[[Forbes]] |year=2015 |accessdate=28 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nOn 6 January 2005, Ti\u00ebsto performed in an outdoor fundraiser in De Dam, Amsterdam. The free event involved Dutch artists like [[Dinand Woesthoff]], [[BL\u00d8F]], [[Acda en De Munnik|Acda & De Munnik]], [[Di-rect]], and [[Trijntje Oosterhuis]] were involved in it to provide financial aid to the people who suffered from the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]] in [[South Asia|southern]] and [[Southeast Asia|southeastern Asia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto closes fundraiser in the Netherlands for Asian tsunami victims|url=http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=71&step=10&pid=NaN|publisher=Tiesto.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=27 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227151243/http://www.tiesto.com/content/tpl_news.asp?nid=71&step=10&pid=NaN}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, Ti\u00ebsto was named the official worldwide ambassador for the [[Dance4Life]] foundation promoting awareness of [[HIV/AIDS]], as the foundation's ambassador he has helped the organisation with fundraising along with recording the track \"[[Dance4life (song)|Dance4life]]\" that he recorded with [[Maxi Jazz]] from [[Faithless]]. The foundation consists on a better way of living with safe sex in exchange of entertainment to the young crowd.<ref name=\"dance4life\">{{cite web|title=Ti\u00ebsto new ambassador of Dance4Life|url=http://www.dance4life.com/en_4life_news_article/2160|publisher=dance4life.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|archivedate=8 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708224352/http://www.dance4life.com/en_4life_news_article/2160}}</ref> The song was a huge success, peaking for five weeks in number 3 and eleven consecutive weeks in the Top 10 of the [[Dutch Top 40|Dutch Singles Chart]], it reached number 5 in Belgium, number 6 in Finland and also charting in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] and Germany.\n\nWith the successful release of ''[[Elements of Life]]'', Ti\u00ebsto and fashion designer [[Giorgio Armani]] collaborated on a limited edition Ti\u00ebsto T-shirt available at Armani Exchange stores. His single \"[[Elements of Life|Sweet Things]]\" comes with the shirt including an exclusive \"A|X Remix\" by Tom Cloud which shows the great influence Ti\u00ebsto has in fashion culture.<ref name=\"mercy\">{{cite web |title=Armani Exchange and Ti\u00ebsto team up to \"Remix the future\" and support mercy corps |url=http://www.styletraxx.com/2007/12/armani_exchange_and_tiesto_tea.php |publisher=Styletraxx |accessdate=23 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080318155525/http://www.styletraxx.com/2007/12/armani_exchange_and_tiesto_tea.php |archivedate=18 March 2008 }}</ref> The charity raised over U.S. $300,000.<ref name=\"Armani Summer Tour\">{{cite web|title=Armani Onboard With Tiesto For Summer Tour|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/news/e3i1155cb8195120add4b2d93ba82aeb65c|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Ti\u00ebsto released a compilation album ''Dance (RED) Save Lives'' in collaboration with [[Product Red]], with the aim of donating any proceeds from the album to the fight against AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joinred.com/press_releases/tiesto-joins-with-red-to-engage-the-dance-music-community-in-the-fight-against-aids |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618175659/http://www.joinred.com/press_releases/tiesto-joins-with-red-to-engage-the-dance-music-community-in-the-fight-against-aids/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 June 2013 |title=Press |publisher=Joinred.com |accessdate=23 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Ti\u00ebsto headlined the first-ever Thank You Festival, presented by Global Citizen in partnership with [[World Childhood Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/6041168/tiesto-above-beyond-to-perform-at-global-citizens-thank-you-festival|title=Ti\u00ebsto, Above & Beyond To Perform at Global Citizen's Thank You Festival|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> As a part of the festival campaign, Ti\u00ebsto took part in supporting ThankYou.org. For every song shared, the Carlson Family Foundation donated $5 to the World Childhood Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiestoblog.com/tiesto-thankyou-childhood-campaign/|title=Ti\u00ebsto for the ThankYou by Childhood Campaign \u2013 Ti\u00ebsto Blog|date=27 June 2014|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Ti\u00ebsto headlined the free [[Global Citizen Festival]] in New York's Central Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/jay-z-no-doubt-tiesto-set-to-headline-free-global-citizen-festival-20140709|title=Jay Z, No Doubt, Ti\u00ebsto Set to Headline Free Global Citizen Festival|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Ti\u00ebsto discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[In My Memory]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Just Be]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Elements of Life]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Kaleidoscope (Ti\u00ebsto album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[A Town Called Paradise]]'' (2014)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Ti\u00ebsto}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|q=Ti\u00ebsto|s=no|commons=Category:Ti\u00ebsto|n=no|v=no|species=no}}\n* {{official website|http://www.tiesto.com/}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Digweed]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[DJ Magazine]] Number 1 DJ|years=2002\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Van Dyk]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Ti\u00ebsto}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Ti\u00ebsto \n| list =\n{{DJ Mag Top 100 DJs Poll \u2212 No 1 DJ|state=collapsed}} \n{{DJ Award for Best Electro DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best International DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best Progressive and Progressive House DJ|state=collapsed}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiesto}}\n[[Category:Ti\u00ebsto| ]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Club DJs]]\n[[Category:Dutch dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Dutch DJs]]\n[[Category:Dutch record producers]]\n[[Category:Dutch house musicians]]\n[[Category:Dutch trance musicians]]\n[[Category:Eurodance musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Breda]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Ultra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Orange-Nassau]]\n[[Category:Progressive house musicians]]\n[[Category:Future house musicians]]\n[[Category:Revealed Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:9c67:fb00:3dca:6fd2:25d1:ddca", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ti%C3%ABsto"}
{"title_page": "Adrian Fenty", "text_new": "{{short description|Sixth mayor of the District of Columbia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Adrian Fenty\n|image = Adrian Fenty, Mayor of DC, November 5, 2007.jpg\n|office = 5th [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]\n|term_start = January 2, 2007\n|term_end = January 2, 2011\n|predecessor = [[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams]]\n|successor = [[Vincent C. Gray|Vincent Gray]]\n|office1 = Member of the <br>[[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />from Ward 4\n|term_start1 = January 3, 2001\n|term_end1 = January 2, 2007\n|predecessor1 = [[Charlene Drew Jarvis]]\n|successor1 = [[Muriel Bowser]]\n|birth_name = Adrian Malik Fenty\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|12|6}}\n|birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse = Michelle Cross (separated)\n|children = 3\n|education = [[Oberlin College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Howard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|signature = Adrian Fenty Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Adrian Malik Fenty''' (born December 6, 1970)<ref name=\"voters guide\"/> is an American politician who served as the sixth [[mayor of the District of Columbia]].<ref name=\"new mayor\"/> He served one term, from 2007 to 2011, losing his bid for reelection at the primary level to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Vincent C. Gray]]. Though Fenty won the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] mayoral primary as a [[write-in candidate]], he declined the Republican nomination and said he would likely not seek elected office again. Gray went on to win the general election for Mayor in the largely Democratic District.\n\nSince leaving office, Fenty has become a special advisor to the venture capital firm, [[Andreessen Horowitz]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://techcrunch.com/2012/09/26/andreessen-horowitz-hires-former-d-c-mayor-adrian-fenty-to-be-its-newest-special-advisor/ |title=Andreessen Horowitz Hires Former D.C. Mayor Adrian Fenty To Be Its Newest Special Advisor |first=Colleen |last=Taylor |work=TechCrunch |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> and a member of the business development team at the law firm [[Perkins Coie]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.perkinscoie.com/adrian-fenty-joins-perkins-coie-in-silicon-valley-09-24-2013/ |title=Adrian Fenty Joins Perkins Coie in Silicon Valley |work=perkinscoie.com |date=September 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> Fenty has held advisory and business development roles with Rosetta Stone, Everfi and CapGemini. He also serves on the Board of Directors at two nonprofits: Genesys Works-Bay Area and Fight for Children.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/324277-ex-dc-mayor-fenty-joins-perkins-coie |title=Ex-DC Mayor Fenty joins Perkins Coie  |first=Megan R. |last=Wilson |work=The Hill |date=September 24, 2013 |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> He has also embarked on a career as a paid speaker, part-time college professor, adviser for the state and local government practice of an information technology consulting firm. Previously, Fenty was a [[Council of the District of Columbia|D.C. Council]] member for six years. A Washington, D.C., native, Fenty is a graduate of [[Oberlin College]] and [[Howard University Law School]].\n\n==Early life, education, and family==\nFenty was born in Washington, D.C., the second of the three children of Jeanette Bianchi Perno Fenty and Phil Fenty.<ref name=dn/> Fenty's mother is [[Italian-American]].<ref name=ciao/> Her family immigrated to the [[United States]] from the [[comune]] of [[Monte San Giovanni Campano]] in [[Lazio]] in 1920.<ref name=ciao/> His father, who is originally from [[Buffalo, New York]], has roots in [[Barbados]] and [[Panama]].<ref name=dn/><ref name=ciao/> Phil and Jeanette Fenty moved to Washington, D.C., in 1967.<ref name=ciao/> Fenty was raised in the [[Mount Pleasant, Washington, D.C.|Mount Pleasant]] neighborhood.<ref name=\"fleet feet\"/> While he was growing up, his parents owned and ran a Fleet Feet athletic shoe store in the D.C. neighborhood of [[Adams Morgan]].<ref name=\"fleet feet 2\"/><ref name=\"fleet feet\"/>\n\nFenty graduated from [[Archbishop Carroll High School (Washington, DC)#Background|Mackin Catholic High School]],<ref name=\"Jaffee 11-2008\"/> where he ran track.<ref>{{cite news |title= Roberts Wins 4 Races; Suitland Boys Prevail For P.G. County Title |first1= Donald |last1= Huff |first2= Anthony |last2= Powell |first3= Jon |last3= Wilner |work= The Washington Post |date= May 10, 1987 |page= C2 |id= {{ProQuest|306904076}} }}</ref> He earned a [[B.A.]] in English and economics from [[Oberlin College]], and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from the [[Howard University School of Law]].<ref name=\"about adrian\"/> He remains a member of [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity.<ref name=\"kwame promotes\"/>\n\n==Early political career==\nBefore becoming involved in local D.C. politics, Fenty worked as an intern for U.S.&nbsp;Senator [[Howard Metzenbaum]] (D-OH), U.S. House of Representatives D.C. Delegate [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] (D-DC), and U.S. Representative [[Joseph P. Kennedy&nbsp;II]] (D-MA).\n\nHe then served as an aide to Councilmember [[Kevin P. Chavous]],<ref>{{cite news |title= Suspicions on the Council |first1= Michael H. |last= Cottman |first2= Vanessa |last2= Williams |work= The Washington Post |page= J01 |date= February 3, 2000 |id= {{ProQuest|408582400}} }}</ref> was elected to the [[Advisory Neighborhood Commission]] (ANC), district 4C, and also was president of the 16th Street Neighborhood Civic Association.\n\n==D.C. Council==\nIn 2000, Fenty won a seat on the [[Council of the District of Columbia|D.C. Council]], defeating longtime Ward 4 Councilmember [[Charlene Drew Jarvis]] by a margin of 57 to 43 percent after engaging in an aggressive door-to-door strategy.<ref name=\"jarvis ousted\"/><ref name=2000p/><ref name=2000g/> Unopposed in both the primary and general elections in 2004, Fenty was reelected for a second term.<ref name=2004p/><ref name=2004g/>\n\n''The Washington Post'' described Fenty's performance as a Council member as \"independent\" and \"contrarian\".<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> During his time on the Council, he opposed public funding for a new baseball stadium, saying the owners should pay for it.<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> He proposed a $1&nbsp;billion capital improvement program for the public schools\u2014which the Council initially opposed, but eventually passed.<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> According to the Washington Post, Fenty's legislative style was to focus on constituent services and take attention grabbing positions.<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/>\n\n[[Image:Adrian Fenty, 2006.jpg|thumb|right|Adrian Fenty, December 2006]]\n\n==2006 mayoral campaign==\n{{See also|2006 Washington, D.C. mayoral election}}\nFenty began his campaign to replace retiring mayor [[Anthony A. Williams]] in 2005. Then-Council Chair [[Linda W. Cropp|Linda Cropp]], businesswoman Marie Johns, then-Councilmember [[Vincent Orange]], and lobbyist [[Michael A. Brown (Washington, D.C. politician)|Michael A. Brown]] also vied for the position.\n\nThe race was widely viewed as neck-and-neck between Fenty and Cropp through the spring of 2006. Fenty ran on a platform of bringing a more energetic and hands-on approach to city government,{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}, advancing bold ideas for change, and sticking to them.<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> Fenty said he would take his uncompromising style to the mayor's office, and cited with approval, Margaret Thatcher's saying that, \"Consensus is the absence of leadership\".<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> Cropp stressed her 25 years of experience in city government and her desire to continue the progress made by Anthony Williams, who endorsed her candidacy.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} She also stressed her ability to cooperate with diverse groups and reach consensus. She criticized Fenty's proposed approach to governing; being mayor, saying the mayor's job is \"not just standing up and saying, 'This is what I want done,' and miraculously it's going to happen.\"<ref name=\"cropp and fenty\"/> Both candidates raised significant and nearly equal amounts of money&nbsp;\u2013 roughly $1.75 million through June 10, 2006<ref name=\"vocal critic\"/>&nbsp;\u2013 and neither gained any significant advantages from the numerous candidate debates and forums.\n\nBy July 2006 polls showed Fenty with a roughly 10-point advantage;<ref name=\"fenty emerges\"/> political observers debated whether it was due to Fenty's door-to-door campaign, Cropp's lack of engagement in the campaign, or the electorate's desire for a new direction. Cropp's campaign began running [[Negative campaigning|negative attack ads]] during the month before the primary, painting Fenty as unfit for the job and as a careless lawyer who had been admonished by the D.C. Bar,<ref name=\"new cropp\"/> (in 2005, he received an informal admonition from the Bar for his role in a probate case in 1999). The attacks backfired. Fenty won all 142 city precincts in the Democratic Primary\u2014a feat unparalleled in earlier mayoral elections<ref name=\"fenty draws\"/>\u2014defeating Cropp by a 57 to 31 percent margin.<ref name=2006p/> He received 89 percent of the vote in the general election<ref name=\"2006 local elections\"/><ref name=2006g/> and became the District's sixth elected [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.|mayor]] since the establishment of [[District of Columbia home rule|home rule]].\n\n==D.C. mayor (2007\u201311)==\n[[File:20070917 Jack Kemp, Adrian Fenty and Eleanor Holmes Norton.jpg|thumb|[[Jack Kemp]], Fenty, and [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] at D.C. Vote rally on [[Capitol Hill]]]]\nEducation reform was a major focus of Fenty's mayoral tenure. On the first day of his term, he introduced legislation to vest control of the public schools in himself, rather than the elected school board. Previous attempts to reform the schools, including one in 1996 where a D.C. financial control board took charge of the schools, had failed.<ref name=\"board takes charge\"/> At the beginning of Fenty's term, student test performance scores and graduation rates were among the lowest in the nation and District residents had been demanding that the schools be \"fixed\".<ref name=\"on DC politics\"/> In April 2007, the D.C.&nbsp;Council approved Fenty's plan;<ref name=\"takeover approved\"/> the necessary legislation was approved by the U.S.&nbsp;Congress and signed into law by President George W. Bush in May 2007.<ref name=\"school takeover\"/>\n\nUnder the new structure, the existing superintendent was replaced by a chancellor selected by the mayor and reporting directly to him.<ref name=\"oust\"/> The power shift also allowed Fenty to make swift changes in the system's central office, alter teacher qualification requirements, and implement a school consolidation process.<ref name=\"dc.gov\"/><ref name=\"public schools\"/> His selection of [[Michelle Rhee]] to manage District schools surprised the education establishment. In choosing Rhee, Fenty consulted with national education figures including [[New York City School Chancellor]], [[Joel Klein]].<ref name=\"oust\"/>\n\nThe restructuring has been credited with improvements.<ref name=\"show progress\"/> To better allocate resources, Fenty and Rhee significantly reduced the school system's central administrative staff and closed 23 schools with low enrollments.<ref name=\"Adrian Fenty and Michelle Rhee\"/> After 2007, student achievement tests at the secondary level reportedly rose 14&nbsp;points in reading and 17&nbsp;points in math. Student SAT scores rose 27&nbsp;points in 2010.<ref name=\"Adrian Fenty and Michelle Rhee\"/> Graduation rates rose each year since 2007, and 72 percent of District students took the [[PSAT/NMSQT|Preliminary Scholastic Aptitude Test]] (PSAT),<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://dc.gov/mayor/news/release.asp?id=1875&mon=201004 Mayor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527153034/http://dc.gov/mayor/news/release.asp?id=1875&mon=201004 |date=2010-05-27 }}. Dc.gov. Retrieved on 2010-11-13.</ref> which functions as a practice test for college bound students.<ref name=\"psat\"/> Fenty's administration had also taken on a major, five-year maintenance and construction effort to improve school buildings by 2014.<ref name=\"dc.gov\"/> Fenty and Rhee successfully negotiated a collective bargaining agreement with the Washington Teachers Union that establishes a system of performance-based teacher compensation.<ref name=\"Adrian Fenty and Michelle Rhee\"/>\n\nThe Fenty administration also overhauled District agencies for efficiency.<ref name=\"wapo8-28-10\"/> His choice of a woman for police chief, [[Cathy Lanier]], received media attention.<ref name=\"chief\"/> Under Fenty, Lanier added police officers to the streets and expanded community policing initiatives, for example, \"beefing up\" the policy of accepting anonymous [[text message]] tips from local residents to cut down on potential retaliation.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The homicide rate in the District dropped 25% in 2009;<ref name=\"murder rate\"/> the homicide closure rate rose to 70%.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> with Fenty reporting that homicides were at their \"lowest level since 1964\" and that \"both violent crimes and property crimes\" had experienced a double-digit decline.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nFenty championed development efforts including renovating libraries, parks and recreation centers. Under Fenty, 16 neighborhood and school playgrounds were opened and nine play courts and fields were completed.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The District's largest shopping center, the DC USA Shopping Center, and the Camp Simms retail development were opened, and thousands of affordable housing units were established or renovated.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} The \"Housing First\" program to provide permanent supportive housing for the city's homeless was begun. The backlog of Child Protective Services (CPS) investigations was reduced by improving the retention of social workers, building an experienced leadership team, and increasing the recruitment of social workers to fill vacancies. Additionally, the Fenty administration improved the delivery of emergency medical services and expanded health care coverage for the uninsured. It also finalized the sale of Greater Southeast Community Hospital (now United Medical Center) in a public-private partnership that kept the facility open.<ref name=\"dc.gov\"/>\n\nIn December 2009, Fenty signed the Religious Freedom and Civil Marriage Equality Act of 2009 to legalize [[same-sex marriage]] in the District of Columbia.<ref name=\"same sex\"/>\n\nWhile serving as mayor, Fenty was a member of the [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]],<ref name=\"against guns\"/> an organization formed in 2006 and co-chaired by [[New York City]] mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] and [[Boston]] mayor [[Thomas Menino]]. Fenty was known to carry three [[BlackBerry]] devices: one directly connected him to the police chief, the second was for other city business, and the third was for personal matters.<ref name=\"blackberry\"/>\n\n===2010 re-election campaign===\n{{see also|Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 2010}}\nOn July 31, 2009, Fenty's 2010 mayoral campaign chest passed the 2006 primary fundraising total of $2.4 million.<ref name=\"fatigue\"/> Fenty officially launched his reelection bid in April 2010, defending his management style and pledging to remind voters that had made the types of tough decisions that are necessary for real change.<ref name=\"DC Mayor Begins Campaign For Second Term\"/>\n\nOn August 1, 2010, the editorial board of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' officially endorsed Fenty, citing his attempts to fix the District's struggling public school system.<ref name=\"editorial\"/> ''[[Washington City Paper]]'' followed on September 9.<ref name=\"editorial 1\"/>\n\nJanuary 2010 hypothetical polling showed Gray in the lead by 4 points;<ref name=\"approval ratings\"/> a ''Washington Post'' poll of August 29 found Gray with a 17-point lead;<ref name=\"wapo poll\"/> a Clarus poll conducted September 7 gave Gray a 7-point lead;<ref name=\"second poll\"/> and a [[Public Policy Polling]] survey sponsored by [[WAMU-FM]] radio and ''Washington City Paper'' showed an 11 percent lead for Gray on September 8.<ref name=\"gray leads\"/>\n\nFenty lost the September 14 Democratic primary to Gray by a margin of 10 points\u201454 percent to 44 percent.<ref name=defeats/> While Fenty received the most write-in votes for mayor in the Republican primary election, Fenty had previously said he would not accept the Republican nomination.<ref name=republican/> Following the reporting of the primary results, Fenty called it highly unlikely he will run for public office again.<ref name=\"pledges support\"/>\n\nIn August 2011 an investigation into the hiring practices of Mayor Vincent Gray found that during the 2010 primary, a Gray campaign official had paid another candidate, Sulaimon Brown, to disparage Fenty.<ref name=\"faults gray\"/>\n\n====Forward Faster====\nFenty, like all District mayors and council members, had a citizen-service fund that is intended to help the residents of the District of Columbia.<ref name= gives>{{cite news |title= Fenty gives $440K to nonprofit launched by campaign strategist |work= Washington Business Journal |first= Michael |last= Neibauer |date= April 11, 2011 |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/2011/04/fenty-gives-440k-to-mystery-group.html }}</ref> Much of the cash held by the fund came from the money raised during his 2006 mayoral candidacy.<ref name= gives/>\n\nUpon leaving office, District law required Fenty to donate the remaining funds in his citizen-service fund to a [[Nonprofit organization#United States|nonprofit organization]]. Two weeks prior to Fenty's last day as mayor, his chief campaign fundraiser, John Falcicchio, incorporated a [[501(c)(4)|social welfare organization]] called Forward Faster as a legacy organization to carry out Fenty's vision.<ref name= board>{{cite news |title= Fenty friends, but not Fenty, on nonprofit board |date= Apr 13, 2011 |first= Michael |last= Neibauer |work= Washington Business Journal |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/2011/04/fenty-friends-but-not-fenty-on.html }}</ref> Fenty donated the $440,709 remaining in his citizen-service fund to Forward Faster.<ref name= gives/>\n\nForward Faster's board of directors consists of Falcicchio; George Simpson, Fenty's appointee to the [[National Capital Planning Commission]]); Sara Lasner, a former aide to Fenty; and Jason Washington, a former Fenty advance man.<ref name= board/> During its first year of existence, Forward Faster spent $88,700 on grants; $88,000 of salary to John Falcicchio as executive director; $49,500 to Tracy Sandler, also as executive director; and $3,000 to Jennifer Nguyen, also as another executive director.<ref name= former>{{cite news |title=Former staffers leading beneficiaries of Fenty's Forward Faster nonprofit |first= Michael |last= Neibauer |date= November 17, 2014 |work= Washington Business Journal |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/2014/11/former-staffersleading-beneficiaries-of-fentys.html?page=all }}</ref>\n\nBy 2013, Simpson, Lasner, and Washington were no longer connected to the organization.<ref>{{cite news |title= Fenty's Forward Faster files report, remains an enigma |work= Washington Business Journal |first= Michael |last= Neibauer |date= September 16, 2013 |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/2013/09/fentys-forward-faster-files-report.html }}</ref>\n\nSince then, District law was changed to prohibit an elected official from incorporating a nonprofit organization at the end of his or her term in office and transferring constituent services fund money into it.<ref name= former/>\n\n==Post-mayoral life==\nAfter his term as mayor was over, Fenty signed with [[Greater Talent Network (GTN)|Greater Talent Network]], a major speakers bureau, in January 2011.<ref name=\"speakers bureau\"/> The same month, Fenty became an outside adviser and counsel to Heffler, Radetich & Saitta, an accounting and consulting firm based in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"lands gig\"/> Also in January 2011, it was announced that Fenty would become a distinguished visiting professor of politics, a featured lecturer and a career adviser in the Department of African American Studies at Oberlin College in Ohio.<ref name=\"oberlin\"/> In February 2011, Fenty became an outside adviser to [[Rosetta Stone (company)|Rosetta Stone]], which produces foreign-language software.<ref name=\"rosetta stone\"/> In March 2011, Fenty became a strategic adviser for the state and local government practice of Capgemini Government Solutions LLC, an information technology consulting firm.<ref name=\"tapped\"/> In May 2011, Fenty became a member of the advisory board of EverFi Inc., an online education and certification firm.<ref name=\"joins D.C.\"/> In July 2011, Fenty joined the plaintiff and litigation oriented law firm of Klores Perry Mitchell as special counsel.<ref name=\"joins law firm\"/>\n\nOn ''[[Morning Joe]]'' on March 8, 2011, Fenty backed Wisconsin Republican Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]]'s [[Scott Walker (politician)#Right to work|anti-union efforts]] and broadly condemned the concept of public employee [[collective bargaining]].<ref name=\"backs walker\"/> Saying that \"Most governors and mayors would love to be able to manage their team without the interference of collective bargaining\", Fenty expressed his faith in the ability of managers to set fair wages and hours, and to fairly reward or hold their employees accountable.<ref name=\"backs walker\"/> He also said that the Democratic Wisconsin senators should be held accountable for leaving the state to delay the enactment of Walker's legislation.<ref name=\"backs walker\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1997, Fenty married Michelle Cross Fenty, an attorney. The couple have three children\u2014twin sons Andrew and Matthew born in 2000, and daughter Aerin born in 2008.<ref name=\"baby\"/> In January 2013, the couple officially separated.<ref name=\"Laurene\">{{cite news|last1=Warren|first1=Lydia|title=Steve Jobs' billionaire widow Laurene Powell and new love ex-DC mayor Adrian Fenty take island shopping trip during Caribbean vacation|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2920090/Steve-Jobs-billionaire-widow-Laurene-Powell-new-love-ex-DC-mayor-Adrian-Fenty-island-shopping-trip-Caribbean-vacation.html|accessdate=26 July 2017|work=Daily Mail|date=21 January 2015}}</ref> Andrew is a tennis player who achieved a national [[junior tennis]] rank of 4 before starting at the [[University of Michigan]] in 2018 where he earned Freshman of the Year status from the [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association]] and the [[Big Ten Conference]], and was named the [[NCAA]]'s [[Rookie of the Year (award)|Rookie of the Year]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/06/30/andrew-adrian-fenty-dc-tennis-citi-open/ |title=Adrian Fenty's Son Andrew Wants to Be the Next Big Tennis Star |date=June 30, 2017 |magazine=Washingtonian |first=Xander |last=Peters |access-date=February 11, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennisrecruiting.net/player.asp?id=728842 |title=Andrew Fenty |website=Tennis Recruiting Network |access-date=February 11, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.michigandaily.com/section/mens-tennis/andrew-fenty-growing |title=Andrew Fenty is growing up |date=January 14, 2020 |newspaper=The Michigan Daily |first=Jared |last=Greenspan |access-date=February 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, the Washington Post reported that Fenty was in a relationship with [[Laurene Powell Jobs]]. Powell Jobs, widow of Apple co-founder [[Steve Jobs]], also has three children.<ref name=\"Laurene\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/wp/2013/08/08/adrian-fenty-and-his-budding-romance-with-laurene-powell-jobs-billionaire-widow-of-apple-co-founder-steve-jobs/|work=The Reliable Source|author1=Roxanne Roberts|author2=Amy Argetsinger|date=August 9, 2013|title=Adrian Fenty and his 'budding romance' with Laurene Powell Jobs, widow of Steve Jobs|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> The couple was last seen together in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aol.com/article/entertainment/2019/08/01/steve-jobs-widow-laurene-powell-jobs-dating-celebrity-chef-report/23784667/ |title=Steve Jobs' widow Laurene Powell Jobs dating celebrity chef |date=August 1, 2019 |publisher=AOL |access-date=February 11, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nFenty is an amateur triathlete and runner. During his time as mayor, he participated in events such as the [[Nation's Triathlon]] and the [[Washington, D.C. Triathlon]].<ref name=\"triathlon\"/><ref name=\"fitness\"/>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n===2000===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2000 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[Ward Four of the District of Columbia|Ward 4]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Primary Election]]<ref name=2000p/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=8,136\n|percentage=57\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|candidate=[[Charlene Drew Jarvis]]\n|votes=6,193\n|percentage=43}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|candidate=[[Write-in]]\n|votes=51\n|percentage=0}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2000 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[Ward Four of the District of Columbia|Ward 4]], [[General Election]]<ref>{{cite news |title= Unofficial Returns: District of Columbia |work= The Washington Post |date= November 9, 1990 |page= B7 |id= {{ProQuest|409057691}} }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|votes= 22,201\n|percentage=89}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Ren\u00e9e Bowser\n|party=D.C. Statehood Green Party\n|votes= 2,604\n|percentage=10\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n|candidate=[[Write-in]]\n|party=\n|votes= 95\n|percentage=0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2004===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2004 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[Ward Four of the District of Columbia|Ward 4]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Primary Election]]<ref name=2004p/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=11,659\n|percentage=99}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Write-in]]\n|votes=146\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|percentage=1}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2004 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[Ward Four of the District of Columbia|Ward 4]], [[General Election]]<ref name=2004g/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=30,530\n|percentage=99}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n|party=\n|candidate=Write-in\n|votes=334\n|percentage=1}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2006===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2006 [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.|Mayor of the District of Columbia]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Primary Election]]<ref name=2006p/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=60,732\n|percentage=57\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Linda W. Cropp]]\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=32,897\n|percentage=31\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Marie Johns]]\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=8,501\n|percentage=8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Vincent Orange]]\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=3,075\n|percentage=3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Michael A. Brown]]\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=650\n|percentage=1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Artee (RT) Milligan\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=105\n|percentage=0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Nestor Djonkam\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=73\n|percentage=0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Write-in\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=145\n|percentage=0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2006 [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.|Mayor of the District of Columbia]], [[General Election]]<ref name=2006g/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=106,848\n|percentage=89\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[David Kranich|David W. Kranich]]\n|party=Republican Party (US)\n|votes=7,517\n|percentage=6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Chris Otten\n|party=D.C. Statehood Green Party\n|votes=4,914\n|percentage=4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n|candidate=Write-in\n|party=\n|votes=1,351\n|percentage=1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2010===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=2010 [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.|Mayor of the District of Columbia]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Primary Election]]<ref name=\"2010 primary\"/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=[[Vincent C. Gray]]\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=72,648\n|percentage=54.27\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Adrian Fenty\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=59,524\n|percentage=44.47\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Leo Alexander\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=908\n|percentage=0.68\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Ernest E. Johnson\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=317\n|percentage=0.24\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=write-in, including [[Calvin H. Gurley]]<ref name= where>DeBonis, Mike. \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/mike-debonis/wp/2012/11/07/where-did-calvin-h-gurley-find-57119-votes/ Where did Calvin H. Gurley find 57,119 votes?] ''The Washington Post''. November 7, 2012.</ref>\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=248\n|percentage=0.19\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate=Sulaimon Brown\n|party=Democratic Party (US)\n|votes=209\n|percentage=0.16\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=2000p>{{cite web |title=Final and Complete Election Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=September 22, 2000 |url=https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/elec_2000/primary.asp |access-date=November 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905215510/https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/elec_2000/primary.asp |archive-date=September 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=2000g>{{cite web |title=Final and Complete Election Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=November 17, 2000 |url=https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/elec_2000/general_elec.asp |access-date=2015-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923085434/https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/elec_2000/general_elec.asp |archive-date=2015-09-23 |