mar|naval}} [[Myanmar Navy|Navy]]<ref name=\"Zaw24619\">{{cite news |last1=Zaw |first1=Htet Naing |title=AA Naval Attack Kills 2 Tatmadaw Fighters |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/aa-naval-attack-kills-2-tatmadaw-fighters.html |accessdate=20 July 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|Myanmar|coast guard}} [[Myanmar Police Force|Police Force]]\n** [[Border Guard Police]]\n* [[Border Guard Forces]]<ref name=\"MMbgf\">{{cite web|title=Border Guard Force Scheme|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/background/border-guard-force|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n| units2      =\n* Local armed insurgents<ref name=\"MMstakeholders\">{{cite web|title=Armed ethnic groups|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/armed-ethnic-groups|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=11 January 2013}}</ref>\n* Foreign volunteers<ref name=\"VICE1\">{{cite news |last1=Swain |first1=Rob |title=We Don't Always Get the War We Want |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/8gvym4/we-dont-always-get-the-war-we-want |accessdate=30 June 2018 |work=[[Vice Media|VICE]] |date=29 December 2012 |language=en-ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=War in Karen Country: Armed Struggle for a Free and Independent Karen State in Southeast Asia |last=Bleming |first=Thomas James |year=2007 |publisher=iUniverse |location=New York; Bloomington, Ind. |isbn=978-0-595-69327-6 |oclc=609978846}}</ref>\n| strength1   = {{flagicon image|Myanmar Armed Forces Emblem.svg}} 492,000{{efn|Number shown includes personnel not directly involved in the conflict.<ref name=\"IISS2010\">International Institute for Strategic Studies; Hackett, James (ed.) (2010). ''The Military Balance 2010''. London: Routledge, pp. 420\u2013421. {{ISBN|1-85743-557-5}}.</ref>}}\n{{Collapsible list\n| title = Previous totals:\n| 43,000 (1951)<ref name=\"Gibson\"/>\n| 289,000 (1995)<ref>Heppner & Becker, 2002: 18\u201319</ref>\n}}\n----\n{{flagicon image|United Wa State Army flag.png}} 20,000<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\">Johnson, Tim (29 August 2009). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/28/AR2009082803764.html China Urges Burma to Bridle Ethnic Militia Uprising at Border]. ''[[The Washington Post]]''.</ref>\u201325,000<ref name=\"JanesDefence\">{{cite magazine|last1=Davis |first1=Anthony |title=Wa army fielding new Chinese artillery, ATGMs |url=http://www.janes.com/article/53155/wa-army-fielding-new-chinese-artillery-atgms |magazine=IHS Jane's Defence Weekly |accessdate=23 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723214739/http://www.janes.com/article/53155/wa-army-fielding-new-chinese-artillery-atgms |archivedate=23 July 2015  }}</ref>\n| strength2   = '''{{abbr|NA-B|Northern Alliance}}: 21,500\u201326,500+'''\n* {{flagicon image|Infobox AA.png}} ~20,000<ref name=\"Denby\">{{cite news |last1=Denby |first1=Kenneth |title=Rise of the Arakan Army in Burma \u2014 this is not Game of Thrones, the suffering is real |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rise-of-the-arakan-army-in-burma-this-is-not-game-of-thrones-the-suffering-is-real-hv3krpm60 |accessdate=12 December 2019 |work=The Times |date=18 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Kachin Independence Army flag.svg}} 10,000\u201312,000<ref name=\"MMkio\">{{cite web|title=Kachin Independence Organization (KIO)|url=http://mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/155-kio|website=mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312204620/http://mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/155-kio|archive-date=12 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Myanmar National Democratic Alliance Army.svg}} 3,000\u20134,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/47-govt-troops-killed-tens-thousands-flee-heavy-fighting-shan-state.html|title=47 Govt Troops Killed, Tens of Thousands Flee Heavy Fighting in Shan State|work=irrawaddy.org|date=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Ta'ang National Liberation Army Flag.png}} 1,500<ref name=\"MMpslf\">{{cite web|title=PSLF/TNLA|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/nippon-foundation/156-tnla|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310072318/http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/nippon-foundation/156-tnla|archive-date=10 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\u20133,500<ref name=\"ViceNews\">{{cite news|last1=Larsen|first1=Niels|title=On Patrol With Myanmar Rebels Fighting Both the Army and Drug Addiction \u2013 VICE News|url=https://news.vice.com/article/on-patrol-with-myanmar-rebels-fighting-both-the-army-and-drug-addiction|work=VICE News|issue=Crime and Drugs|date=23 April 2015|language=en-US}}</ref>\n{{flagicon image|Flag of the United Nationalities Federal Council.png}} '''~10,000'''\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the Karenni people.png}} 500<ref name=\"Rotberg\"/>\u20131,500<ref name=\"burmalibrary1\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|New Mon State Party flag.png}} 800+<ref name=\"MMnmsp\">{{cite web|title=New Mon State Party (NMSP)|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/164-nmsp|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=15 October 2017|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Shan State Army-North flag.png}} 8,000<ref name=\"MMstakeholders\"/>\n{{plainlist|\n* {{flagicon image|Fighting Peacock Flag.png}} 600<ref name=\"MMabsdf\">{{cite web|title=All Burma Students' Democratic Front (ABSDF)|url=http://mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/154-absdf|website=mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310081946/http://mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/154-absdf|archive-date=10 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\u20131,000<ref name=\"Rotberg\">{{cite book|last1=I. Rotberg|first1=Robert|title=Burma: Prospects for a Democratic Future|date=1998|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|isbn=0815791690|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6bjyIcXIKgC}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of DKBA-5 (Buddhist).png}} 1,500<ref name=\"MMstakeholders\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|Karen National Liberation Army flag.svg}} 6,000<ref name=\"Rotberg\"/>\u20137,000<ref name=\"burmalibrary1\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the NDAA.png}} 3,000<ref name=\"MMndaa\">{{cite web|title=NDAA|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/nippon-foundation/163-ndaa|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>\u20134,000<ref name=\"MMstakeholders\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|SSA-S.svg}} 6,000<ref name=\"burmalibrary1\">Burma center for Ethnic Studies, Jan. 2012, \"Briefing Paper No. 1\" http://www.burmalibrary.org/docs13/BCES-BP-01-ceasefires(en).pdf</ref>\u20138,000<ref name=\"MMstakeholders\"/>\n''Unknown numbers of various other groups''\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n| title = Previous totals:\n| 60,000\u201370,000 (1988)<ref name=\"Pavkovi\u0107, 2011: 476\">Pavkovi\u0107, 2011: 476</ref>\n| 50,000 (1998)<ref name=\"Lintner1999\">{{cite book|last1=Lintner|first1=Bertil|title=Burma in revolt: opium and insurgency since 1948|url=https://archive.org/details/burmainrevoltopi0000lint|url-access=registration|date=1999|publisher=Silkworm Books|location=Chiang Mai|isbn=978-974-7100-78-5|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n| 15,000 (2002)<ref>{{cite web|title=Armed forces - Myanmar|url=http://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Asia-and-Oceania/Myanmar-ARMED-FORCES.html|website=www.nationsencyclopedia.com|publisher=Encyclopedia of the Nations}}</ref>\n----\n| {{flagdeco|Taiwan|army}} 14,000 (1950)<ref name=\"ThantMyint\"/>\n| {{flagicon image|Communist Party of Burma flag (1946-1969).png}} 6,000 (1951)<ref name=\"Gibson\"/>\n| {{flagicon image|Karen National Liberation Army flag.svg}} 4,000+ (1951)<ref name=\"Gibson\"/>\n}}\n| casualties1 =\n| casualties2 =\n| casualties3 = 130,000<ref>{{cite web|title=Modern Conflicts \u2013 Death Tolls PDF |url=http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/dpe/modern_conflicts/death_tolls.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720091321/http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/dpe/modern_conflicts/death_tolls.pdf |archivedate=20 July 2011  }}</ref>\u2013250,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://remilitari.com/guias/victimario4.htm|title=De re militari: muertos en Guerras, Dictaduras y Genocidios|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> killed<br />\n600,000\u20131,000,000 civilians [[Displaced person|displaced]]<ref>Janie Hampton (2012). ''Internally Displaced People: A Global Survey''. London: Routledge. {{ISBN|978-1-136-54705-8}}.</ref>\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Myanmar conflict}}\n}}\n{{Contains Burmese text|compact=yes}}\n\nThe '''internal conflict in Myanmar''' is a series of primarily [[ethnic conflict]]s within [[Myanmar]] that began shortly after the country, then known as Burma, became [[Post-independence Burma, 1948\u201362|independent]] from the [[United Kingdom]] in 1948. The conflict is the world's longest ongoing civil war.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miliband |first1=David |title=How to Bring Peace to the World's Longest Civil War |url=http://time.com/4597920/myanmar-peace/ |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=TIME |date=12 December 2016 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Slow |first1=Oliver |title=Fighting in Kachin Highlights Myanmar Civil War Worries |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/kachin-fighting-myanmar-civil-war/4365603.html |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=VOA |date=26 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaicome |first1=Jittrapon |title=Marking 70 Years of War in Myanmar |url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/02/marking-70-years-of-war-in-myanmar/ |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=The Diplomat |date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPrior to independence from the United Kingdom, several anti-colonial groups in Myanmar (Burma) protested against [[British rule in Burma|British rule]] over the country. These groups became especially influential during [[World War II]], when the [[Empire of Japan]] promised an \"independent Burmese state\" (though it would be ''[[de facto]]'' [[Japanese occupation of Burma|controlled by Japan]] as a [[puppet state]]) and appointed [[Ba Maw]] as its [[head of state]].<ref name=\"Leeds\">{{cite book|url=http://www.smlc.leeds.ac.uk/eas/eas_content/resources/documents/67LEAP.pdf#search=%22%22Thakin%20Than%20Tun%22%22|title=The Burmese Communist Party and the State-to-State Relations between China and Burma|first=Oliver|last=Hensengerth|year=2005|publisher=Leeds East Asia Papers|pages=10\u201312, 15\u201316, 17}}</ref> During this period, left-wing groups such as the [[Communist Party of Burma]] (also known as the Burma Communist Party) and armed ethnic groups began to emerge in opposition to both the British and Japanese.<ref>{{cite book|last= Allen|first= Louis|year= 1986|title= Burma: the Longest War 1941\u201345|publisher = J.M. Dent and Sons|location= Great Britain|isbn= 0-460-02474-4}}</ref> In 1947, the [[Panglong Agreement]] was reached between [[Aung San]] and ethnic leaders, in an attempt to quell hostilities; however, the agreement was not honoured by the post-independence government following [[Aung San#Assassination|Aung San's assassination]], leading to further ethnic tensions.<ref name=\"Maung\">{{cite news|last=Maung|first=Zarni|title=Remembering the martyrs and their hopes for Burma|url=http://www.dvb.no/analysis/remembering-the-martyrs-and-their-hopes-for-burma/30028|accessdate=27 December 2013|newspaper=DVB NEWS|date=19 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 1948, Myanmar gained independence from the United Kingdom. The communists and ethnic minorities in the country were dissatisfied with the [[Post-independence Burma, 1948\u201362|newly formed government]], believing that they were being unfairly excluded from governing the country.<ref name=\"Lintner1995\"/><ref name=\"Leeds\"/> Three months after independence, the communists began an armed insurgency against the government. Similarly, Karen insurgent groups began to fight for independence.<ref>Callahan, M., ''Making Enemies. War and State Building in Burma.'' United States of America: Cornell University Press, 2003, p. 118 \u2013 123</ref>\n\nIn the early 1960s, the government refused to adopt a [[federalism|federal system]], to the dismay of insurgent groups such as the CPB, who proposed adopting the system during peace talks. By the early 1980s, politically motivated armed insurgencies had largely disappeared, while ethnic-based insurgencies continued.<ref>Callahan, M., ''Making Enemies. War and State Building in Burma.'' United States of America: Cornell University Press, 2003, p. 34 \u2013 36</ref>\n\nSeveral insurgent groups have negotiated ceasefires and peace agreements with successive governments, which until [[2011\u201315 Myanmar political reforms|political reforms between 2011 and 2015]] had largely fallen apart.<ref name=\"Licklider, R. 1995\">Licklider, R. (1995). The Consequences of Negotiated Settlements in Civil Wars, 1945\u20131993. The American Political Science Review, 89(3), 681.</ref> The [[Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement]] (NCA) was a landmark agreement signed between the government of Myanmar and eight insurgent groups on 15 October 2015;<ref name=\"rfaNCA\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar Signs Historic Cease-Fire Deal With Eight Ethnic Armies|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/deal-10152015175051.html|accessdate=15 October 2017|work=Radio Free Asia|language=en}}</ref> two other insurgent groups later joined on 13 February 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=2 groups join Myanmar government's peace process|url=https://apnews.com/e668736f3c4b44cfa310addefd4da1e3|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=AP News|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Mon State Party and Lahu Democratic Union sign NCA|url=http://www.president-office.gov.mm/en/?q=issues/peace/id-8468|publisher=Office of the President of Myanmar|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Analysis: A Win for Peace Commission as Mon, Lahu Groups Sign NCA|url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/analysis-win-peace-commission-mon-lahu-groups-sign-nca.html|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=The Irrawaddy|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NCA signing ceremony for NMSP, LDU to take place on 13 Feb|url=http://www.mizzima.com/news-domestic/nca-signing-ceremony-nmsp-ldu-take-place-13-feb|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=Mizzima|date=6 February 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\nThe conflict is generally divided into three parts: Insurgencies during the [[Post-independence Burma, 1948\u201362|post-independence period]] under parliamentary rule (1948\u20131962), insurgencies during the post-[[1962 Burmese coup d'\u00e9tat|1962 coup]] [[Burmese Way to Socialism|socialist government]] under the rule of General [[Ne Win]] and his [[Burma Socialist Programme Party]] (1962\u20131988), and insurgencies during the modern [[post Cold War era]]; first under the military administration of the [[State Peace and Development Council]] (1988\u20132011) and now under the [[2015 Myanmar general election|newly elected]] civilian government.\n\n=== Post-independence conflict (1948\u20131962) ===\n{{main|Communist insurgency in Myanmar|Karen conflict}}\n\nFollowing independence from the United Kingdom, the two largest opposition groups in Burma (Myanmar) were the communists, led by the [[Communist Party of Burma]] (CPB) and the Karen nationalists, led by the [[Karen National Union]]'s predecessor. The former had fought the British colonial government prior to independence; however, during the final days of the [[Japanese occupation of Burma]] in [[World War II]], both groups helped the British against the [[Imperial Japanese Army]].<ref name=\"Leeds\"/> Initially there was calm during the transitional period after independence, but on 2 April 1948, the CPB fired the first shots of the conflict in Paukkongyi, Pegu Region (present-day [[Bago Region]]).<ref name=\"Lintner1990\"/>\n\nDuring the post-independence period, the KNU favoured an [[independent state]], administered by the Karen people. The proposed state would have encompassed the territories of Karen State and Karenni State (present-day [[Kayin State]] and [[Kayah State]]), in [[Lower Burma]] (Outer Myanmar). The KNU has since shifted their focus from full independence to [[regional autonomy]], under a [[Federalism|federal system]] with fair Karen representation in the government.<ref name=\"KNUabout\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.knuhq.org/about/|title=About {{!}} Official Karen National Union Webpage|access-date=21 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121204309/http://www.knuhq.org/about/|archive-date=21 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-coup conflict (1962\u20131988) ===\n[[File:They go back.jpg|thumb|\"''They Go Back''\": Insurgents of the [[Communist Party of Burma]] walk back to their bases after failed peace talks. (c. November 1963)]]\n\nAfter three successive parliamentary governments governed Myanmar (Burma), the [[Tatmadaw]] (Myanmar Armed Forces), led by [[Ne Win|General Ne Win]], enacted a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] [[1962 Burmese coup d'\u00e9tat|in 1962]], which ousted the parliamentary government and replaced it with a [[military junta]]. Accusations of severe human rights abuses and violations followed afterwards, and the cabinet of the parliamentary government and political leaders of ethnic minority groups were arrested and detained without trial.<ref name=\"Pavkovi\u0107, 2011: 476\"/> Around this period, other ethnic minority groups began forming larger rebel factions, such as the [[Kachin Independence Army]], in response to the new government's refusal to adopt a [[federalism|federal government]] structure.\n\nIn 1967, following [[China]]'s initiation of the [[Cultural Revolution]], violence broke out between local [[Bamar people|Bamars]] and overseas Chinese in Myanmar, leading to [[The 1967 anti-Chinese riots in Burma|anti-Chinese riots]] in Rangoon (present-day [[Yangon]]) and other cities.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fan|first1=Hongwei|title=The 1967 anti-Chinese riots in Burma and Sino-Burmese relations|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=43(2)|issue=June 2012}}</ref> The riots left many overseas Chinese dead, which allegedly prompted China to begin giving logistical aid to the [[Communist Party of Burma]] (CPB) in 1968.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fan|first1=Hong Wei|title=The 1967 Anti-Chinese Riots in Burma and Sino-Burmese Relations|issue=2|pages=234\u2013256|url=https://www.questia.com/library/journal/1G1-290856826/the-1967-anti-chinese-riots-in-burma-and-sino-burmese|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=43|language=en|date=1 June 2012|doi=10.1017/S0022463412000045}}</ref>\n\nBoth immediately after the coup and again in 1972, General Ne Win held peace talks with opposition forces, but both times they fell apart, partly due to General Ne Win's refusal to adopt a [[multi-party system]]. After negotiations failed, defectors from the Tatmadaw and ethnic insurgents walked back to their bases, with headlines across Myanmar famously reading \"''They Go Back''\" (\u101e\u1030\u1010\u102d\u102f\u1037\u1015\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1000\u103c\u101c\u1031\u1015\u103c\u102e). Private property was confiscated by the government, and the [[Burmese Socialist Programme Party]] (BSPP) was founded in 1974 to govern the country under a [[One-party state|one-party system]]. Under General Ne Win's [[Burmese Way to Socialism|26 year dictatorship]], Myanmar became an isolated [[hermit kingdom]] and one of the [[Human Development Index|least developed countries]] in the world. In 1988, [[8888 Uprising|nationwide student protests]] resulted in the BSPP and General Ne Win being ousted and replaced with a new military regime, the [[State Peace and Development Council]].<ref name=\"Lintner1999\"/>\n\n=== 1988 Uprising ===\n{{main|8888 Uprising}}\n\nOn 8 August 1988, students began demonstrating in Rangoon (Yangon) against General Ne Win's rule and the disastrous [[Burmese Way to Socialism]] system. The protests spread across the country,<ref>{{cite web|title=Burmese Days|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/44329/maureen-aung-thwin/burmese-days|work=Foreign Affairs|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations, Inc|accessdate=27 March 2013|author=Maureen Aung-Thwin|year=1989}}</ref> The uprising ended on 18 September 1988, after a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup]] was enacted by the [[State Peace and Development Council|State Law and Order Restoration Council]] (SLORC) and the BSPP government was overthrown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://rlp.hds.harvard.edu/faq/burma-socialist-programme-party-bspp|title=The Burma Socialist Programme Party (BSPP)|access-date=16 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities in Myanmar (Burma) claimed that around 350 people were killed,<ref>''[[Ottawa Citizen]]''. 24 September 1988. pg. A.16</ref><ref>[[Associated Press]]. ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. 26 September 1988</ref> whilst anti-government groups claimed thousands died in the protests, with a high number of deaths attributed to the military.<ref name=\"Ferrara\">Ferrara (2003), pp. 313</ref><ref name=\"BBC32013\">{{cite news|title=Was Burma's 1988 uprising worth it?|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7543347.stm|accessdate=27 March 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 August 2008|author=Philippa Fogarty}}</ref><ref name=\"Wintle\">Wintle (2007)</ref> According to ''[[The Economist]]'', over 3,000 people were killed in the public uprising.<ref name=\"economist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/node/9867036 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408092710/http://www.economist.com/node/9867036 |archive-date=8 April 2011 |url-status=dead |title=The saffron revolution &#124; The Economist |accessdate=21 October 2015  }}</ref> As a result of the uprising, the new government agreed to sign separate peace treaties with certain insurgent groups. Because the 1988 uprising was mostly politically motivated, ethnic insurgent groups did not receive much support from political movements in Myanmar. In the 1990s, the Tatmadaw severely weakened ethnic insurgent groups, destroying most of their bases and strongholds.<ref>{{cite book|title=RECONSTRUCTING CONFLICT : integrating war and post war geographies.|last=COLIN.|first=FLINT, PROFESSOR OF GEOGRAPHY|date=2016|publisher=ROUTLEDGE|isbn=978-1138277076|location=[S.l.]|pages=99|oclc=982562747}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-Cold War conflict (1988\u2013present) ===\nIn 2006, the Tatmadaw conducted a large military offensive against the Karen National Union (KNU) in Kayin State, which resulted in the displacement of hundreds of thousands of civilians. One estimate claimed that approximately half a million people were displaced due to fighting between government forces and the KNU, and the forcible relocation of villages by the government.<ref name=\"blogs.cfr.org\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cfr.org/asia/2015/10/07/myanmars-cease-fire-deal-comes-up-short/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009042537/http://blogs.cfr.org/asia/2015/10/07/myanmars-cease-fire-deal-comes-up-short/ |archive-date=9 October 2015 |url-status=dead |title=Asia Unbound \u00bb Myanmar's Cease-Fire Deal Comes up Short |accessdate=21 October 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"Ray Pagnucco and Jennifer Peters\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar's National Ceasefire Agreement isn't all that national|url=https://news.vice.com/article/myanmars-national-ceasefire-agreement-to-end-68-year-civil-war-isnt-all-that-national|accessdate=18 October 2015|newspaper=Vice News|date=15 October 2015|author=Ray Pagnucco and Jennifer Peters}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Tatmadaw launched a military offensive named ''Operation Perseverance'' ({{my|\u1007\u103d\u1032\u1019\u1014\u103a\u101f\u102d\u1014\u103a\u1038}}) against insurgents in [[Shan State]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=21101 |title=Conflict in Shan State Spreading |last=Htwe |first=Ko |date=8 April 2011 |work=The Irrawaddy |accessdate=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615203913/http://irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=21101 |archivedate=15 June 2011 }}</ref> During the offensive, the Tatmadaw captured territory from the [[National Democratic Alliance Army]] (NDAA) and the [[Shan State Army - North]] (SSA-N), with the latter being involved in most of the fighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3509:burma-army-occupies-ssa-core-base&catid=86:war&Itemid=284 |title=Burma Army occupies SSA core base |publisher=Shanland.org |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=14 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930053633/http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3509%3Aburma-army-occupies-ssa-core-base&catid=86%3Awar&Itemid=284 |archivedate=30 September 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3511:ssa-north-given-ultimatum-to-surrender&catid=86:war&Itemid=284 |title=SSA 'North' given ultimatum to surrender |publisher=Shanland.org |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=14 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930053645/http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3511%3Assa-north-given-ultimatum-to-surrender&catid=86%3Awar&Itemid=284 |archivedate=30 September 2011  }}</ref> The operation was officially a response to the groups' rejections of the junta's \"One Nation, One Army\" policy;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org |title=Shan Herald Agency for News (S.H.A.N.) |publisher=Shanland.org |accessdate=14 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3402:mongla-base-shelled-by-burma-army-artillery&catid=86:war&Itemid=284 |title=Mongla base shelled by Burma Army artillery |last=Hseng |first=Khio Fah |date=10 January 2011 |work=Shan Herald Agency |accessdate=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117091017/http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3402%3Amongla-base-shelled-by-burma-army-artillery&catid=86%3Awar&Itemid=284 |archivedate=17 January 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3432:land-confiscation-emerges-in-area-under-new-command&catid=86:war&Itemid=284 |title=Mongla base shelled by Burma Army artillery |last=Hseng |first=Khio Fah |date=26 January 2011 |work=Shan Herald Agency |accessdate=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128051424/http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3432%3Aland-confiscation-emerges-in-area-under-new-command&catid=86%3Awar&Itemid=284 |archivedate=28 January 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3484:-all-roads-to-shan-rebel-base-closed&catid=86:war&Itemid=284 |title=All roads to Shan rebel base closed |publisher=Shanland.org |date=24 February 2011 |accessdate=14 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930053529/http://www.shanland.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3484%3A-all-roads-to-shan-rebel-base-closed&catid=86%3Awar&Itemid=284 |archivedate=30 September 2011  }}</ref> however, researchers have linked it to the military's interests in the [[Jade trade in Myanmar|jade trade]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalwitness.org/en/campaigns/oil-gas-and-mining/myanmarjade/|title=Jade: Myanmar's \"Big State Secret\"|website=Global Witness|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Christensen|first=Darin|last2=Nguyen|first2=Mai|last3=Sexton|first3=Renard|date=12 March 2019|title=Strategic Violence During Democratization|journal=World Politics|volume=71|issue=2|language=en|pages=332\u2013366|doi=10.1017/S0043887118000308|issn=0043-8871}}</ref>\n\nGovernment forces attacked the [[Kachin Independence Army]]'s headquarters near the city of [[Laiza]] on 19 November 2014, killing at least 22 KIA insurgents, according to the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/myanmars-kachin-rebels-22-dead-attack-27023038|title=Myanmar's Kachin Rebels Say 22 Dead in Fighting|date=19 November 2014|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween February and May 2015, government forces launched a [[2015 Kokang offensive|series of military operations]] in [[Kokang]], in northern [[Shan State]],<ref name=\"rfa.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/kokang-02132015185129.html|title=Myanmar Kokang Rebels Deny Receiving Chinese Weapons|work=Radio Free Asia}}</ref> after the [[Myanmar National Democratic Alliance Army]] (MNDAA) attempted to retake territory it had [[2009 Kokang incident|lost in 2009]].<ref name=\"dvb.no\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvb.no/news/kokang-enlist-allies-help-in-fight-against-burma-army-myanmar/48184|title=Kokang enlist allies' help in fight against Burma army|website=dvb.no|date=10 February 2015|author=NANG MYA NADI|access-date=15 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221153/http://www.dvb.no/news/kokang-enlist-allies-help-in-fight-against-burma-army-myanmar/48184|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nInsurgents of the [[Arakan Rohingya Salvation Army]] (ARSA) [[Northern Rakhine State clashes#2016|attacked Burmese border posts]] along the [[Bangladesh\u2013Myanmar border]] on 9 October 2016, killing nine border officers.<ref name=\"BBC9102016\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar policemen killed in Rakhine border attack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37601928|accessdate=12 October 2016|work=BBC News|date=9 October 2016}}</ref> Armed clashes continued and on 11 October 2016, four Tatmadaw soldiers were killed by insurgents with recently looted weapons.<ref name=\"BBC12102016\">{{cite news|title=Rakhine unrest leaves four Myanmar soldiers dead|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37627498|accessdate=13 October 2016|work=BBC News|date=12 October 2016}}</ref> On 25 August 2017, the ARSA [[Northern Rakhine State clashes#25 August 2017 ARSA attacks|launched a second large-scale attack]] against 24 police posts and the 552nd Light Infantry Battalion army base in northern [[Rakhine State]]. A total of 71 people were reportedly killed in the armed clashes.<ref name=\"BBC4\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar tensions: Dozens dead in Rakhine militant attack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-41046729|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 August 2017|date=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AP1\">{{cite news|last1=Htusan|first1=Esther|title=Myanmar: 71 die in militant attacks on police, border posts|url=https://apnews.com/37103be49dd249af8f2e7297b599fb41/Myanmar:-25-dead-in-militant-attacks-on-police,-border-posts|accessdate=25 August 2017|work=AP News|date=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters6\">{{cite news|last1=Lone|first1=Wa|last2=Slodkowski|first2=Antoni|title=At least 12 dead in Muslim insurgent attacks in northwest Myanmar|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-idUSKCN1B507K?il=0|accessdate=25 August 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|date=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Main fronts ==\n\n=== Kachin State ===\n{{main|Kachin conflict}}\n[[File:Kachin Independence Army cadets in Laiza (Paul Vrieze-VOA).jpg|thumb|Cadets from the [[Kachin Independence Army]] (KIA) preparing for military drills at the group's headquarters in [[Laiza]].]]\n\nThe [[Kachin people]] are a major ethnic minority in Myanmar who mainly inhabit the mountainous northern regions of the [[Kachin Hills]] in [[Kachin State]]. Kachin regular soldiers previously formed a significant part of the [[Tatmadaw|Myanmar military]]; however, after [[Ne Win|General Ne Win]]'s regime seized power in 1962, many Kachin soldiers defected from the military and reorganized with already active Kachin insurgents to form the [[Kachin Independence Army]] (KIA), under the [[Kachin Independence Organisation]] (KIO). Religious tensions have also been a source of conflict, as Kachin people have historically been predominantly Christian, while the majority [[Bamar people]] have been predominantly [[Buddhist]].<ref>Fuller, T. (4 April 2013). \"Ethnic Rifts Strain Myanmar as It Moves Toward Democracy\". The New York Times.</ref>\n\nIn 2012 alone, fighting between the KIA and the government resulted in around 2,500 casualties (both civilian and military); 211 of whom were government soldiers. The violence resulted in the displacement of nearly 100,000 civilians and the complete or partial abandonment of 364 villages.<ref name=\"kachinnews2\">KIA claims 211 Tatmadaw soldiers have died in two months of fighting in Hpakant, 10 October 2012, http://www.kachinnews.com/news/2418-kia-says-211-army-soldiers-die-in-two-month-fighting-in-hpakant.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031043518/http://www.kachinnews.com/news/2418-kia-says-211-army-soldiers-die-in-two-month-fighting-in-hpakant.html |date=31 October 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"dailytimes2012\">31 dead in new clashes with Kachin: Myanmar News, 5 May 2012, http://dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012\\story_5-5-2012_pg14_7 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612193343/http://dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2012|date=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref>Lanjouw, S., Mortimer, G., & Bamforth, V. (2000). Internal Displacement in Burma. Disasters, 24(3), 228\u2013239.</ref><ref name=\"kachinwomen1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kachinwomen.com/publications/reports/105-state-terror-in-the-kachin-hills-.html|title=Kachin Women's Association Thailand \u2013 State terror in the Kachin hills|publisher=Kachinwomen.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130411051706/http://www.kachinwomen.com/publications/reports/105-state-terror-in-the-kachin-hills-.html|archivedate=11 April 2013|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nCeasefire agreements have been signed between the KIA and the government several times; most notably a ceasefire signed in 1994, that lasted for 17 years until June 2011, when government forces attacked KIA positions along the [[Taping River]], east of [[Bhamo]], Kachin State.<ref name=\"hrwarchive1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/reports/burma0312ForUpload_1_0.pdf|title=Untold Miseries|publisher=Hrw.org|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> As a result of the ceasefire breakdown, Kachin State has faced waves of internal displacement, with over 90,000 internally displaced people spread across over 150 camps or camp-like settings as of April 2017. Many IDP camps are located in non-government controlled areas with severely restricted access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data2.unhcr.org/en/documents/download/56547|title=Factsheet: Myanmar April 2017|author=CCCM Cluster|date=April 2017|website=data2.unhcr.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Internal Displacement Monitoring Centre (IDMC) estimates that in April and May 2018, over 14,000 people were displaced from fighting between the KIO/KIA and the Tatmadaw.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/sites/default/files/2019-05/GRID%202019%20-%20Conflict%20Figure%20Analysis%20-%20MYANMAR.pdf|title=Myanmar: Figure Analysis - Displacement Related to Conflict and Violence|first=|date=|website=internal displacement monitoring centre|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Kayah State ===\nThe largest insurgent group in [[Kayah State]] (formerly Karenni State) is the [[Karenni Army]], whose goal for the past few decades has been to obtain independence and self-determination for the [[Karenni people]].<ref name=\"KAJane\">Karenni Army (KA) (Myanmar), GROUPS \u2013 ASIA \u2013 ACTIVE, Jane's World Insurgency and Terrorism, 13 March 2012</ref>\n\nThe group has claimed that their grievances towards the government include: the (government's) exploitation and rapid depletion of the natural resources in the region, the forced sale of farmer's agricultural products for low prices, extortion and corruption within local authorities, forced labour, forced relocation of whole villages and farms, destruction of houses, planting of mines in civilian areas, torture, rape, extrajudicial killings, burning of villages, expropriation of food supplies and livestock, arrests without charge and exploitation of the poor. The Karenni Army is currently led by General Bee Htoo,<ref name=\"KAJane\"/> and consists of roughly between 500<ref name=\"Rotberg\"/> and 1,500 soldiers.<ref name=\"burmalibrary1\"/>\n\n=== Kayin State ===\n{{main|Karen conflict}}\n[[File:KNLA medic treating displaced civilians (Steve Sandford-VOA).jpg|thumb|A KNLA medic treats [[Internally displaced person|IDPs]] in [[Hpapun District]], [[Kayin State]].]]\n\nThe [[Karen people]] of [[Kayin State]] (formerly Karen State) in eastern Myanmar are the third largest ethnic group in Myanmar, consisting of roughly 7% of the country's total population. Karen insurgent groups have fought for independence and self-determination since 1949. In 1949, the [[commander-in-chief]] of the Tatmadaw General [[Smith Dun]], an ethnic Karen, was fired because of the rise of Karen opposition groups, which furthered ethnic tensions. He was replaced by Ne Win, a [[Bamar]] [[nationalist]] who would go on to become the [[dictator]] of Myanmar.<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Martin|title=Burma: Insurgency and the politics of ethnicity|date=1991|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=0862328683|edition=2. impr.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s4NuAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThe government of Myanmar has been accused of using \"[[scorched earth]]\" tactics against Karen civilians in the past, including (but not limited to) burning down entire villages, planting [[land mine]]s, using civilians as slave labour, using civilians as minesweepers and the rape and murder of Karen women.<ref name=\"NYFree\">Phan, Zoya and Damien Lewis. Undaunted: My Struggle for Freedom and Survival in Burma. New York: Free Press, 2010.</ref> According to a report by legal firm [[DLA Piper]], whose report was presented to the [[United Nations Security Council]], these tactics against the Karen can be identified as [[ethnic cleansing]]. The government had however, denied these claims.<ref name=\"DLApiper\">{{cite news|last1=Gray Cary|first1=Rudnick|title=Threat to the Peace: A Call for the UN Security Council to Act in Burma|url=http://www.dlapiper.com/files/Publication/ed49fff4-6c18-4bcf-a550-64b4734eb9c3/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/5320f731-eaf2-45ff-9735-6541f3561f5b/BurmaReport.pdf|accessdate=10 April 2016|work=[[DLA Piper]]|date=2005}}{{dead link|date=August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe initial aim of the largest Karen opposition group, the [[Karen National Union]] (KNU), and its armed wing, the [[Karen National Liberation Army]] (KNLA), was to obtain independence for the Karen people. However, since 1976 they have instead called for a [[federation|federal union]] with fair Karen representation and the self-determination of the Karen people.<ref name=\"KNUabout\"/> Nearly all of their demands and requests have been ignored or denied by successive governments, a contributing factor to failed peace talks until [[2011\u201315 Myanmar political reforms|political reforms]] which begun in 2011 and ended in 2015.\n\nIn 1995, the main headquarters and operating bases of the KNU had mostly been destroyed or captured by the government, forcing the KNLA (the armed wing of the KNU) to instead operate in the jungles of Kayin State. Up until that year, the [[Government of Thailand|Thai government]] had been supporting insurgents across its border, but soon stopped its support due to a new major economic deal with Myanmar.<ref name=\"Lintner1995\"/>\n\nThe KNU signed the [[Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement]] (NCA) with the government of Myanmar on 15 October 2015, along with seven other insurgent groups.<ref name=\"rfaNCA\"/> However, in March 2018, the government of Myanmar violated the agreement by sending 400 Tatmadaw soldiers into KNU-held territory to build a road connecting two military bases.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sandford |first1=Steve |title=Conflict Resumes in Karen State After Myanmar Army Returns |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/conflict-resumes-in-karen-state-after-myanmar-army-returns/4417421.html |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Voice of America |date=31 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Armed clashes erupted between the KNU and the [[Myanmar Army]] in the Ler Mu Plaw area of [[Hpapun District]], resulting in the displacement of 2,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sandford |first1=Steve |title=Karen Return to War in Myanmar |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/karen-return-war-myanmar/4416908.html |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Voice of America |date=31 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On 17 May 2018, the Tatmadaw agreed to \"temporarily postpone\" their road project and to withdraw troops from the area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nyein |first1=Nyein |title=Tatmadaw Agrees to Halt Contentious Road Project in Karen State |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/tatmadaw-agrees-halt-contentious-road-project-karen-state.html |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Rakhine State ===\n{{further|Rohingya conflict|Northern Rakhine State clashes}}\n[[File:Rohingya mujahid surrenders (1961).jpg|thumb|A Rohingya mujahid surrenders his weapon to Brigadier-General [[Aung Gyi]], 4 July 1961.]]\n\nInsurgent groups of the [[Rakhine people|Rakhine]] (formerly Arakanese),<ref name=\"MMalp\">{{cite web|title=Arakan Liberation Party (ALP)|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/research/monitoring-archive/157-alp|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> [[Chin people|Chin]],<ref name=\"MMcnf\">{{cite web|title=Chin National Front (CNF)|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/158-cnf|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013}}</ref> and [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]]<ref name=\"RBangladesh\">{{cite news|title=Myanmar, Bangladesh leaders 'to discuss Rohingya'|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-26/an-burma-bangladesh-rohingya-talks/4092238|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=29 June 2012}}</ref> ethnic minorities have fought against the government for self-determination in [[Rakhine State]] since the early 1950s.\n\nEthnic Rakhine insurgent groups, such as the [[Arakan Army (Kachin State)|Arakan Army]] and [[Arakan Liberation Army]] (ALA), continue to have hostilities towards the government, though major violence has been rare since political reforms and peace talks. The Arakan Army, founded in 2009, is currently the largest insurgent group in Rakhine State, with around 20,000 active fighters.<ref name=\"Denby\"/>\n\nRohingya insurgents have been fighting local government forces and other insurgent groups in northern Rakhine State since 1948, with ongoing [[religious violence]] between the predominantly [[Muslim]] Rohingyas and [[Buddhist]] Rakhines fueling the conflict. The legal and political rights of the Rohingya people have been an underlying issue in the conflict, with spontaneous bouts of violence such as the [[2012 Rakhine State riots]] and [[2013 Myanmar anti-Muslim riots]] periodically occurring as a result. Despite making up a majority of the population in the three northern townships of Rakhine State,<ref name=\"RBangladesh\"/> Rohingyas are often targets of religiously motivated attacks. Because the government does not recognise the Rohingya people as an official ethnic group in Myanmar, Rohingyas cannot apply for citizenship and few laws exist to protect their rights.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.mmtimes.com/index.php/national-news/7376-origin-of-most-persecuted-minority-statement-unclear.html|title = Origin of 'most persecuted minority' statement unclear|last= MclaughLin|first= Tim|date= 8 July 2013|work= |accessdate= 17 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October 2016, unidentified insurgents attacked three Burmese border posts along Myanmar's border with Bangladesh, starting a [[Northern Rakhine State clashes|new armed conflict]] in northern Rakhine State. According to government officials in the border town of [[Maungdaw]], the attackers looted several dozen firearms and ammunition from the border posts, and brandished knives and homemade slingshots that fired metal bolts. The attacks left nine border officers and \"several insurgents\" dead.<ref name=\"BBC9102016\"/> On 11 October 2016, four Tatmadaw soldiers were killed on the third day of fighting.<ref name=\"BBC12102016\"/> A newly emerged insurgent group, the [[Arakan Rohingya Salvation Army]] (ARSA), claimed responsibility a week later.<ref name=\"BKP1\">{{cite news|title=Islamist fears rise in Rohingya-linked violence|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/asia/1111481/islamist-fears-rise-in-rohingya-linked-violence|accessdate=5 November 2016|work=Bangkok Post|publisher=Post Publishing PCL}}</ref>\n\nDuring the early hours of 25 August 2017, ARSA insurgents launched coordinated attacks on 24 police posts and the 552nd Light Infantry Battalion army base, killing a dozen people.<ref name=\"BBC4\"/><ref name=\"AP1\"/><ref name=\"Reuters6\"/> In response, the Tatmadaw launched \"clearance operations\" in northern Rakhine State, which critics argued targeted Rohingya civilians rather than insurgents.<ref name=\"myanmar_accused_2017_09_10_ap_chicago_tribune\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-myanmar-refugees-20170910-story.html \"Myanmar accused of laying mines after refugee injuries,\"] 12 September 2017, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' retrieved 12 September 2017. Quote \"Accounts from refugees show the military is also targeting civilians with shootings and wholesale burning of Rohingya villages in an apparent attempt to purge Rakhine state of Muslims.\"</ref><ref name=\"hundreds_dead_2017_09_10_washpost_chg_trib\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-rohingya-myanmar-20170902-story.html \"Hundreds dead in Myanmar as the Rohingya crisis explodes again.\"] 10 September 2017, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' retrieved 12 September 2017</ref><ref name=TroopsOpenFire>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/myanmar-violence-traps-rohingya-bangladesh-border-170826101215439.html|title=Myanmar troops open fire on civilians fleeing attacks|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> Following the violence, 200,000 civilians remained trapped in the region without adequate access to markets, livelihoods, services and medical care.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erasing the Rohingya: Myanmar's moves could mean refugees never return |url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/myanmar-rohingya-return/ |accessdate=27 June 2019 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"People in Need\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clovekvtisni.cz/en/what-we-do/humanitarian-aid-and-development/burma-myanmar/humanitarian-aid|title=Humanitarian Assistance in Rakhine|website=People in Need|date=2017|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2019, around 300 Arakan Army insurgents launched pre-dawn attacks on four border police outposts\u2014Kyaung Taung, Nga Myin Taw, Ka Htee La and Kone Myint\u2014in northern [[Buthidaung Township]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lintner |first1=Bertil |title=Arakan Army clashes with government forces in Rakhine state |url=http://www.atimes.com/article/arakan-army-clashes-with-government-forces-in-rakhine-state/ |accessdate=5 January 2019 |work=Asia Times |date=3 January 2019}}</ref> Thirteen members of the [[Border Guard Police]] (BGP) were killed and nine others were injured,<ref>{{cite news |title=13 policemen die in Rakhine rebel attacks |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/13-policemen-die-in-rakhine-rebel-attacks |accessdate=5 January 2019 |work=The Straits Times |date=5 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Aung |first1=Min Thein |title=Rakhine Insurgents Kill 13 Policemen, Injure Nine Others in Myanmar Outpost Attacks |url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/rakhine-insurgents-kill-13-policemen-01042019162156.html |accessdate=5 January 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |date=4 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Aung |first1=Thu Thu |last2=Naing |first2=Shoon |title=Rakhine Buddhist rebels kill 13 in Independence Day attack on... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rakhine/rakhine-buddhist-army-kills-seven-in-independence-day-attack-on-police-posts-idUSKCN1OY0N0 |accessdate=5 January 2019 |work=Reuters |date=4 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> whilst 40 firearms and more than 10,000 rounds of ammunition were looted. The Arakan Army later stated that it had captured nine BGP personnel and five civilians, and that three of its fighters were also killed in the attacks.<ref name=\"WSJ4119\">{{cite news |last1=Emont |first1=Jon |last2=Myo |first2=Myo |title=Buddhist Violence Portends New Threat to Myanmar |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/buddhist-violence-portends-new-threat-to-myanmar-11546626324 |accessdate=5 January 2019 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=4 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=AA Frees 14 Police, 4 Women Captured in Attack on Border Posts |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/aa-frees-14-police-4-women-captured-attack-border-posts.html |accessdate=11 January 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the attacks, the Office of the President of Myanmar held a high-level meeting on national security in the capital [[Naypyidaw]] on 7 January 2019, and instructed the Defense Ministry to increase troop deployments in the areas that were attacked and to use aircraft if necessary.<ref>{{cite news |title=President Convenes Top-Level Security Meeting in Wake of AA Attacks |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/president-convenes-top-level-security-meeting-wake-aa-attacks.html |accessdate=11 January 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=8 January 2019}}</ref> Subsequent clashes between the [[Myanmar Army]] and the Arakan Army were reported in [[Maungdaw Township|Maungdaw]], [[Buthidaung Township|Buthidaung]], [[Kyauktaw Township|Kyauktaw]], [[Rathedaung Township|Rathedaung]] and [[Ponnagyun Township]]s, forcing out over 5,000 civilians from their homes,<ref>{{cite news |title=UN Calls for 'Rapid and Unimpeded' Aid Access to Myanmar's Rakhine |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/un-calls-rapid-unimpeded-aid-access-myanmars-rakhine.html |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Myanmar villagers flee to Bangladesh amid Rakhine violence |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/02/myanmar-villagers-flee-bangladesh-rakhine-violence-190208054201660.html |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=www.aljazeera.com |date=8 February 2019}}</ref> hundreds of whom (mostly Rakhine and [[Mro people (Awa Khami)|Khami]]) have fled across the border into Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news |title=203 Buddhists from Rakhine entered Bangladesh in last 5 days |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/nation/2019/02/07/203-buddhists-from-rakhine-entered-bangladesh-in-last-5-days |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=Dhaka Tribune |date=6 February 2019}}</ref> Civilian casualties,<ref>{{cite news |title=Three Villagers Shot Dead in Fighting Between Gov't, AA Troops in Rakhine |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/three-villagers-shot-dead-in-fighting-between-govt-aa-troops-in-rakhine.html |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u1031\u1019\u102c\u1004\u1039\u1031\u1010\u102c \u101b\u1014\u1039\u1031\u1021\u102c\u1004\u1039\u103b\u1019\u1004\u1039\u101b\u103c\u102c\u1011\u1032\u1000\u102d\u102f \u101c\u1000\u1039\u1014\u1000\u1039\u1080\u1000\u102e\u1038\u1000\u103a\u101c\u102d\u102f\u1094 \u101c\u1030\u1042 \u1026\u1038 \u1012\u100f\u1039\u101b\u102c\u101b |url=https://www.rfa.org/burmese/news/weapon-hit-child-injure-01162019072943.html |accessdate=18 January 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |date=16 January 2019 |language=my}}</ref> arbitrary beatings<ref>{{cite news |title=\u101e\u1019\u102e\u1038\u101c\u103d\u101b\u103c\u102c\u1001\u1036 \u1043\u1026\u1038 \u101b\u102d\u102f\u1000\u1039\u108f\u103d\u1000\u1039\u1001\u1036\u101b\u1010\u101a\u1039\u101c\u102d\u102f\u1094 \u1031\u103b\u1015\u102c |url=https://www.rfa.org/burmese/news/soldiers-hit-thameehla-villagers-01282019012623.html |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |date=28 January 2019 |language=my}}</ref> and detentions of ethnic Rakhines,<ref>{{cite news |title=\u101e\u101b\u1000\u1039\u103b\u1015\u1004\u1039\u1031\u1000\u103a\u1038\u101b\u103c\u102c\u1021\u102f\u1015\u1039\u1001\u103a\u1033\u1015\u1039\u1031\u101b\u1038\u1019\u103d\u1034\u1038\u1021\u1015\u102b\u1021\u1040\u1004\u1039 \u1041\u1045 \u1026\u1038\u1000\u102d\u102f \u1010\u1015\u1039\u1019\u1031\u1010\u102c\u1039 \u1016\u1019\u1039\u1038\u1006\u102e\u1038 |url=https://www.rfa.org/burmese/news/mm-military-detained-15villagers-including-village-chief-in-butheetaung-01142019065934.html |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |language=my}}</ref> forced seizures of property,<ref>{{cite news |title=\u101c\u1030\u1094\u1021\u1001\u103c\u1004\u1037\u1039\u1021\u1031\u101b\u1038\u1001\u103a\u1033\u102d\u1038\u1031\u1016\u102c\u1000\u1039\u1010\u102c\u1031\u1010\u103c \u101b\u102d\u103d\u1010\u101a\u1039\u1006\u102f\u102d\u1010\u1032\u1037 \u1005\u103c\u1015\u1039\u1005\u1032\u103c\u1001\u103a\u1000\u1039\u1000\u102d\u102f \u1010\u1015\u1039\u1019\u1031\u1010\u102c\u1039\u103b\u1004\u1004\u1039\u1038\u1006\u102f\u102d |url=https://www.rfa.org/burmese/news/army-declined-aa-statement-01272019060729.html |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |date=27 January 2019 |language=my}}</ref> and blockage of food aid and medical relief by the Tatmadaw have also been reported.<ref>{{cite news |title=Concern Mounts for IDPs in Northern Rakhine as Army Blocks Aid Shipments |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/concern-mounts-idps-northern-rakhine-army-blocks-aid-shipments.html |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Shan State ===\n[[File:UWSA soldiers stand at attention during ceremonies.jpg|thumb|UWSA troops standing at attention during a military ceremony.]]\n\nThe [[Shan people]] are the largest ethnic group in [[Shan State]] and the second largest in Myanmar. In 1947, the [[Panglong Agreement]] was negotiated between [[Aung San]], a prominent [[founding father]] of Myanmar, and Shan leaders, which would have given the Shan the option to split from Myanmar a decade after independence if they were unsatisfied with the central government.<ref name=\"Maung\"/> This was, however, not honoured by the post-independence government following Aung San's assassination.<ref name=\"ThantMyint\">{{cite book|title=The River of Lost Footsteps \u2013 Histories of Burma|pages=274\u2013289|author=U Thant Myint|year=2006|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|isbn=978-0-374-16342-6}}</ref> During the Tatmadaw's heavy militarisation of the state in the late 1940s and early 1950s, locals accused them of mistreating, torturing, robbing, raping, unlawfully arresting and massacring villagers. As a result, on 21 May 1958, an armed resistance movement, led by Sao Noi and Saw Yanna, was started in Shan State.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nOne the largest Shan insurgent groups in Myanmar is the [[Shan State Army - South]] (SSA-S), which has around 6,000 to 8,000 soldiers, and was led by [[Yawd Serk]] until his resignation on 2 February 2014. The SSA-S maintains bases along the Myanmar\u2013Thailand border, and signed a ceasefire agreement with the government on 2 December 2011.<ref name=\"MMrcss\">{{cite web|title=Restoration Council of Shan State (RCSS/SSA-S)|url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/stakeholders/stakeholders-overview/168-ssa-s|website=www.mmpeacemonitor.org|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=12 March 2018|language=en-gb|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Myanmar National Democratic Alliance Army]] (MNDAA) is a [[Kokang people|Kokang]] insurgent group active in the [[Kokang Self-Administered Zone]] in northern Shan State. The group signed a ceasefire agreement with the government in 1989, the same year it was founded, which lasted for two decades [[2009 Kokang incident|until 2009]], when violence erupted between the group and government forces.<ref name=\"WP\">{{cite news|last1=Johnston|first1=Tim|title=China Urges Burma to Bridle Ethnic Militia Uprising at Border|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/28/AR2009082803764.html|work=The Washington Post|date=29 August 2009}}</ref> Violence again erupted between the MNDAA and government forces [[2015 Kokang offensive|in 2015]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/kokang-02132015185129.html|title=Myanmar Kokang Rebels Deny Receiving Chinese Weapons|website=Radio Free Asia|accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref> and 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Deadly clashes hit Kokang in Myanmar's Shan state|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/03/deadly-clashes-hit-kokang-myanmar-shan-state-170306143633608.html|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=wcww.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar rebel clashes in Kokang leave 30 dead|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39182713|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=BBC News|date=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn late November 2016, the [[Northern Alliance (Myanmar)|Northern Alliance]]\u2014which consists of four [[Insurgency|insurgent groups]], the [[Arakan Army (Kachin State)|Arakan Army]] (AA), the [[Kachin Independence Army]] (KIA), the [[Myanmar National Democratic Alliance Army]] (MNDAA) and the [[Ta'ang National Liberation Army]] (TNLA)\u2014[[Muse offensive|attacked towns and border posts]] along the [[China\u2013Myanmar border]] in [[Mu Se Township|Muse Township]], northern Shan State.<ref name=\"Nadi\">{{cite news|last1=Nadi|first1=Nang Mya|title=8 killed as ethnic rebels hit Muse- DVB Multimedia Group|url=http://www.dvb.no/news/8-killed-ethnic-rebels-hit-muse/72729|accessdate=3 May 2018|work=DVB Multimedia Group|date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504010454/http://www.dvb.no/news/8-killed-ethnic-rebels-hit-muse/72729|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Aung|first1=Thu Thu|title=Ethnic armed groups launch attack near Muse|url=https://www.mmtimes.com/national-news/23800-ethnic-armed-groups-launch-attack-near-muse.html|accessdate=3 May 2018|work=The Myanmar Times|date=21 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> The insurgents captured the town of [[Mong Ko]] on 25 November 2016<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weng|first1=Lawi|title=Ethnic Armed Groups Claim Control of Border Town|url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/ethnic-armed-groups-claim-control-of-border-town.html|accessdate=3 May 2018|work=The Irrawaddy|date=28 November 2016}}</ref> and maintained control of it until they withdrew from the town on 4 December 2016 to avoid civilian casualties from [[airstrike]]s by the [[Myanmar Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aung|first1=Thu Thu|title=Air strikes reported as Shan State conflict spreads|url=https://www.mmtimes.com/national-news/23870-air-strikes-reported-as-shan-state-conflict-spreads.html|accessdate=3 May 2018|work=The Myanmar Times|date=24 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Noreen|first1=Naw|title=Burmese army recaptures Mongko- DVB Multimedia Group|url=http://www.dvb.no/news/burmese-army-recaptures-mongko/72958|accessdate=3 May 2018|work=DVB Multimedia Group|date=5 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503181057/http://www.dvb.no/news/burmese-army-recaptures-mongko/72958|archive-date=3 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2019, Northern Alliance insurgents attacked a military college in [[Nawnghkio Township]], killing 15.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aung |first1=Thu Thu |title=Myanmar insurgents attack elite military college, other targets; 15... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-insurgency/myanmar-insurgents-attack-elite-military-college-other-targets-15-killed-idUSKCN1V50EH |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Reuters |date=15 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Myanmar rebels kill over a dozen in attack in Shan state |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/myanmar-rebels-kill-dozen-attack-army-college-190815233509598.html |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Al Jazeera |date=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zaw |first1=Moe |last2=Oo |first2=Aung Lwin |title=More than a Dozen People Killed in Myanmar Rebel Attacks |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/more-dozen-people-killed-myanmar-rebel-attacks |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Voice of America |date=15 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Win |first1=Pyae Sone |title=Myanmar ethnic rebel alliance makes coordinated attacks |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/myanmar-ethnic-rebel-alliance-makes-coordinated-attacks/2019/08/15/c0d24e0e-bf56-11e9-a8b0-7ed8a0d5dc5d_story.html |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=15 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Further clashes occurred in the following days,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ambulance driver killed in Myanmar as army battles rebels |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/08/ambulance-driver-killed-myanmar-army-battles-rebels-190818103407132.html |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Al Jazeera |date=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shi |first1=Yinglun |title=Armed attacks escalate in Myanmar northern Shan state |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/19/c_138320519.htm |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Xinhua |date=19 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rebel Fighters Attack 2 Towns in Myanmar's Shan State |url=https://www.irrawaddy.com/news/burma/rebel-fighters-attack-2-towns-in-myanmars-shan-state.html |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=The Irrawaddy |date=19 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Foreigners, Migrant Workers Evacuated From Conflict Zone in Myanmar's Shan State |url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/foreigners-migrant-workers-evacuated-08222019171628.html |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Radio Free Asia |date=22 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> with Myanmar's military warning there could be a full-scale war if the Northern Alliance did not halt their attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bnionline.net/en/news/myanmar-army-warns-full-scale-war-shan-state|title=Myanmar army warns of full-scale war in Shan State|accessdate=24 August 2019|publisher=BNI}}</ref>\n\n== Political factors ==\nPrior to independence, [[Aung San]], considered a founding father of Myanmar, had convinced local Shan leaders to join him in his pursuit for independence, and with them, negotiated the Panglong Agreement in 1947. The agreement guaranteed the right to self-determination, political representation in the post-independence government and economic equality amongst the various ethnic groups. It also gave the [[Chin people|Chin]], [[Kachin people|Kachin]] and [[Shan people|Shan]] people the option to separate from Myanmar after a decade if their states' leaders were unhappy with the central government. However, after Aung San's assassination, this was not honoured by the government, and has been one of the causes of insurgencies in those states.<ref name=\"ThantMyint\"/>\n\nWhilst some groups continue to fight for full independence and for the right for self-determination of their people, groups such as the [[Chin National Front]] (CNF) and the [[Karen National Union]] (KNU) have since fought instead for [[regional autonomy]] and a [[federalism|federal system]] of government in Myanmar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.knuhq.org/language/en_gb|title=Karen National Union Website \u2013 English|access-date=28 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128221719/http://www.knuhq.org/language/en_gb/|archive-date=28 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[8888 Uprising]], [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] emerged as a national symbol for democracy, after leading the largest opposition party, the [[National League for Democracy]] (NLD). The [[military junta]] arranged a [[1990 Myanmar general election|general election in 1990]] and Aung San Suu Kyi's party, the [[National League for Democracy|National League for Democracy (NLD)]] won a majority of the vote. However, the military junta refused to recognise the results and instead placed Aung San Suu Kyi under [[house arrest]] for 15 years.\n\nIn 2007, hundreds of thousands of monks protested against the military junta's rule, and called for [[free election]]s, [[minority rights]] and the release of [[political prisoner]]s in an event now known as the [[Saffron Revolution]].<ref name=\"August, 2007 Burma\">{{cite web |title=Human Rights Concern |url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/all-countries/myanmar-burma/page.do?id=1011205 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624155454/http://www.amnestyusa.org/all-countries/myanmar-burma/page.do?id=1011205 |archivedate=24 June 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=7 April 2009  }}</ref> The protest originally began in response to the government's removal of price subsidies for [[compressed natural gas]].<ref name=\"Fuel\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6947251.stm |title=BBC NEWS &#124; World &#124; Asia-Pacific &#124; Burma leaders double fuel prices |publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the government introduced a new [[Constitution of Myanmar|constitution]] following [[2011\u201315 Myanmar political reforms|political reforms]], and thousands of [[political prisoner]]s were released, including Aung San Suu Kyi. In November 2014, the NLD attempted to make amendments to the constitution, in response to a clause that made Aung San Suu Kyi ineligible to become [[President of Myanmar]] if her party won an election. These amendments however, were rejected.<ref>Landler, M. (14 November 2014). Obama and Aung San Suu Kyi Meet Again, With Battle Scars. Retrieved 24 November 2014, from https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/15/world/asia/obama-aung-san-suu-kyi-myanmar.html?_r=0</ref>\n\n== Human rights violations ==\n{{main|Human rights in Myanmar}}\n\nThe [[government of Myanmar]] has been accused of using \"[[scorched earth]]\" tactics against civilians, most notably in Kayin State. The accusations included burning down entire villages, planting [[landmines]], using civilians as slave labour, using civilians as minesweepers and the rape and murder of Karen women.<ref name=\"NYFree\"/> According to a report by legal firm [[DLA Piper]], whose report was presented to the [[United Nations Security Council]], these tactics against the Karen have been identified as [[ethnic cleansing]].<ref name=\"DLApiper\"/>\n\nBoth sides have been accused of using [[landmines]], which have caused hundreds of accidental civilian injuries and deaths. The [[Karen National Union]] (KNU) has been accused of planting landmines in rural areas, most of which have not been disarmed. The KNU claim that landmines are vital to repelling government forces, because it \"discourages them from attacking civilians\". However, a majority of those who fall victim to KNU planted landmines are local villagers, rather than government soldiers.<ref name=\"alJazeeraYoutube\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wa_8Sc-TUcE|title=The world's longest ongoing war|date=13 August 2011|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> Victims of landmines must travel to the Myanmar\u2013Thailand border to seek treatment, as local hospitals and facilities lack proper equipment and funding.<ref name=\"thediplomat\">{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/the-landmine-victims-of-myanmars-civil-war/|title=The Landmine Victims of Myanmar's Civil War &#124; The Diplomat|author=Arthur Nazaryan, The Diplomat|publisher=thediplomat.com|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth sides have also been accused of using thousands of [[child soldiers]], despite the fact that the government of Myanmar and seven insurgent groups signed an agreement with [[UNICEF]] in 2012, promising not to exploit children for military and political gains. The [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO) has accused both sides of continuing to use child soldiers despite the agreement. According to the ILO, the Tatmadaw has discharged hundreds of child soldiers since 2012; however, the ILO also estimated that at least 340 child soldiers had been recruited by the Tatmadaw between 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dvb.no/news/burmese-army-releases-91-child-soldiers-unicef-burma-myanmar/42936 |title=Burmese army releases 91 child soldiers: UNICEF |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912212226/https://www.dvb.no/news/burmese-army-releases-91-child-soldiers-unicef-burma-myanmar/42936 |archivedate=12 September 2014 }}</ref> Meanwhile, insurgent groups such as the MNDAA, SSA-S, and TNLA have reportedly [[Impressment|press-ganged]] minors into their armies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thar |first1=Chan |title=Armed ethnic groups press-gang villagers |url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/armed-ethnic-groups-press-gang-villagers.html |accessdate=19 February 2019 |work=The Myanmar Times |date=15 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most notable cases of the use child soldiers in Myanmar was that of twins [[Johnny and Luther Htoo]], the leaders of [[God's Army (revolutionary group)|God's Army]], a former rebel faction. When the God's Army was formed in 1997, the pair were just ten-years-old.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.globalpolitician.com/default.asp?21979-myanmar-burma|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818185124/http://globalpolitician.com/default.asp?21979-myanmar-burma|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 August 2013|magazine=[[Global Politician]]|title=Bizarre 'God's Army' Led By Young Boys Surrenders|author=Richard S. Ehrlick|date=27 July 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Refugee and internal displacement crisis ==\n[[File:Mae La refugee camp2.jpg|thumb|[[Mae La refugee camp|Mae La Camp]] in [[Tak Province|Tak]], [[Thailand]], one of the largest of nine [[UNHCR]] camps in Thailand where over 700,000 refugees, asylum seekers and [[Statelessness|stateless]] persons have fled.<ref>{{cite web |title=2013 UNHCR country operations profile \u2013 Thailand |url=http://www.unhcr.org/pages/49e489646.html |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Kutupalong Refugee Camp (Maaz Hussain-VOA).jpg|thumb|[[Kutupalong refugee camp]] in [[Bangladesh]], home to nearly 550,000 [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]] refugees who live in makeshift shelters.]]\n\nThe conflict has resulted in a large number of both civilian deaths and refugees, with many refugees fleeing to neighbouring countries such as [[Thailand]], [[China]], [[India]], and [[Bangladesh]]. The persecution of [[Burmese Indians]] and other ethnic minorities after the 1962 coup led to the expulsion of nearly 300,000 people.<ref name=\"Smith1\">{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Martin|title=Burma: Insurgency and the politics of ethnicity|date=1991|pages=43\u201344|publisher=Zed Books|location=London and New Jersey|isbn=0862328683|edition=2. impr.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s4NuAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> The UN estimated that between 1996 and 2006, around 1&nbsp;million people were [[Internally displaced persons|internally displaced]] inside Myanmar, over 230,000 of whom remain displaced in the southeast of the country, and 128,000 refugees lived in temporary shelters on the Myanmar\u2013Thailand border.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Human Rights Council, Report of the Special Rapporteur on the situation of human rights in Burma, Paulo Sergio Pinheiro, 12 February 2007</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2014/02/02/fort-wayne-refugees-from-myanmar-worried-about-policy-changes/5166423/|title=Fort Wayne refugees from Myanmar worried about policy changes|date=2 February 2014|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> In August 2007, approximately 160,000 refugees fled to nine refugee camps along the Myanmar\u2013Thailand border and the Thai border provinces of [[Chiang Mai Province|Chiang Mai]] and [[Ratchaburi]]. Approximately 62% of the refugee population consisted of displaced Karen people. Humanitarian organisations such as [[Doctors Without Borders]] have since sent workers and medical support to the refugees.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Joanna|last2=Fuller|first2=Holly|last3=Scott|first3=Kelly|title=Governance in refugee camps on the Thai/Burma border|url=http://brownschool.wustl.edu/sites/DevPractice/Refugees%20Group%20Project/Governance%20in%20Refugee%20Camps%20on%20Thai%20and%20Burma%20Border.pdf|accessdate=23 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610021517/http://brownschool.wustl.edu/sites/DevPractice/Refugees%20Group%20Project/Governance%20in%20Refugee%20Camps%20on%20Thai%20and%20Burma%20Border.pdf|archive-date=10 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the conflict, government officials in Myanmar have been accused of forcefully removing civilians living in conflict areas and confiscating their property, in order to repurpose them for commercial, industrial, and military projects.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"oxfordburmaalliance.org\">Ethnic Nationalities of Burma. (n.d.). Retrieved 23 November 2014, from http://www.oxfordburmaalliance.org/ethnic-groups.html</ref><ref>2014 UNHCR country operations profile \u2013 Myanmar. (1 January 2014). Retrieved 8 November 2014.</ref>\n\nIn Rakhine State, there were around 75,000 internally displaced [[Rohingya people|Rohingyas]] in 2012, according to Refugee International.<ref>\"About 75,000 Rohingyas in Myanmar camps: Refugee International\". The Hindu (Chennai, India). 29 September 2012. Retrieved 27 March 2013.</ref> UNICEF has reported that living conditions in Rohingya refugee camps in Rakhine State are \"wholly inadequate\" and lacks access to basic services.<ref>Democratic Voice of Burma: Level of suffering in Arakan 'never seen before': UN. (18 June 2014). Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref> In October 2017, there were an estimated 947,000 [[Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Is refugee crisis 'textbook ethnic cleansing'?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-41566561|accessdate=20 March 2018|work=BBC News|date=2018}}</ref> The Rohingya people have been described by the United Nations as \"among the world's least wanted\" and \"one of the world's most persecuted minorities.\"<ref>A Handbook of Terrorism and Insurgency in South East Asia, editor=Tan, Andrew T. H., chapter=Chapter 16, State Terrorism in Arakan, author=Islam, Syed Serajul Islam. Edward Elgar Publishing. 2007. p. 342. {{ISBN|978-1-84542-543-2}}.</ref>\n\nThe Internal Displacement Monitoring Centre reports a total of 401,000 people internally displaced in Myanmar as of 2018, owing both to man-made and natural disasters as well as conflict and violence.<ref name=\":0\" /> This figure includes IDPs across the country, with 131,000 in Rakhine State, 97,000 in Kachin State, 50,000 in Kayin State, 40,000 in Tanintharyi Region, 27,000 in Karenni State, 22,000 in Bago Region, 18,000 in Mon State, 15,000 in Shan State and 1,300 in Chin State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.internal-displacement.org/countries/myanmar|title=Myanmar|last=internal displacement monitoring centre|date=|website=internal displacement monitoring centre|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Of these total displacements, IDMC estimates that approximately 42,000 people were newly displaced in 2018 by conflict and violence.<ref name=\":0\" /> Compared to 2017, the rate of new displacements was lower in Rakhine State but higher in Kachin State and northern Shan State, which together saw approximately 36,000 people displaced.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Global Camp Coordination and Camp Management Cluster (CCCM) estimates at least 941,000 people in Myanmar remain in need of humanitarian assistance, with over 128,000 people living in IDP camps in Rakhine State and over 105,000 people displaced in Kachin State and northern Shan State.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://cccmcluster.org/operations/myanmar|title=Myanmar {{!}} CCCM Cluster|website=cccmcluster.org|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> While many displacements last only for the duration of active fighting, protracted displacement is evidenced by camps in Kachin State, Rakhine State, and Shan State.<ref name=\":0\" /> Living situations in these camps are often overcrowded with inadequate shelter, sanitation, healthcare, food, and education.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Human Rights Council|date=28 September 2018|title=Report of the independent international fact-finding mission on Myanmar|url=http://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/a_hrc_39_64.pdf|journal=United Nations General Assembly|volume=A/HRC/39/64|pages=|via=}}</ref> In total, approximately 35 percent of IDPs in Myanmar are estimated to live in non-government controlled areas that have limited if not wholly restricted access as of November 2019, complicating relief efforts both for international and local organizations.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Ceasefire attempts ==\n{{main|Ceasefires in Myanmar}}\n\nUnder the new constitutional reforms in 2011, state level and union level ceasefire agreements were made with several insurgent groups. 14 out of 17 of the largest rebel factions signed a ceasefire agreement with the new reformed government. According to the [[Myanmar Peace Center|Myanmar Peace Monitoring group]], clashes between the Kachin Independence Organisation (KIO), its allies, and the government, have displaced hundreds of thousands of people, and created another severe humanitarian crisis in Kachin and northern Shan State.<ref name=\"MMoverview\">{{cite web|title=Conflicts, communal violence and IDPs |url=http://www.mmpeacemonitor.org/conflict/conflict-overview|publisher=Myanmar Peace Monitor|accessdate=21 October 2015|date=20 May 2013}}</ref> All of the 14 signatories wanted negotiations in accordance with the [[Panglong Agreement]] of 1947, which granted self-determination, a federal system of government (meaning regional autonomy), religious freedom and ethnic minority rights. However, the new constitution, only had a few clauses dedicated to minority rights, and therefore, the government discussed with rebel factions using the new constitution for reference, rather than the Panglong Agreement. There was no inclusive plan or body that represented all the factions, and as a result, in resent, the KNU backed out of the conference and complained the lack of independence for each party within the ethnic bloc.<ref name=\"Nai, A. 2014\">Nai, A. (3 September 2014). Democratic Voice of Burma: UNFC opens 2 top positions for KNU. Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref> However, most of the negotiations between the ''State Peace Deal Commission'' and rebel factions were formal and peaceful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-asia-16523691|title=World Asia|accessdate=27 March 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2015, a draft of the [[Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement]] (NCA) was finalised between representatives from 15 different insurgent groups (all part of the Nationwide Ceasefire Coordination Team or NCCT) and the government of Myanmar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/03/myanmar-government-rebels-reach-ceasefire-deal-150331194752849.html|title=Myanmar government and rebels agree on ceasefire draft|publisher=}}</ref> However, only eight of the 15 insurgent groups signed the final agreement on 15 October 2015.<ref name=\"rfaNCA\"/> The signing was witnessed by observers and delegates from the [[United Nations]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Norway]], [[Japan]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=\"blogs.cfr.org\"/><ref name=\"Ray Pagnucco and Jennifer Peters\"/>\n\nThe [[Union Peace Conference - 21st Century Panglong]] was held from 31 August to 4 September 2016 with several different organisations as representatives, in an attempt to mediate between the government and different insurgent groups. The name was a reference to the original [[Panglong Conference]] held during [[British rule in Burma|British rule]] in 1947, which was negotiated between [[Aung San]] and ethnic leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/myanmars-panglong-peace-conference-to-include-all-armed-ethnic-groups-07052016152026.html|title=Myanmar's Panglong Peace Conference to Include All Armed Ethnic Groups|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== International responses ==\n{{further|International reactions to the Rohingya genocide}}\n\nSince 1991, the [[UN General Assembly]] has adopted twenty-five different resolutions regarding Myanmar's government, condemning previous [[military junta]]s for their systematic violations of human rights and lack of political freedom.<ref name=\"ALTUN\">{{cite web|title=UN General Assembly Resolutions on Burma \u2013 ALTSEAN Burma|url=http://www.altsean.org/Research/UN%20Dossier/UNGA.htm|website=www.altsean.org|publisher=Alternative Asean Network on Burma|accessdate=4 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104120635/http://www.altsean.org/Research/UN%20Dossier/UNGA.htm|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2009 they urged the then [[State Peace and Development Council|ruling junta]] to take urgent measures to end violations of international human rights and humanitarian laws in the country.<ref>\"UN General Assembly Resolution: Time for Concrete Action\" (Press release). International Federation for Human Rights. 20 November 2009. Retrieved 4 January 2010.</ref> The request was mostly honoured during [[2011\u201315 Myanmar political reforms|political reforms]] that begun in 2011 and ended in 2015.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nReports of human rights abuses committed by the\u00a0military and local paramilitaries prompted the UN Human Rights Council to launch an independent international fact-finding mission in March 2017, with which Myanmar's government failed to cooperate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/en/hrbodies/hrc/myanmarffm/pages/index.aspx|title=OHCHR {{!}} Myanmar FFM Independent International Fact-Finding Mission on Myanmar|website=www.ohchr.org|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The mission's report (A/HRC/39/64) released in September 2018 highlighted \"clear patterns\" of serious human rights abuses and violations of international humanitarian law in Kachin State, Rakhine State, and Shan State since 2011. The Tatmadaw are accused of deliberate and systematic targeting of civilians, sexual violence, discriminatory rhetoric against minorities, and impunity for its soldiers.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nEyewitness testimony alleged that in Rakhine State, \"clearance operations\" by the Tatmadaw amounted to planned and deliberate mass killings in at least 54 locations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Hundreds and perhaps thousands of Rohingya women and girls were reported to have been raped, including in mass gang rapes, and at least 392 Rohingya villages were burned to the ground.<ref name=\":2\" /> The report also highlighted the conviction of [[Wa Lone]] and [[Kyaw Soe Oo]], two Reuters reporters who had exposed the military's [[Inn Din massacre|extrajudicial killing of ten Rohingya men]] and were subsequently imprisoned; the journalists have since been released and awarded a 2019 [[Pulitzer Prize]] for their reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/staff-reuters-notable-contributions-wa-lone-and-kyaw-soe-oo|title=Staff of Reuters, with notable contributions from Wa Lone and Kyaw Soe Oo|last=The Pulitzer Prizes|date=2019|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to violence against Rohingya communities, the report noted Tatamadaw abuses against ethnic Rakhine, including forced labor, sexual violence, forced evictions, and killings. It also highlighted abuses committed by insurgent groups in Kachin State, Rakhine State, and Shan State, including forced taxation, destruction of property, rape, and killings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/Pages/NewsDetail.aspx?NewsID=23575&LangID=E|title=OHCHR {{!}} Myanmar: UN Fact-Finding Mission releases its full account of massive violations by military in Rakhine, Kachin and Shan States|website=www.ohchr.org|access-date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe mission further documented similar patterns of human rights violations in Kachin and Shan States, which witnessed a drastic increase in fighting between the military and ethnic insurgent groups in the years preceding the report. The alleged abuses perpetrated include the widespread looting and destruction of homes, unlawful killings, forced labor, sexual violence, and enforced disappearances.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe mission called for an investigation and the prosecution of military leaders, in particular commander-in-chief Senior General [[Min Aung Hlaing]], in the [[International Criminal Court]] (ICC) for genocide, crimes against humanity, and war crimes. On 11 November 2019 [[The Gambia]] filed a lawsuit in the International Court of Justice against Myanmar; State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi defended Myanmar's military generals against genocide accusations in public hearings in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50741094|title=Suu Kyi rejects genocide claims at top UN court|date=11 December 2019|access-date=12 December 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Foreign support ==\n\n=== China ===\nThe People's Republic of China allegedly gave logistical aid to the [[Communist Party of Burma]] (CPB) during the [[communist insurgency in Myanmar]], in support of the party's [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism|Marxist-Leninist-Maoist]] ideology.<ref name=\"Gibson\"/><ref name=\"Smith2\">{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Martin|title=Burma: Insurgency and the politics of ethnicity|date=1991|publisher=Zed Books|location=London and New Jersey|isbn=0862328683|edition=2. impr.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s4NuAAAAMAAJ}}{{page needed|date=January 2017}}</ref> After the CPB's armed wing agreed to disarm in 1988, China was accused by Myanmar of continuing to support insurgent groups operating along its border, such as the [[United Wa State Army]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucdp.uu.se/gpdatabase/gpcountry.php?id=112&regionSelect=7-Eastern_Asia#,|title=UCDP Conflict Encyclopedia, Myanmar (Burma)|publisher=|accessdate=29 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102193918/http://www.ucdp.uu.se/gpdatabase/gpcountry.php?id=112&regionSelect=7-Eastern_Asia#,|archive-date=2 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, China pledged to support Myanmar's ongoing peace process by encouraging China-friendly insurgent groups to attend peace talks with the Burmese government and by sending more soldiers to secure its border with Myanmar.<ref name=\"RFA\"/><ref name=\"SCMP\"/><ref name=\"USIP\"/> China also offered $3 million [[United States dollar|USD]] to fund the negotiations. However, the Burmese government has expressed suspicion over China's involvement in the peace process, due to China's alleged links to the [[Northern Alliance (Burma)|Northern Alliance]] and the United Wa State Army.<ref name=\"VOA1\">{{cite news|last1=Vrieze|first1=Paul|title=Into Myanmar's Stalled Peace Process Steps China|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/myanmar-peace-process-china/3746486.html|accessdate=16 August 2017|work=[[Voice of America|VOA]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Pakistan ===\nFrom 1948 to 1950, Pakistan sent aid to [[Mujahideen#Myanmar (Burma)|mujahideen]] in northern Arakan (present-day Rakhine State). In 1950, the Pakistani government warned their Burmese counterparts about their treatment of Muslims. In response, Burmese Prime Minister [[U Nu]] immediately sent a Muslim diplomat, [[Pe Khin]], to negotiate a [[memorandum of understanding]]. Pakistan agreed to cease aid to the mujahideen and arrest members of the group. In 1954, mujahid leader Mir Kassem was arrested by Pakistani authorities, and many of his followers later surrendered to the Burmese government.<ref name=\"UNu\">U Nu, U Nu: Saturday's Son, (New Haven and London: Yale University Press) 1975, p. 272.</ref>\n\n=== Thailand ===\nThailand had been a vocal supporter of various insurgent groups in Myanmar, condemning actions done by the then ruling military juntas and allowing weapons and ammunition to be smuggled through its border through lax enforcement.<ref name=\"Thai\">{{cite book|url=http://www.drugtext.org/library/books/McCoy/book/62.htm |author=[[Alfred W. McCoy]], with Cathleen B. Read and Leonard P. Adams II |title=\"The Shan Rebellion: The Road to Chaos\", from The Politics of Heroin in Southeast Asia: CIA Complicity in the Global Drug Trade |edition=2003 |publisher=Lawrence Hill Books |isbn=1-55652-483-8 |accessdate=8 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923173234/http://www.drugtext.org/library/books/McCoy/book/62.htm |archivedate=23 September 2011 |year=2003 }}</ref> However, in 1995, the Thai government secured its border with Myanmar and stopped all logistical support going through Thailand after they signed a major economic deal with Myanmar.<ref name=\"Lintner1995\"/>\n\n=== United States ===\nStarting in 1951, the [[CIA]] began aiding [[Kuomintang in Burma|Kuomintang soldiers that fled to Myanmar from China]] following the advance of [[People's Liberation Army|Chinese communist forces]] into [[Yunnan province]]. This included ''Operation Paper'', which involved supplying them with non-lethal aid via Thailand until 1953, when they airlifted 7,000 soldiers to [[Taiwan]] and ended the operation.<ref name=\"Gibson\"/>\n\n=== Foreign fighters ===\n[[Dave Everett]] was a member of the [[Australia]]n [[Special Air Service Regiment]] before leaving in 1986 and joining the [[Karen National Liberation Army]] (KNLA) as a mercenary. Everett fought alongside the KNLA under the alias \"Steve\" and trained insurgents, helping them improve their marksmanship and teaching them how to use [[Claymore mine|claymore anti-personnel mines]]. In order to fund his time with the KNLA, Everett perpetrated several robberies in Australia with the help of accomplices and took piloting lessons so he could smuggle weapons into Myanmar. Everett returned to Australia a year later in 1987.<ref name=\"Adshead\">{{cite news|last1=Adshead|first1=Gary|title=Cancer kills notorious SAS man|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/17172626/cancer-kills-notorious-sas-man/|work=The West Australian|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=8 June 2014|ref=V1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714214943/https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/17172626/cancer-kills-notorious-sas-man/|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFormer members of the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[green beret]]s, [[French Foreign Legion]], and [[Russia]]n [[Spetsnaz]] have also been reported fighting alongside insurgents as recently as 2012.<ref name=\"VICE1\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Politics of Myanmar]]\n* [[Ceasefires in Myanmar]]\n* [[Opium production in Myanmar]]\n* [[Ethnic separatism]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* International Center for Transitional Justice \"[https://www.ictj.org/publication/opening-remedies-myanmar Opening up Remedies in Myanmar 12/9/2015]\"\n* International Center for Transitional Justice \"[https://www.ictj.org/publication/navigating-paths-justice-myanmars-transition Navigating Paths to Justice in Myanmar's Transition 7/18/2014]\"\n* Kipgen, Nehginpao. \"Democracy Movement in Myanmar: Problems and Challenges.\" New Delhi: Ruby Press & Co., 2014. Print.\n\n== External links ==\n'''News:'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050724083834/http://www.dvb.no/ Democratic Voice of Burma] \u2013 Norwegian-based radio station that provides news to the people of Burma\n* [http://www.mizzima.com/ Mizzima News] \u2013 Multimedia news organisation based in India, run by exiled journalists. ''See also: [[Mizzima News]]''\n* [http://www.myanmathadin.com/ MyanmaThadin] \u2013 Myanmar (Burma) News & Community Hub\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6407305.stm BBC News: The fighting spirit of Burma's Karen] (2007)\n\n'''Organisations:'''\n* [http://www.helfenohnegrenzen.de/ Help without frontiers] \u2013 German relief organisation working with Shan and Karen refugees living in refugee camps on and around the Myanmar\u2013Thailand border\n* [https://www.ictj.org/our-work/regions-and-countries/burmamyanmar International Center for Transitional Justice (Myanmar)] \u2013 Non-profit organisation specialising in [[transitional justice]]\n* [http://mmpeacemonitor.org/ Myanmar Peace Monitor] \u2013 Non-governmental organisation based in Thailand that monitors Myanmar's ongoing peace process\n* [http://en.pyidaungsuinstitute.org/ Pyidaungsu Institute] \u2013 Political institute based in Chaing Mai, Thailand focused on achieving political stability and peace in Myanmar\n\n{{Myanmar topics}}\n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:Internal conflict in Myanmar| ]]\n[[Category:2010s civil wars]]\n[[Category:20th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:21st-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:History of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Politics of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Ethnic conflicts|Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Revolution-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Ethnicity-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Communism-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Coup-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Religion-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Separatist rebellion-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Civil wars post-1945]]\n[[Category:Civil wars involving the states and peoples of Asia]]\n[[Category:Ongoing conflicts]]\n[[Category:Proxy wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Series of primarily ethnic conflicts within Myanmar that began shortly after the country became independent from the United Kingdom in 1948}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Inadequate lead|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Internal conflict in Myanmar\n| partof      =\n| image       = Armed conflict zones in Myanmar.png\n| image_size  = 220px\n| caption     = Map of armed conflict zones in Myanmar (Burma). States and regions affected by fighting during and after 1995 are highlighted in yellow.\n| date        = 2 April 1948<ref name=\"Lintner1990\">{{cite book|last1=Lintner|first1=Bertil|last2=Wyatt (maps prepared by)|first2=David K.|title=The rise and fall of the Communist Party of Burma (CPB)|date=1990|publisher=Southeast Asia Program, Cornell University|location=Ithaca, N.Y.|isbn=0877271232|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tMBtwdQ9ZUsC|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> \u2013 present<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=